<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Injuries, Inconsistency Cost Tribe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CLEVELAND (AP) -- Once again, the only goal was to win the World  
Series. And for the fifth straight year, the Cleveland Indians came 
up a bit short. 
</P>
<P>
	They're running out of excuses. And now, they're running out of  
time. 
</P>
<P>
	Cleveland's offseason arrived prematurely late Monday night when  
too many injuries, too little pitching and too much Pedro Martinez 
and the Boston Red Sox caught up to the Indians. 
</P>
<P>
	It wasn't supposed to end this way for the first team since 1950  
to score 1,000 runs in a season, and one with an All-Star at every 
position. 
</P>
<P>
	As he packed away his catching gear for the winter on Tuesday at  
Jacobs Field, Sandy Alomar summed up the frustrations of a team and 
a town desperate to win it all. 
</P>
<P>
	``We had one goal in mind this year, to get to the World Series  
and win,'' he said. ``We've been saying that every year, and it 
seems like the same story every year. It's disappointing. 
</P>
<P>
	``Unfortunately, somebody played better than we did. Somebody  
always seems to play better than we do. We're always short of 
something. I guess people here are getting tired of it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Wait 'til next century is now the battle cry for some Indians  
fans. 
</P>
<P>
	For others, it's ``Fire Hargrove!''  
</P>
<P>
	Cleveland enters an offseason of uncertainty as owner Dick  
Jacobs is expected to sell the five-time AL Central champions. 
</P>
<P>
	Will new ownership clean house? Will general manager John Hart  
be back? What about manager Mike Hargrove, whose pitching decisions 
will be second-guessed all winter? Can the Indians finally find 
some pitching help? 
</P>
<P>
	Outfielder David Justice thinks next year's Indians could be  
drastically different. 
</P>
<P>
	``A lot of guys aren't going to be back,'' he said. ``We already  
got that feeling. It's just the way things have gone this year. 
Mike Jackson and Doc (Gooden), I feel like they're not going to be 
back. Mike Jackson has always wanted to stay here, but I guess they 
don't want him.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Jackson, who had 39 saves this season, is the biggest name among  
the free agents the Indians could lose this winter. 
</P>
<P>
	``I would love to stay here,'' he said. ``But it's not my  
decision. They haven't really told me anything yet. We've left the 
door open to talk. My intention is to come back.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Justice, too, said he wants to stay in Cleveland but expects to  
hear his name churned through the the rumor mill. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's always up in the air,'' he said. ``I'm at that trade-bait  
age. ... I love playing here. But don't ever forget, it's a 
business. You have to strengthen your team every year, and it's 
obvious what we need to strengthen.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Cleveland has all its stars signed for next year, and holds an  
option on outfielder Manny Ramirez. The Indians may try to sign 
Ramirez to a long-term deal, but after he hit 44 homers and drove 
in 165 runs this year, there's no telling how much that could cost 
a new owner. 
</P>
<P>
	Boston's improbable comeback from an 0-2 deficit to win the AL  
division series in five games over the Indians maybe wasn't as 
stunning as Cleveland winning the first two. 
</P>
<P>
	There were signs all season that the Indians might not play deep  
into October. Despite winning the Central by 21 1/2 games, Cleveland 
went just 10-22 against Boston, New York and Texas, the league's 
other playoff teams. 
</P>
<P>
	And then there was the disabled list.  
</P>
<P>
	Cleveland, perhaps more than any other team, was ravaged by  
injuries to key players. The team used its disabled list 22 times, 
lost 924 player days due to injury and was only able to field its 
opening day lineup four times -- the last on April 22. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's tough when guys get hurt all during the season,'' said  
reliever Steve Karsay, who went on the DL twice and could only be 
used sparingly in the postseason because of injury. ``You always 
wondered if we were ever going to get our guys back at the same 
time. We had to mix and match guys, but I think it was too much of 
a load at the end of the season.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sure enough, it was an injury to starter Dave Burba in Game 3  
that swung the series against the Red Sox. And in Game 5, Kenny 
Lofton dislocated his left shoulder with a head-first slide into 
the bag at first, fittingly capping a season of strains and 
sprains. 
</P>
<P>
	``When Kenny got hurt, it was like the final straw,'' said  
Roberto Alomar, who put up MVP-type numbers in his first season in 
Cleveland. 
</P>
<P>
	However, there was a bright side to the injuries as the Indians  
got contributions from youngsters Richie Sexson, Einar Diaz, Jacob 
Cruz, Dave Roberts, Alex Ramirez and Sean DePaula. 
</P>
<P>
	Burba's injury exposed the Indians' biggest flaw -- pitching  
depth. 
</P>
<P>
	Hart's decision not to go after a frontline No. 1 starter at the  
trading deadline now looks like the wrong one. But it's easy to 
second guess and the Indians did find out this year that Bartolo 
Colon isn't far from being an ace. 
</P>
<P>
	The 24-year-old right-hander went 18-5, going 11-2 in the second  
half. But he buckled under the pressure of having to pitch on three 
days' rest in Game 4 of the division series. 
</P>
<P>
	As Colon matures, the Indians are wondering what to do with  
Jaret Wright, a postseason hero as a rookie in '97 who was just 
8-10 in the regular season and couldn't throw the ball over the 
plate in the playoffs. 
</P>
<P>
	Whoever buys the Indians is assured of getting a contender. But  
contending isn't good enough for Cleveland or the Indians anymore. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have to go home and think about what will make us better  
next year,'' Jim Thome said. ``And then come back and try again.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
