<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Raytheon Cuts Earnings Projections </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LEXINGTON, Mass. (AP) -- Defense giant Raytheon Co. is slashing  
its earnings projections for 1999 and 2000, blaming 
lower-than-expected revenue. The contractor said today it also 
plans to take a $638 million pretax charge for restructuring and 
project problems. 
</P>
<P>
	The Lexington company estimates its 1999 earnings per share will  
be between $1.40 and $1.50 per share, including the charges, or 
$2.70 to $2.80 per share excluding charges -- well below the Wall 
Street expectations of $3.56 per share. 
</P>
<P>
	For the year 2000, the company estimates earnings per share will  
be in the range of $2.10 to $2.25, compared to estimates of $3.91 
per share. 
</P>
<P>
	Shares of Raytheon had not traded today on the New York Stock  
Exchange. On Monday, Class B shares fell 50 cents to $43. 
</P>
<P>
	Describing himself as ``frustrated'' and the news as  
``disappointing,'' Raytheon chairman and CEO Daniel Burnham said in 
a statement that the company lowered its estimates due to increased 
competition and because it took longer for buyers to decide to buy 
material. 
</P>
<P>
	``Military actions in Kosovo diverted attention,'' said  
spokeswoman Toni Simonetti. A shortage of software engineers also 
led to lower revenue projections by $600 million less than 
originally expected, or $200 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	Competition is lowering profit margins at Raytheon Systems  
Company, its defense and electronics unit, from 15 percent to 12 
percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Raytheon also predicts annual revenue growth for 1999 and 2000  
will be 3 percent, at least half of its earlier projections of 6 
percent to 8 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The Wall Street Journal reported today that Raytheon is behind  
schedule or over budget on at least a dozen fixed-price Pentagon 
orders, including orders for Tomahawk cruise missiles and 
reconnaissance aircraft. 
</P>
<P>
	Raytheon is responsible for any differences above the preset  
contract amounts unless the Pentagon agrees to amend the contracts. 
</P>
<P>
	Raytheon said, however, that only eight projects are over budget  
or behind schedule, though that is resulting in $320 million in 
charges. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a small number, but the dollar amount is large,'' said  
Simonetti. ``It's not (due) to pervasive problems.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Restructuring charges account for another $274 million and $74  
million in special charges will be taken, primarily to write down 
to fair market value company assets such as the company's wireless 
networking inventory and its investment in troubled satellite 
mobile phone company Iridium. 
</P>
<P>
	Raytheon disclosed last month it was having difficulties in its  
defense electronics and construction units that would result in a 
third-quarter pretax charge of between $350 million and $450 
million. 
</P>
<P>
	Some of the company's 108,000 employees worldwide will probably  
be laid off, said Simonetti. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't anticipate another significant round of layoffs,'' she  
said. ``I think companywide there may be a couple thousand.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Simonetti said most of reductions would be in staff functions  
such as finance, public relations, human resources and finance. 



</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
