<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Northwest Denies Sun Country Access </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	EAGAN, Minn. (AP) -- Northwest Airlines has decided to stop  
letting Sun Country Airlines use its emergency training facilities, 
forcing the smaller Minnesota-based rival to scramble for 
alternative ways to provide federally mandated training for flight 
attendants and pilots. 
</P>
<P>
	Sun Country had paid Northwest $250,000 a year during the past  
five years for the training, which teaches pilots and flight 
attendants how to exit aircraft in emergency situations. 
</P>
<P>
	The training for more than 600 Sun Country employees requires  
special equipment, which Sun Country doesn't own and would cost 
$200,000, said Doug Matalucci, a Sun Country vice president. That 
total doesn't include additional funds that would be needed to pay 
for trainers, classroom space and other items, the airline said. 
</P>
<P>
	Northwest also recently stopped sharing parts with Sun Country,  
breaking a long-held tradition among airlines and a 16-year pact 
with Sun Country, which is based in Mendota Heights, Minn. 
</P>
<P>
	The two airlines are competing for passengers flying in and out  
of Minneapolis and St. Paul. Northwest, which controls about 80 
percent of the Twin Cities air market, makes no apologies for its 
decision. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have to make these decisions based on what's best for our  
employees, our stockholders and our customers,'' said spokeswoman 
Marta Laughlin. ``We have to be the best competitor that we can, 
and if our decisions don't happen to please one particular airline 
-- one that happens to be trying to steal our customers -- then so be 
it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Among the other airlines that contract for emergency training  
through Northwest are Ryan Air and Champion Air, which is partly 
owned by Northwest. 
</P>
<P>
	Northwest's moves come as Congress prepares to open hearings  
next week on proposed Department of Transportation airline 
competition guidelines. 
</P>
<P>
	Sun Country officials expect to testify at the hearings,  
describing the airline's experiences in the Twin Cities since 
switching from chartered service to scheduled flights last June. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
