<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Judge OKs Gingrich Requests in Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MARIETTA, Ga. (AP) -- A judge granted former House Speaker Newt  
Gingrich permission Tuesday to question his sister-in-law and one 
of his wife's friends in the couple's divorce case. 
</P>
<P>
	Gingrich asked to question Marilyn Heddleston of Leetonia, Ohio,  
his wife Marianne's sister. The request was filed a day after 
Gingrich sought permission to depose Carol Villio, another Ohio 
woman Mrs. Gingrich has known for years. 
</P>
<P>
	Superior Court Judge Dorothy Robinson signed orders Tuesday  
authorizing both depositions. 
</P>
<P>
	Gingrich's attorney, Randy Evans, has said he intends to prove  
that his wife shares the blame for the breakup of their marriage. 
Gingrich filed for divorce July 29, about seven months after 
resigning from Congress. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Gingrich's attorney, John Mayoue, said she welcomes all  
``reasonable steps'' to investigate the marriage's social and 
financial circumstances. 
</P>
<P>
	The divorce case has grown increasing acrimonious in recent  
weeks as lawyers for Gingrich and his wife traded court filings and 
public barbs. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
