<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Arkansas Halts Inmate Work Program </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) -- Prisoners who held jobs at Arkansas'  
state police headquarters and the Governor's Mansion have been 
returned to prison after the escape of a convicted killer in the 
program. 
</P>
<P>
	The inmates, who worked under minimum security, were led  
handcuffed into vans early Monday evening after state police 
director Tom Mars ended a 30-year arrangement in which 50 inmates 
worked in an honor system-based jobs program. 
</P>
<P>
	Mark Stone, 39, remained at large after escaping Friday night  
from barracks at the state police headquarters where he and 35 
other inmates had lived. 
</P>
<P>
	Mars, who assumed command last winter, said he had long been  
uncomfortable with prisoners working at his headquarters. Some had 
access to places off-limits to troopers; others worked on police 
vehicles or maintained the state police radio system. 
</P>
<P>
	The inmates saved the department $500,000 a year, and Mars said  
he could not afford to give up the free work -- until Stone escaped. 
</P>
<P>
	``I wanted to do this months ago,'' said Mars, who previously  
moved to restrict inmate access to guns stored in the troopers' 
cars. 
</P>
<P>
	Stone, convicted in the 1984 beating death of his girlfriend,  
escaped by walking out of a dayroom off the barracks. He was being 
held there while officers investigated reports of inmate beer 
drinking. Mars said previously that Stone should not have been left 
unattended. 
</P>
<P>
	Stone's escape was the third by an Arkansas inmate in the  
program since 1983, police Maj. Jim Tyler said. That year, one 
stole a state police car and led officers on a chase into Oklahoma. 
And in 1992, an inmate left the barracks to settle an argument with 
his girlfriend. He returned a day later. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
