<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Start of Clinton As Lame Duck? </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The battle over the nuclear test ban treaty  
turned into a political minefield of brinksmanship and 
miscalculation, ending with President Clinton in full retreat and 
trying to stave off a humiliating defeat. 
</P>
<P>
	Lacking enough support to win after demanding that Republicans  
hold a vote, Clinton was forced into an eleventh-hour about-face, 
pleading with the Senate to delay the treaty rather than defeat it. 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts began talking about a lame-duck president.  
</P>
<P>
	Republicans, seething from failed battles on everything from tax  
cuts to Clinton's impeachment, refused to let the president off the 
hook easily. They toyed with him over whether to defeat the treaty 
outright or postpone it until after he leaves office in 2001. 
</P>
<P>
	All that aside, some Republicans -- led John Warner of Virginia --  
felt that a vote now to reject the treaty would be a mistake for 
both sides and contrary to America's national interests. 
</P>
<P>
	It was an embarrassing outcome for an agreement that Clinton  
once had hailed as ``the longest sought, hardest fought prize in 
arms control history,'' with roots in the Eisenhower 
administration. 
</P>
<P>
	Arms control experts faulted the president for failing to wage  
an effective campaign for the treaty after signing it with great 
fanfare at the U.N. General Assembly in 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	``The administration got caught flat-footed,'' said Michael  
Mandelbaum of the Council on Foreign Relations. ``They thought they 
were going to be in a position to beat (Senate Majority Leader 
Trent) Lott over the head with this because he would never bring it 
up. But suddenly he turned around and decided to bring it up, which 
put them in an awkward position.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``If this is as important as the administration says it is, you  
wonder why is this the first time we've heard about it,'' said 
Mandelbaum, a onetime foreign policy adviser to Clinton. ``For most 
people ... it's seen as a partisan issue and not a national 
security issue.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton has mentioned the treaty from time to time but did not  
make a sustained effort until Republicans suddenly accepted his 
challenge to hold a vote. They scheduled it in less than two weeks, 
even before the Foreign Relations Committee had devoted a single 
hearing to it. 
</P>
<P>
	Essentially, it became ``this game of political chicken. And  
this could be the moment that signals the start of the lame-duck 
period of Clinton's presidency,'' said John Parachini, a national 
security expert at the Monterey Institute of International Studies. 
``It's a mistake that's unfortunate not only for foreign and 
defense policy reasons. It's also unfortunate for the power of this 
presidency.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The administration appeared lulled by signs that pointed to  
victory. Clinton collected testimonials for the treaty from 
military leaders, Nobel laureates and the directors of the nation's 
nuclear labs. A poll said that 82 percent of Americans supported a 
nuclear test ban. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a president that when he gets up in the morning, he  
focuses on domestic issues,'' Parachini said. ``And what 
principally drives him is sort of the political edge. He has 
focused more and more on foreign issues, and when he really puts 
his shoulder to the stone he's proven to be very effective. But he 
didn't in this case.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Some Democrats thought it was a smart political strategy to make  
Republicans walk the plank on the treaty and vote, regardless of 
the outcome, because it might be useful in next year's elections. 
Of course, that assumes Americans are paying attention to foreign 
affairs, which increasingly is unlikely after the Cold War except 
on issues of war and peace. 
</P>
<P>
	While Clinton belatedly tried to mobilize support, opponents  
drew on the political muscle of chairmen of three powerful Senate 
committees: Armed Services, Foreign Affairs and intelligence. 
</P>
<P>
	The critics also had their own allies: six former secretaries of  
defense, four former national security advisers and two former CIA 
directors from the Clinton administration, John Deutch and Jim 
Woolsey. George W. Bush, the front-runner for the Republican 
presidential nomination, also opposed the treaty. 
</P>
<P>
	While asking that the treaty be withdrawn, Clinton refused to  
meet an additional Republican demand -- that he agree not to try to 
resurrect the treaty for a vote during the remainder of his 
presidency. 
</P>
<P>
	But that seems certain, whether or not Clinton acknowledges it,  
since Republicans will rule the Senate through the 2000 elections. 
That gives them the power to control the floor votes until Clinton 
leaves Washington. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	EDITOR'S NOTE: Terence Hunt has covered the Clinton, Bush and  
Reagan presidencies. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
