<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Posh Car Brand Jensen Returning </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- Actor Tony Curtis drove one. So did 1960s pop star  
Cliff Richard. 
</P>
<P>
	Now Jensen, one of the best-known brands in luxury British  
motoring, is set for a rebirth 23 years after Jensen Motors Ltd. 
stopped producing cars because of labor-management strife. 
</P>
<P>
	But unlike its sleek forbear -- the four-seat Interceptor -- the  
newest Jensen will be a sporty two-seater with an aluminum body 
wrapped around a Ford Cobra V-8 engine. 
</P>
<P>
	And by pricing their new S-V8 convertible at about $65,400, the  
owners of the revived Jensen Motors Ltd. hope to attract young 
professionals who need not earn a Hollywood-league salary to afford 
it. 
</P>
<P>
	Jensen executives said Tuesday that they have secured $16.5  
million from investors in order to begin production next June. They 
aim to manufacture 200 cars next year and triple their output the 
following year from a plant at a site still to be selected near 
Liverpool in north England. 
</P>
<P>
	The company foresees its S-V8 model competing against such  
worthy rivals as the Porsche Boxster. 
</P>
<P>
	``We believe we're opening up a niche in the market,'' said  
company spokesman Norman Childs. ``It looks a timeless British 
classic, but it's brand new.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The new Jensen draws heavily on the United States for  
inspiration. 
</P>
<P>
	The engine, a U.S. import, is the same high-performance unit  
that powers the Ford Mustang Cobra. The Creative Group, a 
consulting firm that bought the Jensen name in 1997, claims credit 
for helping design the Plymouth Prowler, a retro-look roadster. 
</P>
<P>
	But Jensen's small size and limited output mean that S-V8s  
aren't likely to constitute a British invasion of American streets 
anytime soon. 
</P>
<P>
	The first 100 cars are already pre-sold, mostly within Britain,  
where Jensen plans to focus its initial marketing efforts. Later, 
it plans to target continental Europe, Japan and eventually the 
United States, Childs said. 
</P>
<P>
	``The problem for us is that we are a very small manufacturer  
starting from scratch today. We have to build a dealer network,'' 
he said. ``But there's a lot of interest in the United States.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Doug Meyer, president of the Jensen Interceptor Owners Club,  
agrees. 
</P>
<P>
	Meyer restores Interceptors, a hand-built sedan that he fondly  
describes as ``a rich man's road car,'' and sells spare parts for 
them at his business in Snohomish, Wash. Interceptors were last 
built in 1976. They sold for the equivalent price today of 
$100,000-$115,000. 
</P>
<P>
	``Americans want a nice two-seater sports car, and quite  
honestly European manufacturers gave up on them when the American 
government got nasty about emission controls and convertible 
safety,'' Meyer said by phone from his garage. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, Meyer said the S-V8 has nothing in common with the  
vintage Interceptor except for the Jensen name. ``It's nothing but 
an overgrown Mazda Miata with a V-8.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In the interest, perhaps, of bridging differences with clannish  
enthusiasts of the Interceptor, Childs holds out the prospect that 
Jensen might one day build an updated version of that model. 
</P>
<P>
	Meyer estimates that only 2,000 still exist in the United  
States. 
</P>
<P>
	The original Jensen Motors Ltd., founded by two brothers, Alan  
and Richard Jensen, made its name in the 1930s by combining stylish 
bodies with chassis built by Austin, Ford and other manufacturers. 
</P>
<P>
	The brothers introduced their own range of cars beginning with  
the White Lady tourer. Jensen began making the Interceptor in 1966 
and took over the defunct Austin-Healey brand of sports cars, 
renaming it Jensen-Healey. 
</P>
<P>
	After the Jensen brothers retired, a San Francisco-based car  
dealer, Kjell Qvale, became the company's largest shareholder. But 
Qvale's relations with Jensen's largely British work force soured, 
and in 1976, he closed the company. 
</P>
<P>
	Jensen's new owners include 20 private investors, Britain's  
Department of Trade and Industry and the Liverpool City Council. 
However, the reborn company's prospects hinge on more than a 
distinguished pedigree and government support. 
</P>
<P>
	``There certainly are no lack of attempts to revive former brand  
names,'' said John Lawson, European auto analyst with U.S. 
investment bank Salomon Smith Barney. 
</P>
<P>
	``Jensen is one of the more lustrous, but it clearly doesn't  
guarantee success.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
