<DOCNO> APW19991012.0026 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-12 17:00:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Golfer Leonard Still Has Goals  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LAS VEGAS (AP) -- Justin Leonard still has some goals for the  
year, even if they aren't as dramatic as the 45-putt that clinched 
the Ryder Cup. 
</P>
<P>
	That's one reason he's in this gambling town this week to play  
in the five-day Las Vegas Invitational that begins Wednesday on 
three courses. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm trying to cap the year off,'' Leonard said. ``I look at  
the goals I set at the beginning of the year and I still have some 
to go.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Leonard stood on the edge of the practice green at the TPC  
Summerlin course Tuesday with evidence that one of those goals has 
already been reached. 
</P>
<P>
	That was in the form of a gold Ryder Cup ring with a blue stone  
on his right hand. 
</P>
<P>
	Before Leonard's charge down the stretch at The Country Club in  
Brookline, Mass., this might have been a year to forget. 
</P>
<P>
	He had lost a playoff for the British Open and played poorly in  
a Ryder Cup that it seemed the Americans were destined to lose. 
</P>
<P>
	Then he came from 4-down with seven holes to play to tie Jose  
Maria Olazabal and give the United States the half-point needed to 
cap the biggest Ryder Cup comeback in history. 
</P>
<P>
	``Winning the Ryder Cup made it all worthwhile,'' Leonard said.  
</P>
<P>
	With just a few fans milling about Tuesday for practice rounds,  
it was a far cry from the hysteria that surrounded the final day in 
Brookline. Leonard was able to joke with fellow pros and relax 
without any of the hoopla that surrounded the victory. 
</P>
<P>
	Though the Las Vegas Invitational is a pro-am format that most  
pros don't like, they do like to come here for the nightlife and a 
chance to have some fun while also making some money. 
</P>
<P>
	``I wouldn't say I'm here for a fun week, but it is a bit  
different,'' Leonard said. ``I still want to do well and try to win 
this tournament.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ryder Cup teammate Jim Furyk is the defending champion in the  
tournament, which takes place on the TPC, Desert Inn and Las Vegas 
Country Club courses for three days before shifting to the TPC for 
the weekend play. 
</P>
<P>
	Players are grouped with three amateurs for the first three  
days, and then the field is narrowed for the weekend. 
</P>
<P>
	With user-friendly courses and usually calm wind, scores can go  
very low. Tiger Woods shot 28-under when he won for the first time 
as a pro here in 1996 and Furyk was 25-under last year when he won 
the tournament for a second time. 
</P>
<P>
	Woods is absent this year, as is David Duval.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
