<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia Troops Taunted in E. Timor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DILI, East Timor (AP) -- As their trucks cleared the checkpoint  
at Dili's port, Indonesian soldiers cringed and raised their riot 
shields. A barrage of rocks, bottles and sticks came flying at them 
as hundreds of people waiting outside screamed obscenities. 
</P>
<P>
	``Get out of our country, you bandits, you scum,'' shouted East  
Timorese residents who chased after the fleeing trucks, trying for 
a last shot at the terrified troops. 
</P>
<P>
	Thousands of Indonesian soldiers have withdrawn from East Timor  
since international peacekeepers arrived last month to restore 
order in the shattered territory. A garrison of several thousand is 
dwindling every day as troops depart. 
</P>
<P>
	The daily gantlet at the capital's docks illustrates the scorn  
with which the Indonesians, who brooked no opposition during their 
24-year rule over East Timor, are now treated. Even those getting 
away with it are amazed. 
</P>
<P>
	``They could do whatever they wanted before. They could kill you  
whenever they wanted,'' said Amando Cruz, one of those waiting for 
the Indonesians to show up at the port. ``Look at them run now.'' 
</P>
<P>
	At least 100,000 East Timorese died in the aftermath of  
Indonesia's 1975 invasion of the former Portuguese colony. 
</P>
<P>
	The Indonesians cracked down on any sign of defiance, and as  
late as 1992 soldiers massacred about 200 unarmed residents at 
Dili's Santa Cruz cemetery for the funeral of a pro-independence 
activist. 
</P>
<P>
	When East Timor chose independence in an Aug. 30 referendum, the  
Indonesian army and its anti-independence militia proxies responded 
by killing, burning, and looting their way though the province. 
Dili and its main port were left in ruins. 
</P>
<P>
	But the situation has changed dramatically since the  
Australian-led multinational force arrived three weeks ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Peacekeepers cleaned away ashes and rubble and reopened the main  
Portuguese-built market in Dili, which until the rampage had been 
the commercial heart of the city. 
</P>
<P>
	Only of a few vendors sold small amounts of fruit, vegetables  
and fish on Tuesday, but peacekeepers said it was the first step in 
East Timor's recovery. 
</P>
<P>
	There has been friction over the border separating East Timor  
and Indonesian-controlled West Timor, where hundreds of 
anti-independence militiamen are massed -- some of whom say they are 
preparing to launch guerrilla war against the U.N.-mandated forces. 
</P>
<P>
	Foreign Minister Ali Alatas said Tuesday he would protest to the  
United Nations about a firefight between Australian and Indonesian 
forces over the weekend. Indonesia says one of its policemen was 
killed in West Timor, but Australia denies that it violated the 
border. 
</P>
<P>
	Indonesia has reinforced its position on the western side of the  
border. Military chief Gen. Wiranto said Tuesday said his forces 
and the peacekeepers should jointly patrol the area to prevent 
further clashes. 
</P>
<P>
	About 16,000 Indonesian troops have now withdrawn from East  
Timor, leaving behind two battalions that are to depart by next 
month. The 1,400 troops are hunkered down inside government 
buildings, barricaded behind barbed wire, sandbags and machine-gun 
emplacements. 
</P>
<P>
	The remaining troops in Dili are busy loading furniture,  
weapons, and tires onto trucks that are driven each morning to 
waiting cargo ships in the harbor. 
</P>
<P>
	Australian soldiers stand guard around the Indonesian troops as  
they transfer the loads to the ships. 
</P>
<P>
	But along the main seafront avenue, citizens gather in a daily  
ritual with stones and bottles in their hands, eagerly awaiting the 
trucks to emerge for their return trip. 
</P>
<P>
	Col. Mark Kelly, chief of staff of the peacekeeping force, said  
Tuesday the local Indonesian commander had asked for help, and 
peacekeepers would now also escort Indonesian convoys to the port. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
