<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Weyerhaeuser Earnings Up 115 Pct. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FEDERAL WAY, Wash. (AP) -- Forest products maker Weyerhaeuser Co.  
said its third-quarter earnings more than doubled thanks to strong 
U.S. demand and the economic recovery in Japan. The company also 
said it planned a reorganization aimed at cutting costs and that 
would affect an undetermined number of employees. 
</P>
<P>
	The forest products company reported today it had net earnings  
of $237 million, or $1.18 per common share, compared to $110 
million, or 56 cents per common share, for the same three-month 
period of 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	Weyerhaeuser's results easily surpassed analysts' expectations  
of 95 cents a share, according to First Call/Thomson Financial. 
Wall Street was pleased with the results, and bid Weyerhaeuser's 
stock up $1.88 a share to $61.31 in midday New York Stock Exchange 
trading. 
</P>
<P>
	Net sales for the quarter were $3.12 billion, up nearly 15  
percent from $2.74 billion last year. 
</P>
<P>
	Weyerhaeuser also said it planned what it called a streamlining  
of internal services expected to result in $150 million to $200 
million in annual savings. The company did not say whether jobs 
would be cut or whether there would be layoffs, but it did say the 
process, expected to take up to three years to complete, would 
affect an as-yet unknown number of employees. 
</P>
<P>
	During the third quarter, Weyerhaeuser's timberlands segment had  
operating earnings of $130 million, up 25 percent from $104 million 
a year ago. The company credited the rise to stable export log 
volumes, reflecting recovery in the Japanese housing market. 
</P>
<P>
	The wood products segment had operating earnings of $202  
million, up 132 percent from $87 million last year, due mainly to 
strong demand in the U.S. market. 
</P>
<P>
	The pulp, paper and packaging unit posted operating earnings of  
$105 million, up 57 percent from last year's $67 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Real estate and related assets had earnings of $56 million, up  
47 percent from the $38 million of third-quarter 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	For the first nine months of the year, Weyerhaeuser reported net  
earnings, before nonrecurring charges, of $503 million, or $2.51 
per common share, compared with $264 million, or $1.33 per common 
share, last year. 
</P>
<P>
	Including the nonrecurring charges, primarily associated with  
the sale of the company's composite products business, Weyerhaeuser 
reported net earnings of $353 million, or $1.76 per common share. 
</P>
<P>
	Net sales during the first nine months were $8.8 billion,  
compared to $8 billion during the same period of 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	The company is in the process of acquiring Canadian  
wood-products company MacMillan Bloedel. The deal is expected to 
close by Nov. 1. 




  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
