<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gannett Earnings Jump 19 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Stronger newspaper revenues boosted Gannett Co.'s third-quarter  
earnings by nearly 20 percent, beating analysts' estimates. E.W. 
Scripps Co. recorded flat third-quarter earnings yesterday because 
of several expenses related to its television operations. 

</P>
<P>
                            *Gannett Co.    	
</P>
<P>
	Gannett recorded a 19 percent gain in profits for the third  
quarter as revenues rose from its newspapers, which include USA 
Today. 
</P>
<P>
	Gannett earned $207.5 million, or 74 cents per share, in the  
quarter ended Sept. 26, up from 62 cents per share, or $176.5 
million, in the same period last year. 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts surveyed by First Call Corp. had projected earnings of  
71 cents per share. 
</P>
<P>
	Revenues increased 11 percent to $1.36 billion, from $1.23  
billion in the same quarter in 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	Strong sales of classified and national advertising, along with  
a decline in the cost of newsprint, powered the company's newspaper 
earnings. Operating income from newspapers grew 23 percent in the 
third quarter to $304.7 million. 
</P>
<P>
	At USA Today, the company's flagship newspaper, paid advertising  
pages jumped 16 percent to 1,443 compared to 1,242 in the third 
quarter of 1998, while ad revenues grew 21 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Cable revenues increased 11 percent in the third quarter to  
$64.7 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Gannett, which is based in Arlington, Va., publishes 74 daily  
newspapers and operates 21 television stations and cable TV systems 
in three states. In addition, the company owns a variety of 
non-daily publications, including the USA Weekend newspaper insert. 
</P>
<P>
	For the first nine months of the year, Gannett's net earnings  
fell 11 percent to $663 million, or $2.35 per share, from $742 
million, or $2.59 per share, in the same period a year ago. 
Revenues for the period rose 6 percent to $3.95 billion from $3.73 
billion. 
</P>
<P>
	Not counting one-time gains this year and last from such things  
as the disposal of properties, operating earnings for the first 
nine months rose nearly 13 percent to $630.6 million, or $2.26 a 
share, from $558.6 million, or $1.96 a share, a year earlier. 
</P>
<P>
	Shares of Gannett rose 68 3/4 cents to $72.68 3/4 on the New York  
Stock Exchange Monday. 

</P>
<P>
                          *E.W. Scripps Co.    	
</P>
<P>
	Scripps, a newspaper and television company based in Cincinnati,  
had flat earnings in the third quarter because of several one-time 
expenses related to its TV business. 
</P>
<P>
	Scripps earned $24.9 million in the three months ended Sept. 30,  
down slightly from $26.1 million in the same period a year ago. 
Per-share earnings were unchanged at 32 cents. 
</P>
<P>
	Revenues rose 8 percent to $369.9 million from $343.4 million.  
</P>
<P>
	Scripps earmarked $2.5 million to compensate advertisers for  
possibly not having delivered the expected audiences for past 
broadcasts of the company's Home &AMP; Garden Television cable network. 
</P>
<P>
	Expenses also included $800,000 for relocating the Food  
Network's operations within New York City, $1.2 million in 
severance costs for television station employees, and $1 million 
for costs of the Scripps Ventures fund, including compensating its 
managers. 
</P>
<P>
	Scripps' revenues from newspaper advertising remained strong,  
but television stations were hurt by weak advertising revenues. 
</P>
<P>
	Scripps operates 19 daily newspapers; nine network-affiliated  
television stations; three cable television networks, Home &AMP; Garden 
Television, Food Network and Do it Yourself, and a TV programmer, 
Scripps Productions. 
</P>
<P>
	Other businesses include United Media, which syndicates and  
licenses news features and comics; Scripps Howard News Service and 
independent Yellow Pages directories. 
</P>
<P>
	For the first nine months of the year, earnings totaled $101.1  
million, or $1.28 per share, compared with last year's $87.6 
million and $1.08. Revenues were $1.13 billion, up from $1.06 
billion. 
</P>
<P>
	Shares of Scripps fell $1.50 to $49.56 1/4 in trading on the New  
York Stock Exchange. 




  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
