<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Man Guilty of Setting Mass. Fire </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CAMBRIDGE, Mass. (AP) -- A man was sentenced to 2 1/2 years in jail  
Tuesday for burning down a historic building that housed a 
newspaper and a dozen other businesses. 
</P>
<P>
	George Aldrich pleaded guilty to charges of burning a building  
and breaking and entering a building at night. 
</P>
<P>
	Aldrich, a former resident of the J.W. Parementer Building in  
Waltham, admitted to setting the Feb. 19 blaze that consumed the 
three-story brick building that housed The News Tribune, a 
7,500-circulation community newspaper serving readers in Newton and 
Waltham. 
</P>
<P>
	Also destroyed were a military recruiting office, offices of the  
Massachusetts Parent-Teacher Association Inc., a violin repair shop 
and several other businesses. 
</P>
<P>
	Nobody was injured, but damage to the 19th century building and  
its occupants was estimated at between $4 million and $6 million. 
</P>
<P>
	About a week before the fire was set, Aldrich was evicted from  
the basement apartment where he and another person were living 
illegally. The building was not zoned for residential use. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
