<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-12 18:40:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Braves Lead Mets After 3 in NLCS </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- Bret Boone had a run-scoring single in the first  
and the Atlanta Braves grabbed a 1-0 lead over the New York Mets 
after three innings in Game 1 of the NL Championship Series on 
Tuesday night. 
</P>
<P>
	The Mets, making their first appearance in the NLCS since 1988,  
squandered a prime scoring chance by failing to convert a squeeze 
bunt in the third. 
</P>
<P>
	The Braves, who have played in eight straight championship  
series, jumped on New York starter Masato Yoshii right away. Gerald 
Williams hit the first pitch for a single, stole second and scored 
when Boone lined a single to center. 
</P>
<P>
	Chipper Jones followed with a walk, prompting Orel Hershiser to  
begin throwing in the Mets bullpen. But Yoshii settled down to 
retire the next three hitters, and he also escaped in the second 
after Eddie Perez led off with a double. 
</P>
<P>
	Nineteen-game winner Greg Maddux retired the first six New York  
hitters before Roger Cedeno led off the third with a double. Cedeno 
moved to third on Williams' errant throw back to the infield, but 
the Mets couldn't convert. 
</P>
<P>
	After Rey Ordonez was retired on a dribbler in front of the  
plate, the Mets tried to squeeze with Yoshii on a 2-0 count. He 
failed to make contact on a pitch low and away and Cedeno was 
tagged out easily. 
</P>
<P>
	The best-of-7 series between division rivals -- Atlanta finished  
seven games ahead of the Mets in the NL East, but New York claimed 
the wild card -- took on somewhat of a nasty tone as the teams 
exchanged pre-game barbs. 
</P>
<P>
	New York manager Bobby Valentine claimed the Braves had no  
respect for his team, especially after beating New York five of six 
times in the final two weeks of the regular season. 
</P>
<P>
	The Mets, who lost nine of 12 to the Braves overall, recovered  
to earn a tie with Cincinnati for the wild card and beat the Reds 
5-0 in a playoff. New York then upset Arizona in the opening round 
of the postseason to advance to the NLCS for the first time since 
1988. 
</P>
<P>
	The Braves defeated Houston in the other division series.  
</P>
<P>
	After Valentine's comments, Atlanta outfielder Brian Jordan  
admitted that he disliked New York and teammate John Rocker claimed 
it was the Mets who didn't respect the Braves. 
</P>
<P>
	Mets slugger Mike Piazza returned to the lineup after missing  
the final two games of the division series because of an injured 
thumb. He grounded out leading off the second. 
</P>
<P>
	The Braves made a lineup change, inserting opening-round hero  
Walt Weiss at shortstop in place of Jose Hernandez. 
</P>
<P>
	Batting practice for the Mets was cut short by pregame showers,  
forcing the ground crew to put the tarp back on the field. But the 
rain stopped and the game started only four minutes behind 
schedule. 
</P>
<P>
	Andres Galarraga, who missed the season for the Braves while  
recovering from cancer, threw out the ceremonial first pitch. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
