<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-12 07:10:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Taco Bell Dog's Role Shrinking </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The little dog's days as the central character  
in Taco Bell commercials are dwindling but its feisty Chihuahua is 
staying on in a supporting role. 
</P>
<P>
	The fast-food restaurant chain plans to introduce a new  
advertising tagline later this year and emphasize the food and its 
price, spokeswoman Laurie Gannon said Monday. But she said ``the 
dog is staying in the advertising'' although its role will change. 
</P>
<P>
	``We'll use the dog in a different sense to draw attention to  
the food,'' she said, declining to be more specific. 
</P>
<P>
	The tagline debuting in commercials airing in late December will  
be ``Grande Taste. Loco Price. Only at Taco Bell.'' Taco Bell ads 
have not been using any single theme in recent years, Ms. Gannon 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Taco Bell owns or franchises about 7,000 Mexican-style  
restaurants worldwide from its base in Irvine, Calif. It has 
featured a Chihuahua that appears to talk in more than two dozen 
ads over the past two years. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, Ms. Gannon said it has sold over 20 million  
miniature plush toys of the dog that recite some of the phrases it 
has uttered in ads like ``Yo Quiero Taco Bell,'' which means ``I 
Want Taco Bell.'' The toys sell the restaurants for $3 to $4. 
</P>
<P>
	She said four more versions of the toys uttering phrases heard  
in commercials this year will go on sale in mid-November. 
</P>
<P>
	Taco Bell sales per store grew at a slower pace in the second  
quarter. Sales per store open at least a year were up a slim 1 
percent on the April-June period after rising 4 percent in the 
first quarter and 3 percent for all of 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1997, the year before the Chihuahua debuted nationally in  
advertising, sales per store grew 2 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Gannon said the change in ad plans didn't reflect concerns  
over sales growth, however. ``We are just making a change in 
direction. Food, taste and value are what they want to draw 
attention to,'' she said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991012.0048 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-12 20:40:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> John Hancock Names New CEO </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- John Hancock president David D'Alessandro has been  
named chief executive officer of the financial services company 
starting June 1, the board of directors announced. 
</P>
<P>
	D'Alessandro will replace current CEO and Chairman Steven Brown.  
In a company news release Tuesday, Brown, 62, said he's stepping 
down because he's nearing the mandatory retirement age of 65. 
</P>
<P>
	Brown will stay on as chairman, and also become chairman of John  
Hancock Funds, part of the company's mutual fund operation. During 
Brown's seven-year tenure as CEO, the company's assets under 
management have doubled to $124.4 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	The change in leadership comes as John Hancock Mutual Life  
Insurance Co. moves toward an initial public offering on the New 
York Stock Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	Last month, the Boston-based company's board of directors  
adopted a plan to distribute the company's value to policy holders 
in the form of stock, cash or policy credits as it goes through a 
process known as demutualization. 
</P>
<P>
	The new company will be called John Hancock Financial Services.  
</P>
<P>
	D'Alessandro, 48, is credited with increasing the net income of  
John Hancock's retail business 188 percent between 1991 and 1998 to 
$337.8 million. During the same period, he also increased the sale 
of Hancock's life insurance products by 77 percent while the 
industry averaged 4 percent, the company said. 
</P>
<P>
	John Hancock had 1998 earnings of $448.5 million on sales of  
$6.9 billion. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
