<DOCNO> APW19991012.0049 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-12 07:40:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Stocks Mostly Lower; Dow Down 92.13 / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Prices were mostly lower in early trading on  
Wall Street today as rising bond yields, presenting a more 
attractive alternative to stocks, drew investors away from 
equities. 
</P>
<P>
	In the first hour of trading on Wall Street, the Dow Jones  
industrial average was down 92.13 at 10,556.05. 
</P>
<P>
	Broader stock indicators were mixed. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500  
index was down 9.55 at 1,325.66, and the Nasdaq composite index was 
down 0.16 to 2,915.79. The Nasdaq was struggling to build on its 
new record close of 2,915.95, set Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Stocks followed bond prices lower. Bond investors, nagged by  
persisting worries about interest rates, were selling ahead of this 
week's government reports on wholesale prices and industrial 
production. The reports are expected to bring the latest signs of 
whether inflation is escalating in the U.S. economy, and whether 
the Federal Reserve will raise interest rates for a third time this 
year. 
</P>
<P>
	The drop in bond prices pushed the yield on the 30-year Treasury  
bond up to 6.24 percent today from 6.20 percent late Friday. The 
bond market was closed Monday for the Columbus Day holiday. 
</P>
<P>
	Rising bond yields can present an attractive alternative to  
stocks by offering a fixed, guaranteed return. 
</P>
<P>
	Earnings reports were expected to provide a spark to trading  
today. Several Wall Street brokerages reported strong profits, but 
few were rewarded by sharp gains in their share prices. Merrill 
Lynch rose 1/8 to 67 7/8 after reporting its third-quarter earnings beat 
revised analysts' estimates. 
</P>
<P>
	Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a 2-to-1 margin on the  
New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 102.5 million shares, 
well ahead of Monday's quiet pace. 
</P>
<P>
	The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies fell 0.65 to 429.54.  
</P>
<P>
	Overseas, Japan's Nikkei stock average rose 0.2 percent. In  
afternoon trading, Germany's DAX index was down 0.4 percent, 
Britain's FT-SE 100 was up 0.1 percent, and France's CAC-40 was 
down 0.8 percent. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
