<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AlliedSignal To Lay Off 400 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHOENIX (AP) -- AlliedSignal Aerospace will lay off about 400  
workers in Phoenix by the end of the month because of declining 
demand for commercial aircraft. 
</P>
<P>
	Workers in Phoenix and Tempe, Ariz., had been told last month  
that layoffs were coming and that they would know by Oct. 31 
whether their jobs were being eliminated, spokesman Bill Reavis 
said Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Reavis noted that Seattle-based Boeing plans to build 125 fewer  
aircraft next year than this year. Another factor, he said, is the 
need to streamline the Engines and Systems division. 
</P>
<P>
	Steve Loranger, president of the two divisions, told employees  
by memo the layoffs were necessary ``to lower our cost structure 
and prepare for the future.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Reavis said they had nothing to do with AlliedSignal's merger  
with Honeywell Inc., which is expected to be completed this fall. 
</P>
<P>
	The Aerospace section of AlliedSignal Inc. employs nearly 9,000  
people in the Phoenix area and about 1,000 in Tucson. The unit cut 
about 150 jobs about five months ago. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
