<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ex Deputy Solicitor General Dies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ESSEX, England (AP) -- Louis F. Claiborne, who as a deputy  
solicitor general argued more than 60 cases before the U.S. Supreme 
Court on behalf of the federal government, died at his home in 
Wivenhoe on Oct. 6. He was 72. 
</P>
<P>
	Claiborne served in the solicitor general's office in Washington  
from 1962 to 1970 before moving to England to teach at the 
University of Sussex. He returned to the office in 1978, where he 
remained until 1985, when he left to join the San Francisco law 
firm of Washburn, Briscoe &AMP; McCarthy. 
</P>
<P>
	Coincidentally, the Supreme Court was hearing arguments today on  
an environmental issue on which Claiborne wrote his last brief. 
Claiborne argued that private citizens should not be allowed to sue 
under the Clean Water Act because any penalties would go to the 
government, not to the plaintiff. 
</P>
<P>
	Among the survivors are a son and daughter, Andrew and Michele,  
both of Wivenhoe; a brother, Omer, of Santa Fe, N.M.; and a sister, 
designer Liz Claiborne, of New York. 



</P>
</TEXT>
