<P>
	Raytheon Cuts Earnings Projections  
</P>
<P>
	LEXINGTON, Mass. (AP) -- Defense giant Raytheon Co. is slashing  
its earnings projections for 1999 and 2000, blaming 
lower-than-expected revenue. The contractor said today it also 
plans to take a $638 million pretax charge for restructuring and 
project problems. The Lexington company estimates its 1999 earnings 
per share will be between $1.40 and $1.50 per share, including the 
charges, or $2.70 to $2.80 per share excluding charges -- well below 
the Wall Street expectations of $3.56 per share. For the year 2000, 
the company estimates earnings per share will be in the range of 
$2.10 to $2.25, compared to estimates of $3.91 per share. While 
stock market officials maintained a trading halt on Raytheon 
shares, most of its rival contractors tumbled. 

</P>
<P>
	International Paper Posts Profit  
</P>
<P>
	PURCHASE, N.Y. (AP) -- International Paper, the world's largest  
paper and forest products company, reported sharply higher 
third-quarter earnings today thanks to better pricing for its 
products and cost-cutting efforts. Not counting one-time gains and 
losses, International Paper earned $192 million, or 46 cents a 
share, compared to $81 million, or 20 cents per share, in the same 
quarter a year ago. The figures beat analysts' expectations. 
International Paper shares were at 48 11/16, up 3/16. 

</P>
<P>
	Weyerhaeuser Earnings Up 115 Pct.  
</P>
<P>
	FEDERAL WAY, Wash. (AP) -- Forest products maker Weyerhaeuser Co.  
said its third-quarter earnings more than doubled thanks to strong 
U.S. demand and the economic recovery in Japan. Weyerhaeuser 
reported today net earnings of $237 million, or $1.18 per common 
share, compared to $110 million, or 56 cents per common share, for 
the same three-month period of 1998. The results easily surpassed 
analysts' expectations. Net sales for the quarter were $3.12 
billion, up nearly 15 percent from $2.74 billion last year. 
Weyerhaeuser shares were at 60 1/2, up 1 1/16. 

</P>
<P>
	Phelps Dodge Earnings Fall 20 Pct.  
</P>
<P>
	PHOENIX (AP) -- Phelps Dodge Corp. reported its third-quarter  
earnings fell 20.7 percent as a result of the continuing slump in 
copper prices. The big copper and wire producer said it earned 
$16.1 million, or 28 cents per share, down from $20.3 million, or 
35 cents per share, reported for the same period last year. Phelps 
Dodge surpassed analyst expectations of 21 cents per share. The 
results do not reflect a restructuring charge of $700,000, or 1 
cent per share, for the latest quarter, and a 1998 gain of $8.3 
million, or 14 cents per share, from the completion of the sale of 
Accuride Corp. 

</P>
<P>
	MGM Posts First Profit in 3 Years  
</P>
<P>
	SANTA MONICA, Calif. (AP) -- Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer Inc. reported  
its first profitable quarter in almost three years today, earning 
$10.3 million on the strength of recent films, TV programming and 
cost-cutting. The third-quarter results came in well above 
forecasts of Wall Street analysts, who had predicted a loss. 
Earnings for the quarter that ended Sept. 30 were 7 cents a share, 
compared with a $40.3 million, or 61 cents a share, loss for the 
same period in 1998. Analysts surveyed by First Call/Thomson 
Financial had expected MGM to lose 19 cents a share in this year's 
third quarter. MGM shares were unchanged at 22 3/16. 

</P>
<P>
	TD Waterhouse To Join REDIBook ECN  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- TD Waterhouse Group has decided to join the  
REDIBook ECN consortium of discount brokers after a deal to offer 
extended-hours trading through Island ECN fell through. As part of 
today's announcement, TD Waterhouse said it expects to offer 
after-hours trading from 4:30 p.m. to 7 p.m. Eastern time, Monday 
through Friday, beginning in November. TD Waterhouse had originally 
agreed to buy a 12.5 percent interest in Island ECN, a rival 
electronic trading system owned by the discount broker Datek Online 
Holdings. Members of the REDIBook consortium include the investment 
firms Charles Schwab, Fidelity Investments, Donaldson Lufkin &AMP; 
Jenrette, and Spear Leeds &AMP; Kellogg. 

</P>
<P>
	Bank Failures Tapping FDIC Fund  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Federal Deposit Insurance Corp. says bank  
failures this year are expected to generate the insurance fund's 
biggest losses since the regional banking crises of the early 
1990s. Much of the loss was caused by the failure of a big West 
Virginia bank. While the FDIC still has plenty of money to cover 
losses to depositors, the failures bolster recent warnings by 
regulators that some banks may need to tighten their lending 
standards. U.S. Comptroller of the Currency John D. Hawke, told a 
bankers' group yesterday that regulators see some signs of risk 
spreading in the banking industry despite high earnings and hefty 
assets. 

</P>
<P>
	Sonicbox To 'Unchain' PC Listeners  
</P>
<P>
	MOUNTAIN VIEW, Calif. (AP) -- Sonicbox Inc. announced it will  
begin a trial deployment of its Internet radio tuner, which 
transmits Internet-based audio to standard FM radios. The Sonicbox 
Tuner lets consumers with a high-speed Internet connection listen 
to Internet radio programming anywhere in their home, the company 
said today. The device consists of a small base-unit that connects 
to a PC and a hand-held remote tuner. The base-unit relays Internet 
radio broadcasts to an unused frequency of any FM radio receiver 
within 100 feet. The hand-held remote allows listeners to change 
stations, request more information about a song or make an online 
purchase of a CD. 

</P>
<P>
	Merrill Lynch Profit Beats Forecast  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co., the largest brokerage firm  
in the United States, reported strong third-quarter earnings of 
$572 million, easily beating analysts' expectations. The company's 
profits represent earnings of $1.34 a share, a nickel more than the 
$1.29 a share analysts had predicted, according to First Call Corp. 
In the third quarter of 1998, Merrill Lynch reported a loss of $173 
million, or 48 cents a share, due to a $430 million pretax 
write-off of costs related to staff reductions. Merrill Lynch 
shares were unchanged at 22 3/16. 

</P>
<P>
	Posh Car Brand Jensen Returning  
</P>
