<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Pets Targeted By Equipment Maker </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	EDEN PRAIRIE, Minn. (AP) -- If a dog's gotta work, Murado has it  
about as good as it gets. 
</P>
<P>
	Murado, a Rottweiler-shepherd, is chief tester for Sun Pet Toys,  
the Minnesota company that makes pet toys that flash when they hit 
a hard object and dog toys that glow in the dark. 
</P>
<P>
	Murado knows how to put flash in his work. He opens his mouth  
and picks up the company's hard red Fetch &AMP; Glow ball drops it to 
the floor, setting off the pulsing light inside to bring the toy 
alive. 
</P>
<P>
	Murado and his Siberian husky partner, Tasha, are employee pets  
that wander the offices of Sun Products Inc. -- parent of Sun Pet 
Toys and Sun Hockey -- ready to test whatever product comes their 
way. 
</P>
<P>
	``These product testers sneak into the sample room and steal the  
Fetch &AMP; Glows,'' said John Gill, founder and president of the 
private company. ``We have a hard time getting them out of there.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But Gill isn't complaining. Since his company expanded from  
street hockey products into the pet toy business in 1996, annual 
revenues have grown to $4 million and pet products last year made 
up 70 percent of gross sales. 
</P>
<P>
	``Eighteen months ago it was 80 percent hockey. My business has  
gone to the dogs,'' Gill said. 
</P>
<P>
	He was laughing, but it wasn't a joke. Gill's pet toys are sold  
in most major pet store chains throughout the United States, 
including Petco and PetsMart, at Target and on Internet Web sites. 
</P>
<P>
	The company, which has large ads in several major nationwide pet  
magazines, expects sales to grow between 30 percent and 50 percent 
this year. 
</P>
<P>
	Gill, now 52, was selling commercial real estate in 1989 when he  
began to notice kids inline skating around the lakes in 
Minneapolis. The next step, he thought, should be inline hockey. 
</P>
<P>
	Within a year, Gill was in the street hockey business. He  
developed a puck that floated on three balls for playing on 
pavement and sold 6 million worldwide. 
</P>
<P>
	Then in late 1993, Gill introduced the Fire Ball, a street  
hockey ball made of durable plastic surrounding a battery-operated 
light that starts blinking on impact. 
</P>
<P>
	``People were telling me how much fun they were having with the  
street hockey toy with their dogs,'' Gill said. ``I thought, maybe 
I have something here. Let's submit it to PetsMart and see what 
they say.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The giant Phoenix-based chain placed an initial order for 20,000  
of the renamed Fetch &AMP; Glow balls, Gill said. They were introduced 
in PetsMart stores in September 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	In a flash, so to speak, Gill's market expanded from the 4  
million people who play inline street hockey to the 58 million U.S. 
households with pets. 
</P>
<P>
	``There are 60 million dogs and cats in the United States and  
it's growing at 15 percent a year. The pet market is a $28 
billion-a-year business just in the United States,'' Gill said. The 
toys also are sold in Canada, Japan, Europe and South America. 
</P>
<P>
	The Fetch &AMP; Glow, which comes in two sizes, is the best seller  
among the company's pet toys, with nearly 700,000 sold, Gill said. 
</P>
<P>
	Sun Pet Toys also makes a version for cats with a yarn tail  
called Pounce &AMP; Glow, a bone that lights up on impact, durable 
glow-in-the-dark balls for dogs that like softer toys and two tough 
rubber toys that hold treats. 
</P>
<P>
	Prices range from around $5 for the small glow-in-the-dark ball  
to $19 for the flashing bone. 
</P>
<P>
	Because the products grew out of the street hockey business,  
durability was never in question, Gill said. 
</P>
<P>
	``I knew how to build durable hockey pucks so it's obvious I  
knew how to build durable dog toys,'' Gill said. ``When a kid hits 
a hockey puck, it can go 100 miles an hour.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Just to make sure, though, Murado -- a chewer -- stepped in.  
</P>
<P>
	``We found out that he couldn't damage the ball,'' said John  
Kellogg, who lives with the Rottweiler at home and works with him 
at Sun Pet Toys. 
</P>
<P>
	There's just one wrinkle in this success story. The man who  
never played hockey and spends his days dreaming up new ways to 
make dogs happy doesn't own a dog himself. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'd love to have a dog but my wife won't let me have one,''  
Gill said. ``We have a 4 1/2-year-old daughter and my wife says no dog 
until she's at least 8.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
