<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Habibie Choses Wiranto As VP </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) -- President B.J. Habibie chose  
Indonesia's military chief as his vice presidential running mate 
Wednesday, the governing party spokesman said. 
</P>
<P>
	Gen. Wiranto, who like many Indonesians goes by one name, had  
been Habibie's preference for several months and his selection 
could improve the president's chances of being re-elected by the 
700-member People's Consultative Assembly, which contains 38 seats 
controlled by the military. 
</P>
<P>
	Akbar Tandjung, the chief of Habibie's ruling Golkar Party, said  
that its executive board gave the president the power to nominate 
his own candidate for the deputy post. Wiranto had been one of four 
candidates for the vice presidential position, originally nominated 
by Golkar several months ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Habibie's Golkar Party decided to support him for a new  
five-year term despite his falling popularity rating and rising 
student protests, senior party officials said Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The consultative assembly will choose the head of state for the  
world's fourth-most populous nation Oct. 20. Habibie is one of 
three contenders. 
</P>
<P>
	Habibie on Tuesday said an official farewell to his Cabinet at  
Jakarta's Merdeka Palace in a final meeting before next week's 
vote. In recent days, Habibie has repeatedly said that he was both 
confident of maintaining Golkar's support and of winning the 
presidency. 
</P>
<P>
	Even so, Golkar officials have their doubts. Their meeting,  
which began on Tuesday, stretched into the early hours of Wednesday 
morning, when they became deadlocked over what to do if Habibie was 
voted out of office. 
</P>
<P>
	Some wanted to try to form a coalition government with smaller  
parties. Others proposed they should be form a formal opposition. 
</P>
<P>
	Assembly members, including some from the Golkar Party, have  
publicly criticized Habibie for his handling of the East Timor 
crisis as well as a bank corruption scandal involving his inner 
circle. 
</P>
<P>
	There also is anger over Monday's decision by Indonesia's acting  
attorney general to drop a 15-month corruption investigation of 
former President Suharto, Habibie's onetime mentor and friend. 
Habibie has not commented on the decision, but some accuse him of 
trying to protect his former boss, who like many Indonesians uses 
only one name. 
</P>
<P>
	A faction within Golkar has publicly stated doubts about Habibie  
staying in office. 
</P>
<P>
	Even so, many senior Golkar officials, including party chief  
Akbar Tandjung, said Habibie should remain the party's sole 
candidate for now. That could change after the president makes a 
key ``accountability'' speech to the assembly on Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	In the speech, Habibie must detail his achievements and failings  
during the 16 months since he took over from Suharto, who ruled 
Indonesian for 32 years with Golkar as his party. 
</P>
<P>
	The assembly, Indonesia's highest legislative body, has the  
power to reject the content of the speech. If it does, Habibie 
would have little choice but to withdraw his nomination for the 
presidency. 
</P>
<P>
	That is what many student protesters want him to do.  
</P>
<P>
	Hundreds of people took to the streets in Jakarta on Tuesday for  
three separate demonstrations -- two criticizing Habibie and another 
in favor of one of his opponents for the presidency, Megawati 
Sukarnoputri. 
</P>
<P>
	In a march on parliament by about 600 students, at least two  
students and two security guards were injured. 
</P>
<P>
	In the contest for the presidency, Habibie also is expected to  
face Abdurrahman Wahid, the head of Indonesia's largest Muslim 
organization. 
</P>
<P>
	Megawati, whose Indonesian Democratic Party of Struggle defeated  
Golkar in a parliamentary election on June 7, is widely considered 
to be the frontrunner. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
