<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Crude Oil Futures Extend Rally  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Crude oil futures rose 5 percent Tuesday in extending a rally  
from last week's breathtaking price drop, buoyed in part by the 
possibility another tropical storm may be brewing in the Atlantic. 
</P>
<P>
	Prices of other energy products also advanced sharply, led by a  
more than 5 percent hike in heating oil as the cold-weather season 
approaches in the Northern Hemisphere. 
</P>
<P>
	In other markets, coffee futures soared for a second straight  
day on mounting concern over dry weather in Brazilian growing 
regions, and hog futures closed sharply higher. 
</P>
<P>
	Nearing the end of a season in which several storms have  
battered the southeastern United States, investors in energy 
futures had their eyes on a large tropical wave just south of Cuba. 
</P>
<P>
	Prices pushed up on speculation that it could turn into a storm  
and endanger the energy-rich Gulf Coast. Most U.S. crude oil is 
imported between Houston and Lake Charles, La., and many natural 
gas and oil developments are based in the region. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's in the late end of the season, but this has some  
characteristics it could turn into something,'' said Bill O'Grady, 
energy analyst for A.G. Edwards &AMP; Sons Inc. in St. Louis. 
``Hurricanes are a big deal.'' 
</P>
<P>
	On the heels of a 16 percent drop in prices last week,  
attributed to increased OPEC production, some market watchers had 
been expecting a rally. 
</P>
<P>
	``We felt that at the end of last week things got overdone,''  
said Bob Morris, an analyst for Paine Webber. ``I think the funds 
overdid it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Several factors are bullish for crude prices, he said -- the  
North American winter is approaching, U.S. crude inventories are 
still being drawn down and OPEC nations are still largely complying 
with their production cutback agreement. 
</P>
<P>
	Fund buying Tuesday was influenced by the release of American  
Petroleum Institute weekly inventory data after the close of 
trading. 
</P>
<P>
	API reported a sharp 7.139 million barrel drop in crude oil  
stockpiles to 298.936 million barrels for the week ended Oct. 8. 
Analysts were anticipating the decline. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, U.S. gasoline stores rose 2.782 million barrels to  
204.506 million barrels. 
</P>
<P>
	Refinery capacity increased to 93.1 percent from 92.5 percent  
the previous week. 
</P>
<P>
	Crude oil for November delivery rose $1.03 to $22.30 a barrel on  
the New York Mercantile Exchange; November heating oil rose 3.02 
cents to 57.90 cents a gallon; November unleaded gasoline rose 2.74 
cents to 63 cents a gallon; November natural gas rose 10.2 cents to 
$2.927 per million British thermal units. 
</P>
<P>
	In London, North Sea Brent crude oil for November delivery rose  
82 cents to $22.05 a barrel on the International Petroleum 
Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	Coffee prices jumped 6 percent on New York's Coffee, Sugar &AMP;  
Cocoa Exchange after a 7 percent increase the day before. 
</P>
<P>
	The rally is spurred by the continuing dry weather in Brazil,  
where forecasts call for only light rains in some areas in the next 
several days. 
</P>
<P>
	Rainfall is particularly critical for the coffee crop in  
October, when coffee trees flower. Trees can abort their flowers, 
and the developing bean, if subjected to severe weather stress. 
</P>
<P>
	Until the drought emerged, experts had forecast a bumper crop of  
40 million 60-kilogram bags in 2000-01. 
</P>
<P>
	December coffee closed up 5.60 cents at 96.55 cents per pound.  
</P>
<P>
	On the Chicago Mercantile Exchange, lean hogs closed up more  
than 4 percent, regaining losses from the previous day. Speculators 
who were heavily short, or holding large bets that prices will 
fall, bought futures to balance their previous sales, investors 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	December lean hogs rose 1.88 cents to 46.75 cents a pound.  
</P>
<P>
	Pork bellies also were sharply higher. February frozen bellies  
rose 2.18 cents to 64.20 cents a pound. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
