<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Brokerage Earnings Roundup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Three of the largest brokerage firms in the  
United States -- Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co., Paine Webber Group Inc., and 
Donaldson Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette -- benefited from a strong stock market 
to beat analysts expectations for third-quarter profits. 
</P>
<P>
	Revenues generated from trading their own supplies of stocks  
contributed to each of the company's healthy quarterly earnings. In 
comparison, a year ago the entire financial services sector was 
swimming in losses following a huge global stock selloff in the 
wake of the Russian financial crisis. 

</P>
<P>
                         *Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co.    	
</P>
<P>
	The largest brokerage firm in the United States reported strong  
third-quarter earnings Tuesday of $572 million, easily beating 
analysts' expectations. 
</P>
<P>
	The company's profits represent earnings of $1.34 a share, a  
nickel more than the $1.29 a share analysts had predicted, 
according to First Call Corp. 
</P>
<P>
	In the third quarter of 1998, Merrill Lynch reported a loss of  
$173 million, or 48 cents a share, due to a $430 million pretax 
write-off of costs related to staff reductions. 
</P>
<P>
	Merrill Lynch cited record revenues in both global stock  
underwriting and investment banking, which includes mergers and 
acquisitions. 
</P>
<P>
	Total third-quarter revenues were $5.27 billion, up from $3.85  
billion a year ago. 
</P>
<P>
	``Investment banking revenues and asset management and portfolio  
service fees set records, and our global debt and equity businesses 
posted solid trading results despite a more difficult 
environment,'' said Merrill Lynch chairman David Komansky. 
</P>
<P>
	For the first nine months of 1999, Merrill Lynch posted earnings  
of $1.9 billion, or $4.36 a share, up from $900 million, or $2.14 a 
share, in 1998, when taking into account the $430 million loss 
related to layoffs. 
</P>
<P>
	Nine month revenues came to $16 billion, compared to $13.5  
billion a year ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Shares of Merrill Lynch fell 75 cents to $67 on the New York  
Stock Exchange. 

</P>
<P>
                         *Paine Webber Inc.    	
</P>
<P>
	The fourth-largest U.S. brokerage firm reported profits of  
$138.2 million, or 86 cents a share, a 67 percent increase over 
last year's third-quarter figures. In 1998, the firm reported $82.9 
million in earnings, or 51 cents a share. 
</P>
<P>
	Third-quarter revenues were $1.24 billion, versus $1.03 billion  
last year. 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts had predicted earnings of 83 cents per share.  
</P>
<P>
	For the nine-month period, Paine Webber earned $462 million, or  
$2.88 a share. During the same period in 1998, the company earned 
$333 million, or $2.10 a share. Revenues in the first nine months 
were $5.8 billion, up from $5.5 billion a year ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Shares of Paine Webber fell 68 3/4 cents to $35 in trading on the  
NYSE. 

</P>
<P>
                     *Donaldson Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette    	
</P>
<P>
	The eighth-largest securities firm saw its profits quadruple in  
the third quarter, to $122.2 million, or 85 cents a share, from 
$25.7 million, or 15 cents a share, a year ago. Revenues jumped 59 
percent to $1.7 billion from $1.1 billion in 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts had predicted earnings of 76 cents per share.  
</P>
<P>
	In the first nine months of the year, DLJ reported earnings of  
$409.5 million, or $2.84 a share, versus $302.2 million, or $2.18 a 
share in 1998. Nine month revenues were $5 billion versus $4.1 
billion a year ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Shares of DLJ rose $2.18 3/4 to $42.50 on the NYSE.  




  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
