<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> MGM Financier Nabbed in Italy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- U.S. investigators are seeking the  
extradition of financier Giancarlo Parretti, arrested in Italy 
after being named in a federal indictment accusing him of 
defrauding investors of $1.5 billion in a series of Hollywood deals 
that included the 1990 purchase of Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer. 
</P>
<P>
	An indictment unsealed on Tuesday accuses Parretti of 53 counts  
of fraud, conspiracy and other charges. His former partner, Florio 
Fiorini, also was named. 
</P>
<P>
	Credit Lyonnais S.A., the French bank that financed the MGM  
purchase, was identified as an unindicted co-conspirator and has 
agreed to pay $4 million in fines to settle a criminal 
investigation by the U.S. Attorney's Office in Los Angeles. 
</P>
<P>
	The bank also will refer two corporate officers accused of  
aiding Parretti to French authorities for possible prosecution. 
</P>
<P>
	In the meantime, prosecutors have prepared formal extradition  
requests for Parretti and Fiorini that will be hand-carried to 
Italy. Both men are expected to fight extradition, and the process 
could take up to a year, said Assistant U.S. Attorney Jeffrey B. 
Issacs, lead prosecutor in the case. 
</P>
<P>
	Parretti was arrested in Orvieto, about 70 miles north of Rome,  
at the request of U.S. prosecutors, said Assistant U.S. Attorney 
Jeffrey Issacs, the lead prosecutor on the case. Fiorini, 58, was 
arrested in Rome. 
</P>
<P>
	The charges stem from Parretti's $1.3 billion purchase of MGM  
and the 1989 purchase of The Cannon Group Inc., an independent film 
company, and other Hollywood transactions. 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutors contend that Parretti and Fiorini relied on a  
complex web of falsified financial records and overseas shell 
companies to conceal that they actually were borrowing $1.1 billion 
of the MGM purchase price from Credit Lyonnais. 
</P>
<P>
	The money was portrayed in documents as equity that could be  
used to run the studio. Once they got MGM and Cannon, they left 
creditors unpaid and transferred assets overseas, prosecutors said. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is an order of magnitude greater in complexity than  
anything we've seen,'' Issacs said. 
</P>
<P>
	MGM, struggling before Parretti took over, was nearly destroyed  
and Credit Lyonnais' losses reached $2 billion. The bank paid $1.5 
billion to reimburse MGM investors and spent about $500 million to 
keep the studio afloat. 
</P>
<P>
	Those costs contributed to a bad debt crisis that nearly swamped  
Credit Lyonnais. The state-owned bank lost $3.7 billion between 
1992 and 1994. A state bailout package approved earlier this year 
cost French taxpayers nearly $18 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	The indictment accuses Parretti of conspiracy, securities fraud,  
filing false reports to the Securities and Exchange Commission, 
falsifying corporate records, making false statements to auditors, 
money laundering and filing a false tax return. 
</P>
<P>
	Fiorni faces 25 counts of conspiracy, securities fraud, filing  
false reports to the SEC, falsifying corporate records and making 
false statements to auditors. 
</P>
<P>
	Parretti had been in Italy since 1997, when he was convicted of  
perjury and evidence tampering in an MGM-related lawsuit. He fled 
the United States before he could be sentenced. 
</P>
<P>
	Parretti bought MGM in 1990 from Las Vegas billionaire Kirk  
Kerkorian. After he defaulted on a $888 million loan used in the 
purchase, Credit Lyonnais seized the Hollywood studio and removed 
Parretti as chairman. 
</P>
<P>
	A court in Paris convicted him of corruption charges and  
sentenced him in absentia to four years in prison. France sought 
Parretti's extradition from the U.S. before he fled. France can't 
remove him from Italy because the extradition agreement between 
France and Italy does not permit the extradition of Italian 
citizens, Issacs said. 
</P>
<P>
	For years, Credit Lyonnais maintained that it, too, was a victim  
of Parretti's deceptions. The bank agreed to pay fines after 
evidence emerged that two corporate officers, one at Credit 
Lyonnais and the other at its Netherlands subsidiary, had helped 
Parretti show paper assets that didn't really exist. Those assets 
were then used to gain control of Cannon and MGM. 
</P>
<P>
	The goal of the deception, said Issacs, was not to make money  
but gain control of companies. Looted MGM assets were used to 
bolster the books of Parretti's overseas holdings, he said. 



</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
