<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Texas Death Penalty DA Retiring </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HOUSTON (AP) -- The district attorney whose office has won more  
death sentences than any other in the nation will not run for 
another term. 
</P>
<P>
	John B. Holmes Jr. said he has not yet made plans for the  
future, but knows he doesn't want to run for his sixth four-year 
term. He was first appointed as Harris County district attorney in 
1979. 
</P>
<P>
	``My daddy had a saying I subscribe to -- that it's time go home  
from a vacation when you're still having fun,'' Holmes said 
Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Holmes, 58, bristles at the suggestion that his office of  
200-plus prosecutors is a capital punishment machine, although 
about one-third of the 461 men and women on Texas' death row come 
from Harris County. Texas leads the nation in executions. 
</P>
<P>
	``Prosecutors don't sentence people to death, people do,''  
Holmes said. ``I have never wanted to be known as a guru of the 
death penalty, and it's not fun when it's made to be personal. But 
somebody's got to (prosecute the cases), and whoever does it should 
do it to the best of their ability.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Holmes' office seeks a death sentence in 12 to 20 cases a year  
and almost always succeeds. In his years as district attorney, his 
office has won more than 200 death penalty cases. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
