<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-12 08:20:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Court To Consider Police Searches </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Supreme Court today agreed to use a Texas  
drug case to decide whether police are conducting a search, and 
must comply with constitutional requirements, when they feel 
someone's luggage to determine if drugs might be inside. 
</P>
<P>
	The justices said they will hear an appeal by a man convicted on  
drug charges after an officer felt and squeezed the bag he had put 
in an overhead bin while traveling on a bus. 
</P>
<P>
	Steven Dewayne Bond was convicted of conspiracy and possession  
offenses involving the drug methamphetamine. 
</P>
<P>
	He was a passenger on a Greyhound bus stopped at an immigration  
checkpoint in Sierra Blanca, Texas. The bus had traveled from 
California and was enroute to Arkansas. 
</P>
<P>
	A U.S. Border Patrol agent checked the passengers' immigration  
status, then felt their luggage, including bags in overhead bins 
and under passengers' seats. 
</P>
<P>
	The agent squeezed a canvas bag in the bin over Bond's seat, and  
the shape of a ``brick-like'' object inside led him to suspect it 
contained drugs. When the agent asked Bond if he could open the 
bag, Bond said, ``Go ahead.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The agent found, wrapped inside a pair of pants, a brick-like  
object covered in tape. Tests showed it contained methamphetamine. 
Bond admitted he possessed the drug. 
</P>
<P>
	Bond asked a trial judge in October 1997 to rule the drug could  
not be used as evidence, contending that the officer's squeezing of 
his bag amounted to a search that violated the Constitution's 
Fourth Amendment protection against unreasonable searches. 
</P>
<P>
	The amendment generally prohibits searches unless police have  
``probable cause'' to believe they will find evidence of a crime. 
</P>
<P>
	A judge ruled against him, and the 5th U.S. Circuit Court of  
Appeals upheld that ruling last February. The appeals court said 
Bond gave up any reasonable expectation of privacy in his bag 
because he ``exposed it to the public'' by placing it in the 
luggage bin. 
</P>
<P>
	In the appeal granted review today, Bond's lawyer said federal  
appeals courts have reached conflicting rulings in such cases. 
</P>
<P>
	The appeal said squeezing the carry-on bags of bus passengers is  
a ``relatively new tactic in the war on drugs.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Travelers, like Bond, have a legitimate expectation of privacy  
in their personal luggage, an expectation that the Fourth Amendment 
protects,'' his appeal argued. 
</P>
<P>
	The case is Bond vs. U.S., 98-9349.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
