<HEADLINE> Dollar falls broadly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The dollar fell broadly Tuesday as a slumping  
U.S. stock market raised concerns that foreign investors may find 
U.S. assets less attractive. 
</P>
<P>
	In late New York trading, the euro was quoted at $1.0758, up  
from $1.0648 late Monday. The dollar also fell to 106.31 Japanese 
yen from 106.68. 
</P>
<P>
	Stocks fell on Wall Street, with the Dow Jones industrials down  
2.2 percent on worries about upcoming earnings reports and a 
declining bond market. 
</P>
<P>
	``It creates an environment in which investors become  
apprehensive about U.S. assets, particularly if the stock market is 
perceived as not going much higher,'' said Tim Fox, currency 
analyst at Standard Chartered Bank in New York. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's a risk that global investors could start to divest of  
U.S. assets and sell the dollar,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, the dollar fell against the yen as traders waited  
to see what the Bank of Japan might do about the rising yen at its 
policy meeting on Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Some worry that the rising yen may derail Japan's economic  
recovery because a strong yen makes Japanese exports more 
expensive. The Bank of Japan has been under pressure to increase 
the domestic money supply to blunt the Japanese currency's advance. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar also was quoted at 1.4806 Swiss francs, down from  
1.4987, and 1.4746 Canadian dollars, up from 1.4730. The British 
pound rose to $1.6567 from $1.6529. 
</P>
<P>
	Currencies of the 11 countries participating in the euro are no  
longer traded separately and are tied to the euro by a fixed rate. 
Based on Tuesday's euro rate, the dollar was worth: 1.8179 German 
marks, down from 1.8370; 6.0968 French francs, down from 6.1610; 
and 1,799.67 Italian lire, down from 1,818.61. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
