<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Padres President Has Surgery </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN DIEGO (AP) -- San Diego Padres president Larry Lucchino is  
recovering from prostate cancer surgery, the team announced 
Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The 54-year-old Lucchino underwent surgery last Wednesday at  
Johns Hopkins Hospital in Baltimore and was released Saturday. Due 
to Monday's Columbus Day holiday, the team delayed making an 
announcement until after the front office staff was notified on 
Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The surgery, performed by Dr. Patrick Walsh, was successful and  
no additional treatments, such as radiation or chemotherapy, are 
required, club spokesman Charles Steinberg said. 
</P>
<P>
	This is Lucchino's second bout with cancer. He was diagnosed  
with non-Hodgkin's lymphoma in September 1985 and underwent 
surgery, as well as rigorous chemotherapy and radiation treatments 
that lasted through 1986. 
</P>
<P>
	Doctors say the prostate cancer is not related to the earlier  
cancer. 
</P>
<P>
	Lucchino still owns a residence in Baltimore, where he was  
president of the Orioles from 1988 until 1993, and will remain 
there for several weeks while recuperating. 
</P>
<P>
	The Padres are at a critical stage in the development of a  
downtown ballpark that is scheduled to open in 2002. An 
environmental impact report is before the City Council. 
</P>
<P>
	This is the second ballpark project Lucchino has been involved  
with. He was one of the forces behind the construction of 
Baltimore's Camden Yards. 
</P>
<P>
	``After a little rest and relaxation, and with the aid of the  
technological revolution, I will soon be reinvolved -- for better or 
for worse -- in the ongoing affairs of our club,'' Lucchino said in 
a statement. 
</P>
<P>
	``I am as relieved as a friend can be,'' Padres owner John  
Moores said. ``I want him to take his time, rest up, then get back 
to his work of running this organization.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
