<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> China to US: Ratify Test Ban Treaty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BEIJING (AP) -- China on Tuesday urged the United States to  
ratify the nuclear test ban treaty, saying the action would help 
persuade other countries to follow suit. 
</P>
<P>
	Ratification by the United States, which has carried out more  
tests than any other nuclear power, is key to the future of the 
Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty, Chinese Foreign Ministry spokeswoman 
Zhang Qiyue said. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. support would ``serve as an example and promote the  
ratification of the treaty by other countries,'' Zhang said in 
response to a question at a media briefing. 
</P>
<P>
	It is up to the U.S. Senate to ratify the treaty. Rejection  
would be a humiliating defeat for President Clinton, the first 
world leader to sign the 1996 pact. 
</P>
<P>
	On Monday, Clinton asked the Senate to put off voting on the  
treaty, warning that its defeat would ``severely harm the national 
security.'' 
</P>
<P>
	China, a nuclear power, has yet to ratify the treaty, although a  
senior Chinese arms control negotiator told an international 
conference last week that Beijing would speed up ratification. 
</P>
<P>
	Signed by 154 states, the treaty needs to be ratified by 44  
nuclear states to enter into force. So far 41 of them have signed 
but only 26 have ratified. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
