<DOCNO> APW19991012.0104 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-12 02:20:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Tokyo Stock Prices Rise / Japanese Stocks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo stock prices gained slightly Tuesday, boosted  
by an increase in U.S. high technology shares and hopes for company 
alliances in oil and telecommunications. The U.S. dollar fell 
against the yen. 
</P>
<P>
	The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average rose 28.63 points,  
or 0.16 percent, to 18,090.81 at the end of the afternoon session 
Tuesday. The index closed down 74.37 points, or 0.41 percent, on 
Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar traded at 106.28 yen at 5 p.m. (0800 GMT), 1.18 yen  
below its level of 107.46 yen late Friday in Tokyo and also below 
106.68 yen late in New York on Monday. The greenback ranged between 
106.18 yen and 106.95 yen during the day's trading. 
</P>
<P>
	Tokyo financial markets were closed Monday for a national  
holiday. 
</P>
<P>
	Expectations of alliances in oil, telecommunications and  
financial services boosted stocks in those areas Tuesday. The 
communications sector was the top percentage gainer, rising 5.9 
percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Banks were stronger also on hopes for further realignments,  
particularly after Tokai Bank and Asahi Bank formally announced 
their integration on Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Wall Street action overnight also helped Tokyo shares.  
</P>
<P>
	The Dow Jones industrial average fell 1.58 points to close  
Monday at 10,648.18. Spurred by a rise in the semiconductor sector, 
however, the technology heavy Nasdaq composite index rose 29.48 
points to 2,916.05, surpassing its all-time closing high of 
2,887.06, set Sept. 10. 
</P>
<P>
	Waning hope that the Bank of Japan will take significant action  
to stem the yen's rise against the dollar, however, tended to rein 
in enthusiasm on the market, traders said. The bank holds a policy 
meeting on Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	``The market was solidly supported, with investors buying a wide  
range of sectors,'' said Kunihiro Hatae, general manager at Tokyo 
Securities Co. ``But players generally took a wait-and-see stance 
ahead of the BOJ meeting, though we don't expect any policy 
change.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The yen has soared in recent months, and some have been calling  
for the BOJ to increase the domestic money supply to blunt the 
Japanese currency's advance. 
</P>
<P>
	Financial authorities fret that too steep a rise in the yen  
could derail a budding economic recovery here by reducing demand 
for Japanese goods abroad as a stronger currency makes them more 
expensive. Japan is struggling to emerge from its worst economic 
downturn in 50 years. 
</P>
<P>
	In other currencies, the euro was trading at 113.37 yen in  
mid-afternoon, below 114.68 yen late Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	The broader Tokyo stock price index of all issues listed on the  
first section rose 11.97 points, or 0.78 percent, to finish the 
afternoon session at 1,542.80. The TOPIX closed up 5.79 points, or 
0.38 percent, on Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Volume on the First Section of the Tokyo Stock Exchange was  
estimated at 693 million shares, down from 781.47 million shares 
Friday. Advancing issues outnumbered retreaters 617 to 595, while 
125 issues were unchanged. 
</P>
<P>
	The yield on the benchmark 10-year Japanese government bond rose  
to 1.7850 percent from Friday's finish of 1.7650 percent. Its price 
fell 0.17 point to 99.26. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
