<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-12 18:40:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Tricon Restaurants Post Profits </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOUISVILLE, Ky. (AP) -- Tricon Global Restaurants Inc. reported a  
21 percent increase in third-quarter earnings Tuesday, as strong 
sales at Pizza Hut offset a sluggish performance by its taco and 
chicken brands. 
</P>
<P>
	The fast-food giant had earnings from operations of $112  
million, or 70 cents per share for the quarter ended Sept. 4. That 
compares with operating earnings of $91 million, or 58 cents per 
share in the year-ago period. 
</P>
<P>
	The results beat analysts' expectations by a penny a share,  
according to First Call/Thomson Financial. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're on track for an outstanding year,'' said Tricon Chairman  
and CEO Andrall Pearson. 
</P>
<P>
	Pizza Hut's same-store U.S. sales rose 6 percent, marking the  
ninth consecutive quarter of strong growth. Meanwhile same-store 
sales dropped 3 percent at Taco Bell and 2 percent at KFC. 
</P>
<P>
	Tricon also credited strong overseas sales for its higher  
earnings for the most recent quarter. Operating profits in the 
international business exceeded 40 percent, more than doubling the 
showing a year ago. 
</P>
<P>
	``Pizza Hut has been the major bright spot of the company the  
last six months,'' said Damon Brundage, restaurant analyst at J.P. 
Morgan. ``The Big New Yorker (pizza) has been a very, very 
successful new product launch, and they've done a good job 
marketing it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Louisville-based company reported net income of $197 million  
for the quarter, reflecting gains from accounting changes and other 
unusual items, up sharply from $128 million from the same period 
last year. 
</P>
<P>
	The company said it sold more than 500 stores to franchisees  
during the third quarter, bringing the year's total to more than 
1,100 stores sold. 
</P>
<P>
	Year to date, operating earnings have increased 46 percent to  
$290 million, or $1.80 per share, from $199 million, or $1.28 per 
share for the first nine months of 1998, the company said. 
</P>
<P>
	Tricon touted its new line of KFC chicken sandwiches and The  
Chalupa, a fried version of Taco Bell's Gordita, as products that 
could give the two chains a fourth-quarter boost. The company said 
the chicken sandwiches could contribute $100,000 to $200,000 to 
each KFC store's annual sales. 
</P>
<P>
	Brundage said analysts will keep close tabs on how the new  
products are faring with consumers. 
</P>
<P>
	``As the summer went on, Taco Bell and KFC sales continued to  
soften,'' he said. ``I think the bet management is making is that 
these new products are going to move the needle and get people back 
in the stores. Right now, we don't have any idea if that is 
happening.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Tricon's stock closed down 25 cents, at $41.81 1/4, Tuesday on the  
New York Stock Exchange. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991012.0108 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-12 19:20:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> West Has Fond Memories of Wilt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Jerry West remembers how pleased he was when  
he learned Wilt Chamberlain was joining the Los Angeles Lakers. 
Then, he picked up a newspaper and was sick to his stomach. 
</P>
<P>
	The story in the paper said West didn't want Chamberlain as a  
teammate. 
</P>
<P>
	He doesn't know where the story came from, but ``it was the most  
ridiculous thing I've ever read in my life,'' West said Tuesday 
after learning of Chamberlain's death. 
</P>
<P>
	To the contrary, he said, it was a momentous day, because ``we  
had one of the true, great centers.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Lakers, close but never champions during West's first 11  
years with the team, acquired Chamberlain from the Philadelphia 
76ers on July 9, 1968. 
</P>
<P>
	The title both yearned for finally came four years later,  
capping a season in which the Lakers won an NBA-record 33 straight 
games. 
</P>
<P>
	``The frustration of playing here and not being able to win a  
championship had really left me pretty bitter as a player,'' West 
said. ``That was the only thing that mattered to me after a while. 
I was obsessed with it. 
</P>
<P>
	``When I started to play with him, he helped make me a better  
player. We seemed to have a real good feel together. All players 
are generally judged by the number of championships they won. 
Unfortunately, he only won two. Nevertheless, his greatness as a 
basketball player can't be questioned.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Both Hall of Famers would retire at the end of the 1972-73  
season. Chamberlain became coach of the San Diego Conquistadores 
for a year before turning to business and entertainment. West has 
been a Lakers executive for nearly two decades. 
</P>
<P>
	``One of the things when you got to know him a little bit is he  
had a very strong opinion about everything, a very strong opinion 
about himself as a player,'' West said. ``I think all of us who 
played with him realize the tremendous impact he had. 
</P>
<P>
	``I would run into him from time to time; he was one of those  
guys who was a nomad. One of the things I admired about him, you 
see the players of today, they have the entourages, he was the 
common man. He had no problem going places, no problem being 
recognized as Wilt Chamberlain.'' 
</P>
<P>
	West recalled being on a team flight to St. Louis on March 2,  
1962, and the subject was Chamberlain, then a 25-year-old member of 
the Philadelphia Warriors. 
</P>
<P>
	``We were talking about Wilt, how he was going to score 100  
points in a game real soon,'' West recalled. ``When we got off the 
airplane, somebody said, `Hey, did you hear about Wilt Chamberlain? 
He scored 100 points in a game.' 
</P>
<P>
	``That's one record that will never be broken, I can assure  
you.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991012.0109 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-12 05:40:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Downtown Sydney Hit by Power Outage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SYDNEY, Australia (AP) -- Power was cut to parts of Australia's  
largest city today, temporarily shutting down office towers, 
switching off traffic lights and trapping people in elevators 
across downtown Sydney. 
</P>
<P>
	Power company Energy Australia said an explosion caused by a  
fire at a substation in St. Peters, a suburb south of the central 
business district, severed a cable supplying power to downtown and 
several city areas, including at least one venue to next year's 
Olympic Games. 
</P>
<P>
	Company officials said initially that rerouting power to the  
city through other cables could take up to two hours. However, 
power to at least some parts was restored after about 30 minutes. 
</P>
<P>
	Energy Australia's general manager, Paul Broad, said he could  
not guarantee a similar outage would not happen during next year's 
Olympics, but said the electric system would be updated by then. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Olympics will be different, say, for (Olympic venue)  
Darling Harbor, because there will be backup generation there,'' 
Broad told reporters. 
</P>
<P>
	``There will be two sources of supply as well as that backup,''  
he said. ``It will be the same story at most Games sites.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Central Traffic Control Center for Sydney said it had lost  
power to more than 50 traffic lights, causing a brief period of 
chaos on the metropolis' clogged streets. There were no reports of 
accidents. 
</P>
<P>
	Emergency authorities said dozens of office workers were trapped  
in elevators. No one was reported injured. 
</P>
<P>
	All over downtown, workers from office towers took the stairs to  
evacuate from buildings where computers, air conditioners and other 
electrical appliances shut down. 
</P>
<P>
	Some areas appeared to escape the outage. Many switched to  
backup supplies. 
</P>
<P>
	Australia's central bank and stock exchange apparently were  
unaffected, but some commercial banks lost power. 
</P>
<P>
	Eric Aubert, Energy Australia's media manager, said the utility  
had received no reports of hospitals losing power, and said they 
often had emergency back-up systems. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991012.0110 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-12 00:40:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Alabama's Alexander Eyes Heisman </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TUSCALOOSA, Ala. (AP) -- If Shaun Alexander had his way, playing  
in the Southeastern Conference would count heavily in voting for 
the Heisman Trophy. 
</P>
<P>
	If that's the case, Alexander has an edge over Georgia Tech's  
Joe Hamilton, at least in the Alabama running back's mind. 
</P>
<P>
	``If you're one of the best players in the SEC, you've got to  
have a shot,'' Alexander said Monday. ``If I do something good and 
Joe does something good in the ACC, I've got to have the advantage 
because I think the SEC is more dominant.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The only thing that's really important, though, is the numbers.  
So far, Alexander has put up enough of them to find himself thick 
in the Heisman race. 
</P>
<P>
	Once considered a long shot for college football's most coveted  
award, Alexander is suddenly very much in the picture thanks to a 
four-touchdown performance two weeks ago against Florida. 
</P>
<P>
	Even though the 11th-ranked Crimson Tide (4-1) were off last  
week, Alexander's name was heard a lot more often when candidates 
were discussed on Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Not bad, considering Alexander wasn't much of a factor  
Heisman-wise before the season started -- despite the campaign 
Crimson Tide officials launched for him. 
</P>
<P>
	Alabama has never before touted a player for an award because  
former coach Bear Bryant didn't believe in it. Because of that, the 
highest an Alabama player has ever finished in the voting was 
third, David Palmer in 1993. 
</P>
<P>
	But when Alexander chose to return to school for his senior  
season, coach Mike DuBose promised to help him win the Heisman. 
</P>
<P>
	DuBose has done his part by giving Alexander the ball at least  
30 times a game. And the school has created an Alexander Web site 
and sent out a CD-ROM of his performance highlights to Heisman 
voters. 
</P>
<P>
	They left the rest up to Alexander.  
</P>
<P>
	``I think the Heisman campaign is more of a `Hey, look over here  
at what they've got,''' Alexander said. ``If I continue to play 
well and we continue to win, it should take care of itself.'' 
</P>
<P>
	So far, he's living up to his end.  
</P>
<P>
	Alexander leads the nation in scoring and is second in  
all-purpose yardage behind Stanford receiver Troy Walters. 
</P>
<P>
	He has a string of five straight 100-yard rushing efforts, one  
shy of matching the Alabama record, and needs just 519 yards to 
pass Bobby Humphrey as Alabama's career rushing leader with 3,420 
yards. 
</P>
<P>
	But his best work came in nationally televised wins over  
Arkansas and Florida. Against Arkansas, he ran for 165 yards and a 
touchdown. 
</P>
<P>
	The next week against Florida, he scored three rushing  
touchdowns, one receiving touchdown and had 200 all-purpose yards. 
</P>
<P>
	Alexander was even impressive in a 29-28 upset loss to Louisiana  
Tech when he ran for 173 yards and two touchdowns. He scored a 
third TD on a 76-yard kickoff return -- the only time he has 
returned a kick all year. 
</P>
<P>
	DuBose, who had his first chance this season to sit back and  
watch some games on Saturday, said he has yet to find a player 
better than Alexander. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't see anyone that is doing as much on and off the field  
than Shaun does,'' DuBose said. ``He's outstanding in all phases of 
the offense. His presence alone makes the 10 guys around him 
better.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Alexander will get a chance to showcase himself even more over  
the next two weeks when Alabama plays at No. 22 Mississippi, then 
plays host to No. 6 Tennessee. Both games will be nationally 
televised. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think the Heisman is about how you carry your team and what  
you mean to it,'' he said. ``Heisman winners win the big games, so 
we'll see what happens.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991012.0111 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-12 08:03:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Russia Targets Chechen Positions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	GROZNY, Russia (AP) -- Russian forces pounded Chechen positions  
with an artillery barrage on several fronts today, and Russian 
authorities said they suspect Chechen militants will soon try to 
launch terrorist attacks. 
</P>
<P>
	Both the Russians and the Chechens have been fortifying fixed  
positions in recent days, but neither side has launched any major 
offensives. 
</P>
<P>
	The Russians have been relying mostly on their big artillery  
guns. They were hammering two areas north of Chechnya's capital, 
Grozny, this morning. The echo of the exploding shells could be 
heard throughout the city. The Russians were also methodically 
shelling near the western town of Bamut, which has been under 
attack for several days. 
</P>
<P>
	The Russian Defense Ministry cited five regions in central,  
eastern and western Chechnya that were hit in artillery and air 
raids in the previous 24 hours. 
</P>
<P>
	The shelling was the latest development in a conflict that began  
this summer, when Chechnya-based Islamic militants invaded 
neighboring Dagestan twice with the aim of setting up an Islamic 
state. They also are suspected in four Russian apartment bombings 
in September that killed about 300 people. 
</P>
<P>
	Russia responded to the attacks by sending troops into Chechnya  
two weeks ago, raising fears of another all-out war there. During 
the first conflict in 1994-96, Chechnya fought Russian troops to a 
humiliating standstill. It won effective independence for itself, 
but was left devastated and lawless. 
</P>
<P>
	Russian Defense Minister Igor Sergeyev said today that the  
Russian aim of establishing a security zone in Chechnya ``is close 
to completion.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``The ultimate objective is not only to form the security zone,  
but to destroy armed gangs,'' he said while on a visit to Ukraine, 
Russian news agencies reported. Government forces ``will not stop, 
but will carry on tasks to eliminate gangs and terrorist groups.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Although Russian troops have held off mounting a ground attack  
on the capital, Russia has shown little inclination to negotiate an 
end to the fighting. 
</P>
<P>
	For now, the front line is largely defined by the Terek River,  
which flows across the northern third of Chechnya, forming a 
natural defense barrier. 
</P>
<P>
	The Russians control the sparsely populated plains to the north  
of the river, though the Chechens still hold a few positions. The 
Chechens have most of the territory in the more heavily populated 
regions south of the river, though the Russians have made inroads 
in western Chechnya and have been massing forces along Chechnya's 
eastern border. 
</P>
<P>
	The Defense Ministry said that two of Chechnya's most prominent  
warlords, Salman Raduyev and Shamil Basayev, were both planning 
terrorist attacks inside Russia. Raduyev intended to target Russian 
nuclear facilities, while Basayev was training women militants to 
carry out attacks in southern Russia, the ministry claimed, without 
citing any evidence. 
</P>
<P>
	More than 155,000 Chechens have fled since the fighting began,  
with most heading to Ingushetia, an impoverished region on 
Chechnya's western border. 
</P>
<P>
	Humanitarian aid has been slow in arriving, and the United  
Nations High Commissioner for Refugees in Moscow said the next 
convoy of assistance was being delayed due to ``the very slow 
distribution of aid already delivered,'' the Interfax news agency 
reported. 
</P>
<P>
	The Emergency Situations Ministry said it was flying 52 tons of  
baby food, canned meat, sugar and other supplies into the region on 
Tuesday. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991012.0112 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-12 08:03:50 </DATE_TIME>
