<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Russian Porcelain Shares Returned </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MOSCOW (AP) -- A court ruling ordering private investors to  
return to the state their shares in the renowned Lomonosov 
Porcelain Factory has riled Russia's stock market regulator, who 
said it will hurt efforts to promote foreign investment. 
</P>
<P>
	The St. Petersburg factory, which was founded in 1744 by a  
daughter of Peter the Great, is one of Russia's best-known 
manufacturers of luxury goods and was a longtime maker of fine 
china for the czars. 
</P>
<P>
	The decision was the first of its kind since wholesale  
privatization of state property began in 1992 and could provide 
additional reasons for investors, already skittish about the 
country's unstable business climate, to shun Russian ventures. 
</P>
<P>
	Major shareholders affected by the court ruling are several  
executives from Kohlberg Kravis Roberts &AMP; Co., a 
multibillion-dollar U.S. investment firm, and the United 
States-Russia Investment Fund, a U.S. government investment program 
aimed at providing assistance for Russia's stumbling economy. They 
said an appeal is planned. 
</P>
<P>
	Lomonosov produces fine china tea sets and dishes, some  
hand-painted and gilded with precious metals. Homemakers in Russia 
speak lovingly of Lomonosov products, which still sell briskly 
here. 
</P>
<P>
	After the collapse of the Soviet Union, foreign investors bought  
about 60 percent of the shares in Lomonosov, which had sales of 
about $7 million last year. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S.-Russia fund paid about $4.25 million for its 25-percent  
stake in Lomonosov. 
</P>
<P>
	But factory directors have said they chafed at foreigners  
controlling a Russian national treasure. A suit was filed by the 
State Property Committee and a St. Petersburg court ruled Monday 
that the 1993 privatization was illegal. 
</P>
<P>
	The court ruling was viewed by regulators as a setback for  
development. 
</P>
<P>
	Russia needs foreign investment to overhaul crumbling factories  
and infrastructure, but only a relatively small number of investors 
have risked putting money into this country's chaotic economy. 
</P>
<P>
	``From our point of view, this precedent taken by the State  
Property Ministry of Russia deprives existing shareholders and 
investors of the confidence that the state protects them, and calls 
into doubt their ownership rights to shares and bonds in any 
Russian enterprises formed as a result of privatization,'' said 
Dmitry Vasiliyev, chairman of Russia's Federal Securities 
Commission in a public letter to State Property Minister Farit 
Gazizullin. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S.-Russia fund and executives of Kohlberg Kravis Roberts  
together hold more than half of the Lomonosov shares. 
</P>
<P>
	Pending the appeal, they plan to call a shareholders' meeting in  
an attempt to take control of the board and oust top management. 
</P>
<P>
	Alistair Stobie, vice president of the fund, told a news  
conference Tuesday that investors have long wanted to remove a 
management team left over from Soviet times and to overhaul the 
factory. 
</P>
<P>
	In a few previous cases, courts have confiscated shares in  
privatized enterprises when new owners have failed to keep promises 
to invest in their property. But Monday's ruling marked the first 
reversal of a privatization where workers had received shares in a 
company. 
</P>
<P>
	Foreign investors later purchased the shares in Lomonosov on the  
secondary market from a broker. Courts have not questioned the 
legality of this type of a purchase. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
