<HEADLINE> Phelps Dodge Earnings Fall 20 Pct. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHOENIX (AP) -- Phelps Dodge Corp. reported its third-quarter  
earnings fell 20.7 percent due to the continuing slump in copper 
prices. 
</P>
<P>
	The big copper and wire producer said Tuesday it earned $16.1  
million, or 28 cents per share, down from $20.3 million, or 35 
cents per share, reported for the same period last year. 
</P>
<P>
	Phelps Dodge surpassed analyst expectations of 21 cents per  
share, according to First Call/Thomson Financial. The results 
pleased investors, who bid Phelps Dodge stock rose $1.87 1/2 to 
$57.06 1/4 a share in trading on the New York Stock Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	The results do not reflect a restructuring charge of $700,000,  
or 1 cent per share, for the latest quarter, and a 1998 gain of 
$8.3 million, or 14 cents per share, from the completion of the 
sale of Accuride Corp. 
</P>
<P>
	Sales came to $742.7 million, down from $764 million.  
</P>
<P>
	The company was hurt by the lingering depression in copper  
prices and by a difficult market for wire and cable. Copper, which 
traded over $1 a pound two years ago, is now in the 80-cent range. 
</P>
<P>
	However, because of a recent uptick in prices, the Phelps Dodge  
Mining subsidiary had $36 million in operating income, its best 
quarterly performance since the first quarter of 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	Phelps Dodge's specialty chemicals division also continued to do  
well, thanks in part to strong business at its recently acquired 
carbon black facilities overseas. 
</P>
<P>
	In the last several months, Phelps Dodge has been in the midst  
of trying to acquire two rivals, New York-based Asarco Inc. and 
Englewood, Colo.-based Cyprus Amax Minerals Co. 
</P>
<P>
	Asarco last week to be acquired by Phelps Dodge for about $1.1  
billion in cash and stock, but Grupo Mexico has since made a higher 
all-cash offer. 
</P>
<P>
	Phelps Dodge has agreed to acquire Cyprus Amax for $1.8 billion  
in cash and stock. 
</P>
<P>
	Earnings for the first nine months of 1999 came to $17.8  
million, or 31 cents per share, down from $101.6 million, or $1.73 
per share, in the same period of 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	The results do not reflect restructuring charges of $59.4  
million, or $1.03 a share, or a charge of $3.5 million, or 6 cents 
a shre, for an accounting change. They also do not include a gain 
of $131.1 million, or $2.24 per share, from the Accuride sale. 
</P>
<P>
	Sales came to $2,1 billion in the first nine months, compared  
with $2.36 million in the same period of 1998. 



</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
