<HEADLINE> Intel's 3Q Profits Up 21 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SANTA CLARA, Calif. (AP) -- Intel Corp.'s third-quarter operating  
profit rose 21 percent, but the chipmaker's results were shy of 
forecasts and may heighten earnings fears that helped send the 
stock market plunging on Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The world's largest manufacturer of semiconductors earned $1.9  
billion, or 55 cents a share, in the three months ended Sept. 26, 
excluding one-time expenses related to acquisitions of other 
companies. 
</P>
<P>
	It was a strong improvement from last year's third-quarter  
operating profit of $1.58 billion, or 45 cents a share, but 2 cents 
per share below expectations, according to a survey of industry 
analysts by First Call/Thompson Financial. 
</P>
<P>
	Third-quarter revenues rose 9 percent to $7.3 billion from $6.7  
billion a year earlier. While sales were particularly strong for 
Intel's Pentium III chip used in many personal computers, the 
product line drew lower profits than in previous quarters amid 
aggressive pricing by rivals intent on grabbing market share. 
</P>
<P>
	The results, released after the close of regular stock trading,  
were a surprise for many Wall Street investors who've come to 
expect Intel to meet or beat analyst forecasts. Hopes were also 
high because sales of personal computers, the overwhelming majority 
of which run on Intel microprocessors, typically rise in the third 
quarter amid back-to-school and early holiday shopping. 
</P>
<P>
	Notably, Intel's stock rose 18 3/4 cents a share to $76.68 3/4 in  
Nasdaq trading before the report, despite a steep decline on the 
overall stock market that sliced 231 points off the Dow Jones 
industrial average. In after hours trading on other markets, Intel 
fell as low as $70 a share, a drop that could spark another market 
decline at the start of Wednesday's trading. 
</P>
<P>
	Intel, based in Santa Clara, Calif., took a charge during the  
just-ended quarter for expenses related to the purchase of Level 
One Communications. Including the charges, Intel posted a net 
profit of $1.5 billion, or 42 cents a share. That was down from a 
net profit of $1.6 billion, or 45 cents a share, in the same period 
last year, also including one-time charges for acquisitions. 
</P>
<P>
	For the first nine months of 1999, operating income totaled $5.7  
billion, or $1.65 a share, up from $4.2 billion, or $1.19 a share, 
in the same period last year. Net revenue rose to $21.2 billion 
from $18.7 billion in the first nine months of 1998. 



</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
