<HEADLINE> MGM Posts First Profit in 3 Years </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SANTA MONICA, Calif. (AP) -- Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer Inc. reported  
its first profitable quarter in almost three years Tuesday, earning 
$10.3 million on the strength of recent films, TV programming and 
cost-cutting. 
</P>
<P>
	The third-quarter results came in well above forecasts of Wall  
Street analysts, who had predicted a loss. 
</P>
<P>
	It marked MGM's first profit since the last three months of  
1996, when the company was privately owned. From Oct. 11 to Dec. 
31, 1996, MGM reported a $166,000 profit as the company prepared to 
go public. 
</P>
<P>
	Earnings for the quarter that ended Sept. 30 were 7 cents a  
share, compared with a $40.3 million, or 61 cents a share, loss for 
the same period in 1998. Analysts surveyed by First Call/Thomson 
Financial had expected MGM to lose 19 cents a share in this year's 
third quarter. 
</P>
<P>
	Revenue was $299.3 million, up from $259.6 million for the third  
quarter of 1998. Most of that increase came from MGM's television 
division, whose gains included third-run sales of its series ``The 
Outer Limits'' and ``Poltergeist: The Legacy'' to the Sci-Fi 
Channel. 
</P>
<P>
	After a string of film flops that included ``The Mod Squad,''  
``Carrie 2: The Rage'' and ``Dirty Work,'' MGM had modest hits with 
``The Thomas Crown Affair,'' which has grossed $67.4 million 
domestically, and ``Stigmata,'' which has taken in $46.5 million. 
</P>
<P>
	MGM also did well with the arthouse hit ``Tea With Mussolini.''  
The film grossed $14 million after the studio acquired domestic 
rights for $2.5 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Next month, MGM releases ``The World Is Not Enough,'' the 19th  
film in its James Bond franchise. 
</P>
<P>
	The third-quarter profit was a ``tremendous milestone for the  
new MGM,'' chairman and chief executive officer Alex Yemenidjian 
said in a news release. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have set the stage for sustained improvement, with further  
revenue enhancements and diversification planned for the long 
term,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	For the first nine months of 1999, MGM lost $546.1 million on  
revenues of $770.2 million, compared with a $113.9 million loss and 
$857.3 million in revenues for the same period in 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	This year's losses include a $431 million charge for  
restructuring, cost-cutting and other one-time expenses. 
</P>
<P>
	MGM this month canceled a $750 million common stock offering,  
saying its current share price does not reflect the company's 
value. It substituted an offering to allow current shareholders to 
acquire up to $720 million in additional stock. 
</P>
<P>
	Tracinda Corp., the investment arm of billionaire Kirk  
Kerkorian, owns most of the company's stock and has pledged to 
acquire any shares not bought by other MGM investors. 
</P>
<P>
	MGM's stock remained unchanged at $22.18 3/4 on the New York  
Stock Exchange. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
