<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Soybeans, Grains Advance / Board of Trade  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Soybean futures jumped higher today in early  
trading on the Chicago Board of Trade on news that key growing 
areas in South America are bone-dry as planting season nears. 
Grains also advanced sharply. 
</P>
<P>
	Soybeans opened slightly higher amid dry conditions in key  
northern Brazil growing areas, then leaped over the $5-a-bushel 
barrier. Prices increased 2 percent in the first 45 minutes of 
trading as investors followed the lead of the coffee market in New 
York, where prices also soared in early trading. 
</P>
<P>
	Corn also advanced as buyers anticipated a crop update report  
later in the day by the U.S. Department of Agriculture. Solid 
harvest progress is expected into next week. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat futures rose after a long-range weather forecast called  
for no precipitation in the U.S. winter wheat belt for the next 
week or more, possibly causing problems for the newly planted crop. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat for December delivery rose 4 1/2 cents to $2.58 a bushel;  
December corn rose 3 3/4 cents to $2.02 1/2 a bushel; December oats rose 
2 1/4 cents to $1.11 a bushel; November soybeans rose 8 1/4 cents to 
$5.01 1/2 a bushel. 
</P>
<P>
	Beef and pork futures advanced in early trading today on the  
Chicago Mercantile Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	December live cattle rose .10 cent to 69.85 cents a pound;  
October feeder cattle fell .28 cent to 80.62 cents a pound; 
December lean hogs rose .33 cent to 46.40 cents a pound; February 
frozen pork bellies rose .63 cent to 62.65 cents a pound. 
  	   	
