<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Financier Parretti Nabbed in Italy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ROME (AP) -- Italian financier Giancarlo Parretti, who engineered  
a takeover of Metro-Goldwin-Mayer in 1990, has been arrested 
pending an extradition request by the United States for a 
MGM-related case. 
</P>
<P>
	Parretti, 57, was taken into custody Monday in Orvieto, a  
hilltop town 70 miles north of Rome, police there said. 
</P>
<P>
	An Italian court must now decide whether Parretti should be  
detained until a hearing can be held on the extradition request. A 
decision was expected later this week, lawyer Francesco Caroleo 
Grimaldi was quoted as saying by Italian papers. 
</P>
<P>
	Parretti bought MGM in 1990 for $1.3 billion, using loans raised  
by French bank Credit Lyonnais. 
</P>
<P>
	After he defaulted on a $888 million loan, Credit Lyonnais  
seized the Hollywood studio and removed Parretti, accusing him of 
mismanagement -- a decision validated by a court in Delaware, where 
MGM is incorporated. 
</P>
<P>
	Parretti was later convicted in Delaware of perjury and evidence  
tampering, and fled the United States in January 1997, before he 
could be sentenced. 
</P>
<P>
	He has been in Italy ever since.  
</P>
<P>
	France is also seeking Parretti's extradition, after a court in  
Paris convicted him on corruption charges and sentenced him in 
absentia to four years in prison. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
