<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Tonya Harding Making Pro Debut </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) -- When Tonya Harding makes her professional  
debut next week at a small arena in West Virginia, she'll skate to 
the sounds of ZZ Top while wearing a turquoise and purple dress. 
</P>
<P>
	Harding is determined to have a little fun in her first  
competition since the 1994 Olympics in Lillehammer, and she doesn't 
particularly care whether it leads to any more offers. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm very excited that I got this second chance,'' she said  
Tuesday. ``If something comes from this, great, but if it doesn't, 
that's OK too. I take life day by day. I just want to go out there 
and have fun and skate well. Win or lose, it doesn't matter.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Harding, who turns 29 next month, will perform in the Pro  
Skating Championships in Huntington, W.Va., next Monday and 
Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Her adviser, Michael Rosenberg, said the event's promoter told  
him about one-third of the 5,780-seat Huntington Civic Arena's 
tickets have been sold, but that he expected a sellout by Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's not my concern how many tickets they sell in West  
Virginia, which is not skating territory,'' Rosenberg said. ``It's 
how many million people see it on ESPN.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The network will air the competition on tape delay Oct. 25, Nov.  
1 and Nov. 8. 
</P>
<P>
	Harding, implicated in a 1994 attack on rival skater Nancy  
Kerrigan, is banned for life from competing in an amateur event. 
But the U.S. Figure Skating Association has no jurisdiction over 
professional events. 
</P>
<P>
	Harding announced her comeback plans in February, but Rosenberg  
wasn't able to put together a deal. The big-ticket professional 
revues, and many skaters, had been leery of appearing on the same 
ice as her. 
</P>
<P>
	Harding is unfazed, saying she only skates for her fans now.  
</P>
<P>
	``I'm sure there's people who do not want me back in the skating  
world,'' she said. ``But that's their problem. Skating is my life. 
It's all I know.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Harding will skate the technical and artistic programs. Others  
entered in the competition include Surya Bonaly, Elizabeth Manley, 
Tonia Kwiatkowski and Pasha Grischuk. 
</P>
<P>
	Appearing on local talk shows, Harding looks fit and much more  
trim than she was in Lillehammer, where she finished eighth after a 
broken shoelace and the enormous pressure made her weep. 
</P>
<P>
	Kerrigan won the silver medal, just weeks after a shadowy thug  
whacked her on the knee during the U.S. Championships in Detroit. 
Harding later pleaded guilty to hindering prosecution, resulting in 
$160,000 in fines and 500 hours of community service. Her 
ex-husband and two other men served time in jail for planning the 
attack. 
</P>
<P>
	Other than practices at a local mall, Harding last skated in  
public in February 1997, during a two-minute exhibition between 
periods at a minor league hockey game in Reno, Nev. 
</P>
<P>
	Harding has turned down several other opportunities, including  
one to wrestle in Japan. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've had many, many offers to do things that for myself are  
not acceptable,'' she said. ``I've turned down things that were in 
the six-digit range because I have high morals and standards for 
myself.'' 
</P>
<P>
	As memories of her past fade, Harding also is becoming more  
accepted in her hometown. A recent practice session at the mall was 
met with some applause from the crowds that always gather to watch 
her. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was a 60-40 split,'' she said. ``It used to be zero.''  
</P>
<P>
	She said she's looking forward to the less-rigid structure of a  
pro event. Her odd musical selections range ZZ Top's heavy 
metal-tinged ``Sleeping Bag'' to David Sanborn to a song by a group 
called Funky Green Dogs. 
</P>
<P>
	``I picked out music that's very fun for me.''  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
