<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 7 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Tuesday, Oct. 12, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	Wilt Chamberlain Is Dead  
</P>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Wilt Chamberlain, the 7-foot-1 Hall of Famer  
who dominated the NBA in the 1960s, died today at 63, the Los 
Angeles Lakers said. Chamberlain's body was found by authorities 
called to his Bel-Air home shortly after noon PDT. He might have 
had a heart attack, according to a fire department spokesman. 
Called ``Wilt the Stilt,'' Chamberlain played from 1959 to 1973 for 
the Philadelphia (later the San Francisco) Warriors, the 
Philadelphia 76ers and the Lakers. He scored 31,419 points and 
averaged 30.1 points per game. He was named MVP and rookie of the 
year in 1959, and MVP from 1966 through 1968. 

</P>
<P>
	Military Ousts Pakistan PM  
</P>
<P>
	ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) -- Pakistani troops staged a coup  
against the democratically elected government Tuesday, seizing 
state-run media and confining the prime minister to his home in a 
move that raised tensions in the world's newest nuclear region. In 
a TV address, Army Chief Gen. Pervaiz Musharraf accused the 
government of ``systematically destroying'' state institutions and 
driving the economy toward collapse. Sharif was under apparent 
house arrest in Islamabad hours after he tried to fire Musharraf. 

</P>
<P>
	Nuclear Test Ban Is Debated  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Hopelessly outnumbered, Senate supporters of a  
global ban on nuclear testing mounted a last-ditch effort today to 
persuade majority-party Republicans to delay a vote on the pact. 
Republican leaders dashed cold water on one Democratic strategy. 
But efforts were advancing on several other fronts to come up with 
a plan for a delay that would save face for both sides without 
forcing a party-line vote. Trying to meet one Republican demand, 
the Democrats promised not to press again for Senate action on the 
Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty before 2001. The Republicans don't 
want the issue revived as presidential-year election issue. 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton: Help World's Poor  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton says the world's nations  
must work harder to erase the grinding poverty in which many people 
spend their lives. He was responding to estimates by the United 
Nations that the world's population hit the 6 billion mark. ``We 
must refuse to accept a future in which one part of humanity lives 
on the cutting edge of a new economy, while another part lives on 
the edge of survival,'' Clinton said. 

</P>
<P>
	U.S. Has $1 Billion Surplus  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The federal government ran a $1 billion  
surplus excluding Social Security in the last fiscal year, the 
Congressional Budget Office estimated today. It would be the first 
such surplus since 1960. The fiscal 1999 surplus would have been 
larger had congressional Republicans and President Clinton not 
agreed to $21 billion in ``emergency'' spending for defense and 
domestic programs, including $15 billion for Kosovo, aid to U.S. 
farmers. 

</P>
<P>
	Chemistry, Physics Nobels Awarded  
</P>
<P>
	STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) -- A U.S. scientist won the Nobel Prize  
for chemistry today for capturing ultrafast snapshots of atomic 
reactions. Ahmed H. Zewail, 53, of the California Institute of 
Technology was honored for using the rapid-fire laser flashes that 
illuminate the motion of atoms in a molecule, the Royal Swedish 
Academy of Sciences said. Two Dutch researchers, Gerardus 't Hooft 
and Martinus J.G. Veltman, won the Noble Prize for physics for 
refining the theory predicting the existence and behavior of 
sub-atomic particles. 

</P>
<P>
	Intel's 3Q Profits Up 21 Percent  
</P>
<P>
	SANTA CLARA, Calif. (AP) -- Intel Corp.'s third-quarter operating  
profit rose 21 percent, but the chipmaker's results were shy of 
forecasts. The world's largest manufacturer of semiconductors 
earned $1.9 billion, or 55 cents a share, in the three months ended 
Sept. 26, excluding one-time expenses related to acquisitions of 
other companies. It was a strong improvement from last year's 
third-quarter operating profit of $1.58 billion, or 45 cents a 
share, but 2 cents per share below expectations, according to 
analysts. 

</P>
<P>
