<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Farmers Hail The Great Pumpkin </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SYRACUSE, N.Y. (AP) -- The growing popularity of Halloween is  
turning into a treat for the New York state pumpkin industry. 
</P>
<P>
	The gourds are sold at roadside stands, farmers' markets,  
grocery stores and street corners. It's all added up to putting New 
York state on the pumpkin map as the No. 2 producer in the country. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a big cash crop nowadays,'' fruit and vegetable grower  
Paul Grisamore of Cayuga County told the Syracuse newspapers. 
``Everyone's raising them. We used to be the only one growing them 
... but Halloween's the fastest-growing holiday.'' 
</P>
<P>
	For farmers, pumpkins are easy to grow, require little  
attention, and add a cash crop just in time to help get the family 
through the winter. For dairy farmers, who have usually just 
finished getting the hay stored, and cash crop farmers like apple 
growers, pumpkin season offers another product for the market. 
</P>
<P>
	New York's drought this spring and summer did not hurt most  
pumpkin patches. Some farmers say their pumpkins are a bit smaller 
than average, but they generally look good. Prices range from 25 
cents a pound to $4 for picked pumpkins. 
</P>
<P>
	New York farmers planted 5,100 acres in pumpkins in 1997, an  
increase of 1,000 acres from 1992. It's now enough to make New York 
No. 2 after Illinois, according to the New York Agriculture and 
Markets Department's most recent statistics. 
</P>
<P>
	``Pumpkins are becoming more and more a popular commodity for  
New York state farm families,'' said Pete Gregg, a department 
spokesman. ``They're easy to grow and farmers are getting a good 
price.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Brian Sheils started growing and selling pumpkins about 10 years  
ago after some friends at Cornell University suggested he try. 
Sheils, a 1989 Cornell graduate, runs a roadside stand on his 
family farm near King Ferry in Cayuga County. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was a little skeptical, but it has turned into a  
moneymaker,'' Sheils said. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	GREENVILLE, N.H. (AP) -- While New Hampshire leaf-peepers argue  
whether the foliage is as good as it could be, there's no argument 
about another October touchstone -- pumpkins. 
</P>
<P>
	Growers say it's been a fine year, with the drought having no  
effect on the crop. 
</P>
<P>
	``The crop has been excellent. The drought didn't really effect  
it; we didn't even irrigate,'' said Mat McQuesten of his family's 
farm in Litchfield, echoing the comments of many area growers. 
</P>
<P>
	``The numbers are great, and the quality is right up there,'' he  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've got mega-pumpkins, '' said Windy Hill Orchard owner Tim  
Washburn. 
</P>
<P>
	A host of varieties is available, from jack-o'-lanterns to those  
destined for pies. 
</P>
<P>
	The crop is almost too good, especially with Canadian farmers  
``flooding the market,'' Washburn said. ``Because of that, we've 
got more than we can sell.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Leftovers will be fed to cattle or pigs, or harrowed back into  
the soil. 
</P>
<P>
	Farm stands in southern New Hampshire report that the season  
turned out fine for many fruits and vegetables despite the drought. 
</P>
<P>
	As for pumpkins, ``I don't think most people have an idea of all  
the different varieties available'' said Kris Mossey at McLeod's 
Farm in Milford. ``I like 'fat boys' myself. I just love the 
name,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	While most new varieties aim to make the pumpkin more popular in  
the kitchen, the University of New Hampshire recently developed a 
variety with seeds that can be eaten without being shelled. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
