<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-12 21:50:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Wall Street Plunge Affects Asia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- The overnight plunge on Wall Street took its toll  
on Asian markets early Wednesday, with exchanges from Japan to 
Australia opening sharply lower. 
</P>
<P>
	Traders attributed the stock swoons to a mix of reaction to the  
231.12-point dive in the Dow Jones industrial average on Tuesday 
and domestic economic conditions. 
</P>
<P>
	Market players, however, said the impact would be limited.  
</P>
<P>
	``The market is a little cautious today,'' said Woon Ha, a  
dealer at Daiwa Securities in Singapore. ``It's taking the U.S. 
market as a source of direction. The market will be a bit soft.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The losses in New York were dramatic. The Dow closed at  
10,417.06 in the average's 10th biggest point drop in history, and 
the steepest since May 27, when the blue-chip index fell 235.23 
points. 
</P>
<P>
	Broader stock indicators were also lower. The Standard and  
Poor's 500 fell 22.17 to 1,313.04, and the Nasdaq composite index 
fell 43.52 to 2,872.43, retreating from the new record close of 
2,915.95 set Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	That had an immediate impact in Asia. In Tokyo, the benchmark  
225-issue Nikkei Stock Average fell 253.69 points, or 1.40 percent, 
to 17,837.12 at the end of the morning session. 
</P>
<P>
	The Straits Times Index in Singapore was down 29.20 points, or  
1.38 percent, shortly after opening. Hong Kong blue chips also 
tumbled: by midmorning, the Hang Seng Index was off 2.1 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Concern about the dollar and bond prices helped drag down the  
market in New York. In Asia other factors were also at work, either 
adding to the depressing effect of Wall Street or acting to buoy 
stocks. 
</P>
<P>
	In Tokyo, the market was also pushed down by disappointment that  
the central bank will probably not act to blunt the advance of the 
yen against the dollar. 
</P>
<P>
	Many in Japan are worried that the strengthening yen could choke  
off a delicate economic recovery by making Japanese exports too 
expensive abroad. 
</P>
<P>
	Traders were also largely sidelined early Wednesday ahead of a  
Bank of Japan meeting later in the day. 
</P>
<P>
	``Investors have adopted a strong wait-and-see attitude,''  
Hidenori Karaki, general manager at Tokyo Mitsubishi-Personal 
Securities, said Wednesday morning. 
</P>
<P>
	In Taipei, shares recovered from a 38.61-point drop at the  
opening of the market when investors shrugged off the news from New 
York, snapping up low-priced plastics and paper issues to boost the 
Weighted Price Index of the Taiwan Stock Exchange 43.36 points, or 
0.6 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's rotational buying. We think shares of semiconductor  
makers will also outperform in coming sessions as the global 
semiconductor industry continues to recover,'' said Jessica Huang, 
manager at Jih Sun Securities Corp. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite the large point loss on Wall Street, traders in Asia  
showed signs of becoming accustomed to the Dow's volatility. 
</P>
<P>
	In Bangkok, Thai shares fell 1.8 percent at the market's  
opening, in reaction to the Dow and profit-taking from Tuesday's 
sharp 3 percent gain on the Stock Exchange of Thailand. 
</P>
<P>
	Traders expected the market to fall back to the level it was  
before climbing Tuesday to 401.36 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's certainly not panic,'' said Eric Holman of SG Asia  
Credit. ``It's that the market rebounded yesterday and we're giving 
up our gains. It's pretty muted.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
