<HEADLINE> Raytheon Reportedly Behind Schedule </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The defense firm Raytheon is behind schedule or  
over budget on at least a dozen fixed-price Pentagon orders, 
including orders for Tomahawk cruise missiles and reconnaissance 
aircraft, The Wall Street Journal reported today. 
</P>
<P>
	The company, based in Lexington, Mass., is responsible for any  
differences above the preset contract amounts unless the Pentagon 
agrees to amend the contracts. 
</P>
<P>
	Raytheon disclosed last month it was having difficulties in its  
defense electronics and construction units that will result in a 
third-quarter pretax charge of between $350 million and $450 
million. 
</P>
<P>
	Some of the Pentagon contracts are included in the charge,  
details of which Raytheon will reveal to financial analysts 
Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The Tomahawk, P-3 Orion patrol aircraft and RC-135  
reconnaissance aircraft programs are among the contracts running 
over cost, the Journal said, citing people familiar with the 
company. Other programs in trouble are the shoulder-held Javelin 
missile and a Navy satellite communications system. 
</P>
<P>
	The total value of the programs exceeds $2 billion, with the  
Javelin and Tomahawk programs accounting for about $750 million 
each. 
</P>
<P>
	A Raytheon spokeswoman declined to comment on details of  
meetings her company had with the Pentagon two weeks ago or on 
upcoming investor conferences. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
