<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Car Lease Down Payments Weighed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Q: I plan on leasing a car and the dealer is encouraging me to  
put more money down to lower my monthly payments. Is this a good 
idea? 

</P>
<P>
	A: Capital-cost reduction, as it's called, allows dealers to get  
more money up front, but it doesn't necessarily make sense for the 
consumer. 
</P>
<P>
	While it makes sense to put as much money down as you can afford  
when buying a car, that's not the case when leasing, says Jack 
Gillis, a spokesman for the Consumer Federation of America in 
Washington, D.C. 
</P>
<P>
	When buying, ``the more you put down up front, the less you'll  
pay in interest. That's a tangible benefit,'' he says. With a 
lease, the total cost is fixed up front anyway, he notes. 
</P>
<P>
	A down payment on a lease could put you at greater financial  
risk. 
</P>
<P>
	Should you wreck the car, not only would you lose the money you  
put down, but you also would be out a vehicle. Since you're 
essentially renting the car, your insurance would pay only the 
dealer if something happened to the car, Gillis says. 
</P>
<P>
	What is a reasonable amount to put down on a lease? ``Nothing,''  
Gillis says. 
</P>
<P>
	``The whole point is that the one benefit of leasing is you  
don't have to put anything down,'' he says. 
</P>
<P>
	Lin Peacock, executive director of dealership operations at the  
National Automobile Dealers Association in McLean, Va., agrees. 
</P>
<P>
	``That defeats the purpose of a lease to begin with, and it's  
not going to affect the monthly payment appreciably,'' he says. 
</P>
<P>
	For the consumer, that money could be put to better use either  
by investing it or putting it aside for a rainy day, Peacock and 
Gillis agree. 
</P>
<P>
	Gillis adds that if you negotiate the best deal on a lease,  
there should be no need to try to put down money up front to make 
the payments more affordable. 
</P>
<P>
	``One of the nice things about leasing, is basically you're just  
paying for depreciation on the car instead of paying principal and 
interest'' on a loan, he says. 
</P>
<P>
	That leads to another advantage of leasing: You can often get a  
more expensive car for what you would pay to buy a smaller or 
less-equipped car. That's because a luxury model retains more of 
its value, therefore the difference between what the car is worth 
when the lease begins and when it ends is less than it would be on 
a mid-priced car. 
</P>
<P>
	Although leasing means you'll always have car payments, it also  
means you can always have a car that's under warranty and can get a 
new car every three years, Peacock says. 
</P>
<P>
	Gillis says it's more prudent to buy the car rather than lease  
it. 
</P>
<P>
	``Leasing has all of the headaches and responsibility of car  
ownership, with none of the benefits,'' he says. ``If you can eke 
out a few extra dollars a month, at the end of the loan period you 
have a tangible asset -- you have a vehicle.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
