<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Tokyo Stocks Fall Sharply / Japanese Stocks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- The dollar was higher against the yen Wednesday  
morning as traders waited to see if the Bank of Japan would act to 
rein in the yen's recent strength. Tokyo stock prices fell sharply. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar traded at 106.34 yen at late morning, 0.06 yen above  
its level of 106.28 yen late Tuesday in Tokyo and also higher than 
106.31 yen in late New York trading Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average fell 253.69 points,  
or 1.40 percent, to 17,837.12 at the end of the morning session. 
The index closed up 28.63 points, or 0.16 percent, Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	In currency trading, the dollar moved higher on buying from  
Japanese institutional investors after having slipped earlier on 
selling by Japanese interbank dealers, they said. 
</P>
<P>
	But traders said the greenback's moves would be limited, pending  
the outcome of a Bank of Japan policy board meeting, which began 
Wednesday morning. 
</P>
<P>
	Market players, however, were not expecting that the central  
bank will increase the domestic money supply as one way of slowing 
the ascent of the yen, which has soared in recent months on 
optimism over Japan's budding economic recovery. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar has regained some ground since last month when  
finance ministers from major countries expressed concern about the 
yen's strength. But the gains have been limited due to market 
skepticism about the BOJ's ability to bring the yen back down. 
</P>
<P>
	Financial authorities fret that too steep a rise in the yen  
could derail economic recovery by reducing demand for Japanese 
goods abroad as a stronger currency makes them more expensive. 
Japan has been struggling to emerge from its worst economic 
downturn in 50 years. 
</P>
<P>
	In other currencies, the euro was trading at 114.62 yen, above  
its level of 113.37 yen late Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	In stock trading, share prices fell following a drop on Wall  
Street overnight caution over the BOJ policy meeting. 
</P>
<P>
	``Investors have adopted a strong wait-and-see attitude,'' said  
Hidenori Karaki, general manager at Tokyo Mitsubishi-Personal 
Securities. 
</P>
<P>
	Although investors largely expect the central bank to leave its  
zero interest rate policy unchanged, they remain worried about a 
further slide in New York, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	At the close of trading Tuesday in New York, the Dow Jones  
industrial average was down 231.12 points at 10,417.06 as traders, 
already anxious about interest rates, found themselves nervous 
about third-quarter earnings reports as well. 
</P>
<P>
	The broader Tokyo stock price index of all issues listed on the  
first section fell 16.20 points, or 1.05 percent, to 1,526.60. The 
TOPIX closed up 11.97 points, or 0.78 percent, on Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The yield on the benchmark 10-year Japanese government bond fell  
to 1.7900 percent from Tuesday's finish of 1.8000 percent. Its 
price rose 0.08 point to 99.22. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
