<HEADLINE> Norfolk Southern Forms subsidiary </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NORFOLK, Va. (AP) -- Norfolk Southern Corp. has formed a  
subsidiary to sell fiber-optic and microwave capacity to 
telecommunications companies along its 21,600-mile railway system. 
</P>
<P>
	Thoroughbred Technology and Telecommunications Inc., doing  
business as ``T-Cubed,'' will sell the bandwidth as a wholesaler to 
providers of telephone, Internet and cable TV service. 
</P>
<P>
	Like other railroad operators, the parent company of Norfolk  
Southern Railway holds valuable right-of-way agreements designed 
for trains and tracks, but also useful for ``shipping'' the digital 
traffic of an increasingly electronic economy. 
</P>
<P>
	Companies interested in sending voice, data, video and cable  
signals ``will be seeking ways to reach beyond the major 
metropolitan markets into regional centers and even smaller 
locations,'' Charles W. Moorman, president of T-Cubed, said 
yesterday. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
