<DOCNO> APW19991012.0165 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-12 17:00:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Davie, Irish Seniors Await USC </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SOUTH BEND, Ind. (AP) -- Bob Davie saw his share of rivalries as  
an assistant coach. 
</P>
<P>
	Texas-Texas A&AMP;M. Pitt-Penn State. Arizona-Arizona State.  
Tulane-LSU. 
</P>
<P>
	None, he says, compare to Notre Dame-Southern Cal.  
</P>
<P>
	``All of us have been involved in a lot of big games, certainly  
every week you play a big football game here. ... But I think this 
game is the biggest one I've been involved with in my coaching 
career,'' Davie said Tuesday as the Irish (3-3) prepared to play 
host to the Trojans (2-3) on Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	It's also been one of the most disappointing rivalries in  
Davie's three-year stint as Notre Dame's coach. Davie is 0-2 
against USC and his seniors are 0-3 as the Irish have gone 1-3-1 in 
their last five meetings. The only victory in that streak came 
while the fifth-year seniors were still freshmen and Davie was 
Notre Dame's defensive coordinator. 
</P>
<P>
	Even worse, each of those losses was devastating for the Irish.  
</P>
<P>
	In 1996, freshman kicker Jim Sanson missed the $8 million kick,  
an extra point attempt that would've put the Irish up by nine 
points with two minutes to play -- and likely led them to the Fiesta 
Bowl. 
</P>
<P>
	The miss allowed the Trojans to march the length of the field,  
tie the game with a touchdown and 2-point conversion, and win in 
overtime 27-20, ending Lou Holtz's career at Notre Dame with a loss 
and keeping the Irish away from the Fiesta's $8 million payout. 
</P>
<P>
	The next year, Sanson was just 1-of-4 on field goal attempts as  
the Irish lost 20-17. Last season, Notre Dame was blanked 10-0 with 
quarterback Jarious Jackson on the sideline after injuring his knee 
the week before. 
</P>
<P>
	The 1998 loss snapped an eight-game winning streak and kept the  
Irish from being considered for the Bowl Championship Series. 
</P>
<P>
	``You're talking about maybe having the opportunity to go to a  
BCS bowl game in both those occurrences,'' Davie said of the 1996 
and 1998 defeats. ``Those were devastating losses for us. ... This 
is a great rivalry if we hold up our end of the bargain and come 
out and play.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Jackson is healthy this year, and Sanson isn't kicking anymore  
after being benched for hitting just 3-of-9 field goal attempts 
this season. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, the games don't mean as much -- at least in terms of the  
BCS. The Irish have evened their record at 3-3 after a three-game 
slide to the Big Ten, a comeback 34-30 victory over Oklahoma and a 
dominating 48-17 defeat of Arizona State. 
</P>
<P>
	While the BCS bowls are out of reach, their Irish are still in  
good position to play somewhere in a bowl after their disastrous 
start. 
</P>
<P>
	Davie said the Irish have an extra incentive as well. The Irish  
have an open date next week that coincides with Notre Dame's fall 
break, meaning players will get to go home for the first time after 
staying at school all summer in preparation for the preseason Eddie 
Robinson Classic. 
</P>
<P>
	``It means a lot to us because we've scratched and clawed, and  
I'm proud of this football team for getting back to 3-3,'' Davie 
said. ``Now what do we do with that? We've finally dug ourselves 
somewhat out of that hole, we've got to where we can see the light 
a little bit, now what are we going to do?'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
