<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Senate Nears Deal on Tax Extension </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Senate Republicans and Democrats neared  
agreement Tuesday on a short extension of expiring business tax 
provisions, including the research and development tax credit 
backed by high-tech companies. 
</P>
<P>
	The emerging Senate Finance Committee compromise would extend  
most of the breaks through Dec. 31, 2000, at a cost of roughly $7.8 
billion, according to congressional sources who spoke on condition 
of anonymity. 
</P>
<P>
	That contrasts sharply with the 10-year, $75 billion proposal  
outlined last week by Finance Committee Chairman William Roth, 
R-Del., that would have made some of the breaks permanent. Roth's 
proposal encountered bipartisan resistance due to its cost and use 
of projected non-Social Security surpluses. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is more of a consensus toward moving to the shorter-term  
bill,'' said Sen. Don Nickles, R-Okla., the No. 2 Senate GOP leader 
and a Finance Committee member. 
</P>
<P>
	There is widespread sentiment that the Senate could never  
approve a large tax bill without encountering delaying tactics and 
dozens of crippling amendments. 
</P>
<P>
	Roth has met with Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan of New York, the  
committee's top Democrat, to work out a list of tax break 
extensions that can be paid for with a variety of revenue offsets. 
Democrats say they won't vote for any ``extenders'' bill that 
spends projected surpluses. 
</P>
<P>
	``They have to be paid for in the first year,'' said Senate  
Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss. ``What happens after that 
depends on how big it is.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The extensions, most of which were part of the 10-year, $792  
billion GOP tax cut vetoed by President Clinton, include credits 
for businesses that hire former welfare recipients and people from 
groups that have trouble holding jobs. In addition, middle-class 
taxpayers who claim personal credits would be protected from the 
complex alternative minimum tax for the upcoming tax filing season. 
</P>
<P>
	Whatever package the Senate produces would have to be reconciled  
with a $23.3 billion House version that renews many business 
credits for five years and permanently fixes the AMT problem. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
