<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Major Fed. Land Conservation Action </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Major federal land conservation actions:  
</P>
<P>
	--President Theodore Roosevelt adds 150 million acres to the  
national forest system and in 1905 establishes the U.S. Forest 
Service. National forests today cover 192 million acres. 
</P>
<P>
	--The National Park System is created under a single federal  
agency in 1916, covering about 7 million acres. Today the park 
system covers more than 360 units and some 80 million acres. 
</P>
<P>
	--Congress approves the Wilderness Act in 1964, creating the  
National Wilderness Preservation System and making the United 
States the first country to give legal protection to wild lands. 
Originally 9 million acres, federal wilderness today accounts for 
nearly 100 million acres. 
</P>
<P>
	--Congress enacts the Alaska Lands Act in 1980, setting aside  
under federal protection more than 100 million acres of Alaska land 
as parks, refuges and federal wilderness areas. 
</P>
<P>
	--President Clinton expected to direct that the U.S. Forest  
Service develop regulations to protect about 40 million acres of 
roadless federal forests from development. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
