<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Raytheon Slashes Expected Earnings </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- Shares of defense giant Raytheon Co. plunged more  
than 40 percent Tuesday after the contractor slashed its earnings 
projections for 1999 and 2000. 
</P>
<P>
	Blaming lower than-expected revenue, the defense contractor said  
Tuesday its 1999 earnings per share will be between $1.40 and $1.50 
per share -- including a $638 million pretax charge for 
restructuring and project problems. Excluding the charges, this 
year's earnings per share will be $2.70 to $2.80, well below Wall 
Street expectations of $3.56 per share. 
</P>
<P>
	For 2000, the company estimates earnings per share will be in  
the range of $2.10 to $2.25, compared to estimates of $3.91 per 
share. 
</P>
<P>
	Trading in shares of Raytheon was halted for most of the day on  
the New York Stock Exchange. After trading began in the late 
afternoon, Class B shares fell $18.75, or 44 percent, to close at 
$24.25. 
</P>
<P>
	Other defense contractors fell as well. General Dynamics fell  
$4.68 3/4 to $57.68 3/4 while Litton Industries fell $3.56 1/4 to $49.31 1/4. 
</P>
<P>
	Raytheon chairman and chief executive Daniel Burnham said the  
company lowered its revenue estimates by $600 million, to $200 
billion, due to increased competition and because it took longer 
for buyers to decide to buy defense systems. 
</P>
<P>
	Competition is lowering profit margins at Raytheon Systems Co.,  
its defense and electronics unit, from 15 percent to 12 percent, he 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	``What surprised us and shouldn't have,'' Burnham said, ``is how  
the business has shifted.'' He said aggressive bidding eliminated 
much of the company's gains from consolidation after its recent 
acquisitions, including General Motor's Hughes Defense Electronics. 
</P>
<P>
	Burnham also defended Raytheon against a Wall Street Journal  
report Tuesday that the company is behind schedule or over budget 
on at least a dozen fixed-price Pentagon orders, including orders 
for Tomahawk cruise missiles and reconnaissance aircraft. 
</P>
<P>
	He said there are contract problems with only eight projects,  
resulting in $320 million in charges. 
</P>
<P>
	The company is not taking a charge on the Tomahawk, the RC-135  
or the Javelin program, none of which have cost problems, Burnham 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	A Pentagon spokesman said Tuesday that Raytheon should not be  
singled out for having problems in meeting conditions of its 
contracts. 
</P>
<P>
	``I do not consider Raytheon a troubled contractor,'' Pentagon  
spokesman Ken Bacon said. ``Like all defense contractors, there are 
some contracts that are not always on schedule or within cost.'' 
</P>
<P>
	An industry analyst said Raytheon, like the rest of the defense  
industry, is seeing lower earnings growth because cost savings due 
to consolidations have already been realized. 
</P>
<P>
	``What Raytheon is going through is perfectly natural,'' said  
Jon Kutler, an analyst with Quarterdeck Investment Partners. 
``Historically it's been one of the best managed defense aerospace 
companies.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Raytheon, he said, is extremely well-positioned in the growth  
areas of electronics and missiles. ``Investors who truly understand 
this industry will look past this and at the very attractive 
opportunities handed Raytheon,'' Kutler added. 
</P>
<P>
	Raytheon is predicting annual revenue growth for 1999 and 2000  
of 3 percent, at least half of its earlier projections of 6 percent 
to 8 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Restructuring charges account for another $274 million and $74  
million in special charges will be taken, primarily to write down 
company assets to fair-market value such as the company's wireless 
networking inventory and its investment in troubled satellite 
mobile phone company Iridium. 
</P>
<P>
	Raytheon disclosed last month it was having difficulties in its  
defense electronics and construction units that would result in a 
third-quarter pretax charge of between $350 million and $450 
million. 
</P>
<P>
	Burnham said there will be some more layoffs of the company's  
108,000 employees worldwide, though how many more is unclear. At 
least 2,380 positions will be eliminated, with possibly a couple 
hundred more, largely in California and New York state with some in 
Texas. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
