<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AOL, Universal Form Alliance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- America Online, the world's largest Internet  
service provider, has formed a marketing alliance with Universal 
Studios that will offer online services to theme park visitors, the 
companies announced Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	As part of the agreement, five Internet kiosks that use AOL  
software are to be installed shortly at the Islands of Adventure 
theme park in Orlando, Fla., Universal spokeswoman Hellene Runtagh 
said. They could be added to other parks later. 
</P>
<P>
	AOL members can use the kiosks to send and receive e-mail and  
browse other online content, said AOL spokesman Joe Redling. 
</P>
<P>
	Visitors can also use the free computer access to scan for  
information about the park and local travel, as well as products 
from Universal Studios. 
</P>
<P>
	``Some of the consumers in the park will be clients of AOL and  
others will not,'' Ms. Runtagh said. ``The purpose of the project 
is to entertain them and get them to be permanent subscribers.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In exchange for installing the kiosks, AOL will promote  
Universal products and services to its nearly 18 million 
subscribers, she said. 
</P>
<P>
	The marketing alliance was designed to see whether  
cross-promotion will be more successful in reaching new customers 
than standard advertising, the companies said. 
</P>
<P>
	``The kiosk program ... is a natural fit, aligning our online  
service with the world's most technologically advanced theme 
park,'' Redling said in a statement. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
