<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Braves Want To Avoid a Near-Miss </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- The Atlanta Braves have seen this picture once  
too often. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year, the San Diego Padres took a snapshot on the mound at  
Turner Field after winning the NL pennant. The previous October, 
the Florida Marlins posed for the same portrait. 
</P>
<P>
	Easy to see why the Braves are focused on not letting the New  
York Mets take a similar photo this time. 
</P>
<P>
	``We certainly don't want to be known as the Buffalo Bills of  
the '90s,'' reliever John Rocker said before Game 1 of the NLCS. 
</P>
<P>
	Of course, that label has been liberally applied to Atlanta in  
the past. 
</P>
<P>
	The Braves have been the majors' biggest winners in the regular  
season since 1991 -- with 860 victories, they're 76 ahead of the New 
York Yankees -- but they have only one World Series championship to 
show for it. 
</P>
<P>
	Instead, they can lament a string of near-misses.  
</P>
<P>
	If Lonnie Smith doesn't get lost on the bases, maybe they beat  
Jack Morris and the Minnesota Twins in Game 7 in 1991. 
</P>
<P>
	If Jeff Reardon doesn't give up a ninth-inning homer to Ed  
Sprague in Game 2, maybe they go on to defeat Toronto in 1992. 
</P>
<P>
	And if Mark Wohlers doesn't hang that breaking ball to Jim  
Leyritz in Game 4, maybe they beat the Yankees in 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	Instead, they're still searching for that elusive second title.  
Their fans are waiting, too. 
</P>
<P>
	The Braves had plenty of tickets left for the first two games of  
the NLCS as Tuesday night's opener in the best-of-7 series 
approached. Though they've reached the NLCS eight straight times, 
home sellouts have been rare. 
</P>
<P>
	``I tell you, it's surprising,'' Atlanta outfielder Brian Jordan  
said. ``I've been spoiled because I've been in St. Louis for the 
last six years, and they're true baseball fans. Win, lose or draw, 
they're always there. 
</P>
<P>
	``And to come here and be in a postseason and don't have a  
sellout crowd is surprising,'' he said. ``I know they are used to 
the Atlanta Braves winning, but not winning the big game.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Manager Bobby Cox hopes to end that trend this fall. Especially  
after seeing other teams celebrate on the Turner Field mound the 
last two years. 
</P>
<P>
	Having beaten Houston in the division series, the NL East  
champions continue their quest in this recently troublesome second 
round. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't know what you can learn from them,'' he said. ``We've  
won some and we've lost some. I don't know if you learn from 
winning or learn from losing. 
</P>
<P>
	``Hopefully, we'll have a little luck,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	The Braves sure could use some, having lost Andres Galarraga,  
Javy Lopez, Kerry Ligtenberg and others to illness and injuries. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think a lot of people have been doubting us from the  
beginning,'' Rocker said. ``And in past years, people have just 
been penciling us into the World Series back in May. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think we really got that treatment this year,'' he  
said. ``I think we don't have quite as much to prove.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
