<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-12 01:20:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Nurses Welcome New California Law </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) -- Every day, nurse Julie Meylor  
struggles to balance the care of her ailing patients with the staff 
levels in her cardiac surgery unit. 
</P>
<P>
	The workload is steadily rising, and there is never enough time  
or nurses for all who need them, said Meylor, 42, who has 18 years 
experience in nursing. 
</P>
<P>
	``A lot of tempers flare. People yell at you. That happens every  
day,'' she said. ``The crises get taken care of, but the basic 
stuff is put on hold, and patients expect that the basics get 
done.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Proponents of a new law say they have the medicine for Meylor's  
staffing problems: Legislation that makes California the first 
state to require all its licensed hospitals to meet fixed 
nurse-to-patient ratios. 
</P>
<P>
	Nurses like Meylor at Mercy General Hospital in Sacramento  
cheered news that Gov. Gray Davis had signed the law over the 
weekend. She said it will mean more nurses, less tension and better 
care. 
</P>
<P>
	Kay McVey, president of the California Nurses Association, which  
sponsored the bill, described Davis' signing as ``one of the most 
significant days in the history of nursing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	At the American Hospital Association in Washington, D.C.,  
spokeswoman Alicia Mitchell said that the bill ``is the first of 
its type in the nation.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But opponents of the measure argued that each hospital should  
make its own staffing decisions and that state intervention would 
only drive up treatment costs in an era of HMOs -- and even reduce 
care. 
</P>
<P>
	The California Healthcare Association, which represents 460 of  
the state's 470 hospitals, said the bill will only make it harder 
to maintain quality levels. 
</P>
<P>
	``We believe the quality of care is very high in California  
hospitals,'' said Doris Harms, vice president of the hospital 
association. She said she was unaware of overextended staffs or 
nurses. 
</P>
<P>
	``But if that's true, this bill isn't going to help that,''  
Harms added. ``There are no more nurses available to hire. What 
hospitals will have to do is close some units'' to increase 
staffing in others and reduce patient access to services. 
</P>
<P>
	Current California regulations require each hospital to assess  
the needs of patients during every shift and then set their nurse 
staffing levels accordingly. The state sets nurse-patient ratios 
only for critical care units and neonatal intensive care units. 
</P>
<P>
	The new law does not specify a minimum nurse-to-patient ratio,  
but instead requires the state Department of Health Services to set 
such standards. 
</P>
<P>
	The measure also will bar hospitals from assigning unlicensed  
workers to perform certain procedures, including administering 
medication, and it will prohibit hospitals from shifting nurses 
trained in one unit to another unit without adequate preparation. 
</P>
<P>
	Assemblywoman Sheila Kuehl, D-Los Angeles, sponsored the  
legislation and agreed to postpone the date at which it goes into 
effect until Jan. 1, 2002, in order to give hospitals a chance to 
adjust. 
</P>
<P>
	At Los Angeles County-USC Medical Center, the nation's largest  
teaching hospital, nurse Juanita Jones said the nursing bill would 
be welcomed by those who perform medical triage every day. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's past way overdue,'' said Jones, 46, who cares for  
patients who have undergone surgery. She said her workload -- which 
can soar to nine patients at a time -- is tremendous. 
</P>
<P>
	``They have to cut it down,'' Jones said. She said it would be  
more manageable in her department if each nurse had to care for 
four patients at a time. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's always the issue here. We have a lot of patients,'' said  
Ghennet Haile, 32, dialysis nurse at County-USC for six years. 
``It's stressful and patients don't get as much care.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
