<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-12 12:40:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Supreme Court Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	The Supreme Court took these actions Tuesday:  
</P>
<P>
	--Left intact Maine's policy of subsidizing children who attend  
private, non-religious schools while denying public money for 
children who go to religious schools. 
</P>
<P>
	--Refused to let Pennsylvania exempt religious publications from  
the state's sales tax. 
</P>
<P>
	--Rejected New York's effort to revive a public school district  
for disabled children in a Hasidic Jewish community. 
</P>
<P>
	--Let stand the conviction and life sentence of Terry Nichols in  
the 1995 Oklahoma City bombing. 
</P>
<P>
	--Agreed to review Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr's attempt to  
preserve Webster Hubbell's guilty plea to a misdemeanor tax charge. 
</P>
<P>
	--Said it would decide the legitimacy of the Clinton  
administration's regulation of livestock grazing on millions of 
acres of federal land in Western states. 
</P>
<P>
	--Agreed to use a Texas case to decide whether police are  
conducting a search, and must comply with constitutional 
requirements, when they feel someone's luggage to determine if 
drugs might be inside. 
</P>
<P>
	--Voted to decide in another Texas case whether public employees  
who agree to take extra time off instead of collecting overtime pay 
can be forced to use the time off at the employer's convenience. 
</P>
<P>
	--Rejected two efforts to assert a personal and constitutionally  
protected right to own a gun. In one case, two Louisiana men were 
barred from owning hunting rifles because they were convicted of 
nonviolent tax crimes. Also left intact was a federal ban on 
anyone, including police officers, possessing a gun after a 
domestic-violence conviction. 
</P>
<P>
	--Rejected a Georgia killer's appeal, turning away an effort  
aimed at forcing states to provide free lawyers for some death row 
inmates after their first round of appeals. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
