<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Spurs' Robinson Enjoying Anonymity </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MILAN, Italy (AP) -- David Robinson is enjoying the rare taste of  
anonymity he's getting in Milan. 
</P>
<P>
	``Being 7 feet tall, you can't hide,'' the San Antonio Spurs  
center said with a laugh, ``but I walked around for four or five 
hours today and I only was asked for four or five autographs. 
That's a lot different from being in the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a nice break.''  
</P>
<P>
	Robinson and his Spurs teammates arrived in Milan on Tuesday for  
what for them should be a nice break from the NBA preseason -- the 
McDonald's Championship. 
</P>
<P>
	While there have been some close calls, NBA teams boast a  
combined 16-0 record in the tourney's 12-year history. 
</P>
<P>
	This year's six-team field includes the NBA, European, South  
American, Asian and Australian champions, plus the Italian League 
titlist. 
</P>
<P>
	In Italy, basketball is second -- albeit a distant second -- in  
popularity to soccer, and as of Tuesday there were still hundreds 
of tickets left for Thursday's first-round games at the 
10,122-capacity FilaForum on the outskirts of Milan. 
</P>
<P>
	San Antonio has a bye into Friday's semifinals, where it will  
meet the winner of Thursday's game between Brazil's Vasco da Gama 
and Australia's Adelaide 36ers. The other teams are European 
champions Zalgiris Kaunas, Lebanon's C.S. Sagesse and Italy's 
Varese Roosters. 
</P>
<P>
	The final is Saturday.  
</P>
<P>
	``It's tough in the middle of training camp to fly across the  
world,'' said Robinson, the 1995 NBA MVP. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've only been together for a week and right now we have to  
be working on getting ourselves going.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The NBA bills the event as deciding the best club in the world,  
but Spurs forward Tim Duncan views these games as a way for his 
team to ease into a title defense. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're going to use these games over here to get better,'' last  
June's NBA Finals MVP said. ``These are like preseason games for 
us. We have to use them to get ready for the real season. We want 
to get a lot of people on the floor.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Coach Greg Popovich acknowledged he knows little about the  
Spurs' potential opponents here, but said his aim this week will be 
``getting our big people involved in the game.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Only Lithuanian club Zalgiris Kaunas, with George Zidek (a  
member of UCLA's 1995 NCAA champions) and Eurelijus Zukauskas 
(whose NBA rights are owned by the Milwaukee Bucks), has two big 
men that could hope to clog the middle against San Antonio's pair 
of 7-footers, Duncan and Robinson. 
</P>
<P>
	``Basketball has obviously improved around the world, but the  
players are a little bit smaller,'' said Spurs guard Avery Johnson, 
who at 5-foot-11 is short by NBA standards. 
</P>
<P>
	``In fact,'' he quipped, ``I may even find somebody out here my  
size.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
