	------	 
</P>
<P>
	HENDERSON, Nev. (AP) -- Fifth-grader Christopher Hoch waited all  
of Tuesday morning to ask Vice President Al Gore what his middle 
name is. But when the big moment came, mum was the word from the 
Democratic presidential candidate. 
</P>
<P>
	Gore toured Roberta C. Cartwright Elementary School in this Las  
Vegas suburb to talk up his plan to put more teachers in classrooms 
and to reduce class sizes. 
</P>
<P>
	After he spent nearly 45 minutes talking with parents and  
teachers, Christopher decided he couldn't wait any longer. 
</P>
<P>
	``What's your middle name?'' he asked.  
</P>
<P>
	Instead of answering, Gore asked Christopher for his full name.  
Gore either didn't hear Christopher or didn't want to reveal his 
middle name. Press aides and Secret Service agents later said they 
didn't know what it was either. 
</P>
<P>
	For the record, it's Arnold.  
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	COLUMBIA, S.C. (AP) -- The Republican battle for South Carolina  
has begun. 
</P>
<P>
	GOP presidential candidates George W. Bush and Sen. John McCain  
both claimed Tuesday to have been the first to build a statewide 
organization here. 
</P>
<P>
	Both said they did it first.  
</P>
<P>
	McCain issued an announcement at about 8:30 a.m.; Bush, the  
governor of Texas, followed with a statement just before 6 p.m. 
</P>
<P>
	``Far and away it was us. They reacted to our release,'' said  
Jim Merrill, McCain's state campaign director. 
</P>
<P>
	First or not, Bush's campaign said it has signed up 10,000  
volunteers statewide, including 500 last weekend at the state fair, 
said state director Heath Thompson. 
</P>
<P>
	``I just think it shows the tremendous support that he has  
here,'' Thompson said. 
</P>
<P>
	Merrill said his group has 4,000 people signed up. McCain has  
said South Carolina and New Hampshire are do-or-die states in his 
pursuit of the GOP nomination. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, GOP presidential candidate Elizabeth Dole plans to  
open her state campaign headquarters on Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	South Carolina will hold its first-in-the South GOP primary Feb.  
19. 
  	   	
</P>
