<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Assemblywoman Leaves Green Party </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	OAKLAND, Calif. (AP) -- Citing a need for campaign cash, a woman  
who stunned the political establishment when she won election to 
the state Assembly as a candidate of the Green Party has quit the 
party and will seek re-election as an independent. 
</P>
<P>
	The decision by Assemblywoman Audie Bock, who had been the Green  
Party's highest-ranking elected official in the nation, means she 
can skip the March 7 primary next year. As an independent, she will 
win a spot on the November general election ballot if she collects 
signatures of 5,677 registered voters in her Oakland-based 
district. 
</P>
<P>
	The deadline in state law for her to give up her Green Party  
affiliation and become eligible to file as an independent was last 
week. Bock made her decision Thursday and told party members 
Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	Running in a runoff special election in March, Bock narrowly  
defeated the Democratic nominee, former Oakland Mayor Elihu Harris, 
who had held the 16th Assembly District seat for 12 years before 
his election as mayor in 1990. 
</P>
<P>
	Bock did not immediately respond to messages seeking comment  
left at her Oakland and Sacramento offices today by The Associated 
Press. 
</P>
<P>
	Greg Jan, a member of the Green Party's Alameda County Council,  
said it was known within party circles that Bock was concerned 
about the party's ability to raise the kind of money it would take 
to run a serious campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	Her first campaign was run on a shoestring. But Green Party  
members said she told them she could not make a reasonable 
re-election bid for less than $250,000. Bock's most recent campaign 
finance report, filed last June, showed she had $7,090 on hand. 
</P>
<P>
	``Given the pressures, the winner-take-all voting system in this  
country and big money campaigns, she did what she felt she had to 
do,'' Jan said. 
</P>
<P>
	Bock, who often votes with the Democratic majority, has  
acknowledged it isn't easy being Green. Elected after the 
Legislature's deadline for introducing bills this year, she has 
pushed unsuccessfully for universal health care, a bigger increase 
in school funding, more vigorous enforcement of environmental laws 
and more money for mass transit. 
</P>
<P>
	Her party is similar in philosophy to Green parties in various  
European countries, sharing goals such as feminism, decentralized 
authority, nonviolence and environmental consciousness. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
