<DOCNO> APW19991012.0198 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-12 16:20:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Irvin Injury Gives Rookie a Chance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	IRVING, Texas (AP) -- The play that opened a spot in the Dallas  
Cowboys' lineup for Wane McGarity brought tears to his eyes. And 
they weren't ones of joy. 
</P>
<P>
	The rookie receiver was frightened Sunday when he saw teammate,  
friend and mentor Michael Irvin lay motionless after being tackled 
by the Philadelphia Eagles. 
</P>
<P>
	McGarity was inactive for the game and opted to watch it at his  
mother's home in San Antonio. He saw Irvin catch a pass for an 
8-yard gain, then turned away from the television after the tackle. 
He looked back at the screen and Irvin was still down. 
</P>
<P>
	``Move! Move! Move something so I know you're OK,'' McGarity  
screamed, his eyes filling with tears. 
</P>
<P>
	McGarity prayed and worried for hours until learning Irvin would  
be OK. His spinal cord is swollen and he has a herniated disc, but 
he's expected to play again this season. 
</P>
<P>
	On Monday, coaches told McGarity they're counting on him to pick  
up some of the slack in Irvin's absence. It's quite a promotion for 
a fourth-round draft pick who has dropped both passes thrown to him 
and has been inactive the last two games. 
</P>
<P>
	But coaches saw enough from McGarity in the preseason to give  
them confidence in the former University of Texas receiver. Even 
quarterback Troy Aikman, a tough critic, has raved about the 
5-foot-8 McGarity. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think he is right where he was when training camp ended,''  
Dallas coach Chan Gailey said. ``He had a few drops in the Atlanta 
game, but overall he's played pretty good. He made some big plays 
in the preseason, and we're hoping he can pick up right where he 
left off.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ernie Mills will start opposite Raghib Ismail, but McGarity also  
will see action there. When the Cowboys go with three or four 
receivers, Mills likely will go to his usual spot and McGarity will 
take Irvin's place. 
</P>
<P>
	McGarity wondered what the Cowboys thought of him when he was  
made inactive before the Arizona game. 
</P>
<P>
	``I went home that day and thought about what could I have  
possibly done. In talking to people, I don't think I did anything 
wrong,'' McGarity said. 
</P>
<P>
	The problem was a numbers game. McGarity was active the first  
two weeks because he was needed to catch punts, not passes. With 
Deion Sanders healthy and able to return punts, McGarity was 
replaced by Jason Tucker, another reserve receiver who plays on 
various kick coverage units. 
</P>
<P>
	Hearing the explanation from coaches was one thing. Hearing it  
from someone like Irvin was much more reassuring. 
</P>
<P>
	``Mike's been a big part of my adjustment to the NFL,'' McGarity  
said. ``I went through a rough time being inactive and he was one 
of the guys who kept my head up. He came to me and told me not to 
worry about it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	McGarity began watching Irvin and copying his practice habits  
during training camp. He eventually got the courage to ask Irvin 
for advice. A friendship blossomed quickly. 
</P>
<P>
	``He puts something in you,'' McGarity said. ``You don't know  
what it is, but you just want to go out there and compete. You want 
to go out and do your best because that's how he is.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The next pass McGarity catches will be his first in the NFL.  
Even though he's rusty from not playing much and hardly practicing 
the past month, he's ready for this opportunity. 
</P>
<P>
	``I feel like I'm a quick learner,'' McGarity said. ``I can go  
out there and adjust real quick. 
</P>
<P>
	If things don't work out right away, McGarity will have the  
confidence to continue. All he has to do is fall back on something 
Irvin often tells him: ``Always, always keep working hard, keep 
going out there and trying to do the things you can do, and don't 
let anybody tell you different.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
