<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 2 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Tuesday, Oct. 12, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	Pakistani Prime Minister Dismissed  
</P>
<P>
	ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) -- Pakistani Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif  
and his Cabinet have been dismissed, army-controlled television 
said today. Troops took control of airports and government 
buildings throughout the country. The ouster means that army chief 
Gen. Pervaiz Musharraf, who had been fired hours before by Sharif, 
likely would be the country's new leader. He will address the 
nation in a broadcast speech. Pakistani troops took over state-run 
TV and radio stations when Sharif surprisingly fired Musharraf 
while the army chief was visiting Sri Lanka. In recent weeks there 
have been reports of a rift between the army and the civilian 
government. 

</P>
<P>
	Wyo. Gay Slaying Defense: Drugs  
</P>
<P>
	LARAMIE, Wyo. (AP) -- Attorneys for a man accused of beating a  
gay student to death do not dispute Aaron McKinney's role in the 
killing, but say drugs and alcohol spurred his actions. Attorney 
Dion Custis told prospective jurors that McKinney's use of those 
substances would be a core part of his defense in the trial of the 
murder of Matthew Shepard. Jury selection continued today in the 
case. McKinney, 22, could face the death penalty if convicted of 
Shepard's murder. His alleged co-conspirator, Russell Henderson, is 
already serving a life sentence after pleading guilty to felony 
murder and kidnapping in the beating of Shepard. 

</P>
<P>
	Court To Decide Overtime Issue  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Supreme Court today agreed to decide  
whether public employees who agree to take extra time off instead 
of overtime pay can be forced to use the time off at the employer's 
convenience. The court voted to hear arguments by more than 120 
Harris County, Texas, sheriff's deputies that they -- not their 
government employer -- have the right to control when such time-off 
credits are used. The Fair Labor Standards Act generally requires 
public and private employees to be paid time-and-one-half if they 
work more than 40 hours a week. Since 1985, the law has let public 
employees agree to take compensatory time off instead of overtime 
pay. 

</P>
<P>
	Physics, Chemistry Nobels Awarded  
</P>
<P>
	STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) -- A U.S. scientist won the Nobel Prize  
for chemistry today for capturing ultrafast snapshots of atomic 
reactions. Two Dutch researchers won the physics prize for refining 
the theory predicting the existence and behavior of some of the 
smallest particles in the universe. Ahmed H. Zewail, 53, of the 
California Institute of Technology was honored for pioneering a 
revolution in chemistry by using the rapid-fire laser flashes that 
illuminate the motion of atoms in a molecule as they occur. Dutch 
scientists Gerardus 't Hooft and Martinus J.G. Veltman took the 
physics prize. 

</P>
<P>
	German Pays Fine in Iran Sex Case  
</P>
<P>
	DUBAI, United Arab Emirates (AP) -- A German businessman who  
previously had been sentenced to death on charges of having illegal 
sex paid a fine today, closing his case and removing the biggest 
hurdle to his release from prison. It was not clear, however, when 
Helmut Hofer would be freed because he faces a string of other 
charges, including espionage and insulting a prison officer. Hofer 
was acquitted last month of charges of illegal sex, for which he 
was twice sentenced to death for having sex with a Muslim woman. 
Under Iranian law, sex outside marriage is punishable by flogging, 
but if the man is not a Muslim, he faces the death penalty. 

</P>
<P>
	Lorillard Announces Anti-Smoke Plan  
</P>
<P>
	GREENSBORO, N.C. (AP) -- Lorillard Tobacco is launching a  
nationwide youth smoking-prevention program in addition to the one 
included in the industry's $206 billion settlement with 46 states. 
The program urges parents to talk to their children about not 
smoking and includes national print and broadcast announcements, 
Web sites and a multi-city tour. Cigarette giant Philip Morris 
sponsored a similar program earlier this year that critics said 
lacked credibility with children. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Down 122  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Just before 2 p.m. EDT, the Dow industrials were  
down 122.21 to 10,525.97. Declining issues on the New York Stock 
Exchange led advancers 1,967-910. The Nasdaq was down 10.45 to 
2,905.50. 

</P>
<P>
	Philippoussis Wins at Heineken Open  
</P>
<P>
	SINGAPORE (AP) -- Mark Philippoussis, playing for the first time  
since hurting his knee in August, defeated Bob Bryan 6-4, 6-4 today 
in the first round of the Heineken Open. The injury forced the 
hard-serving Australian to miss the U.S. Open. In other matches, 
Sweden's Jonas Bjorkman, seeded No. 8, defeated Australia's Richard 
Fromberg 7-5 6-2. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by VINCENT CINISOMO  



  	   	
