<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> India Encourages Telecom Activity </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	GENEVA (AP) -- India's new government will encourage foreign  
participation in the development of its telecommunications network, 
an official said Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Contracts for building domestic long-distance networks will be  
put up for bid on Jan. 1 and foreign companies are welcome to 
participate, said Anil Kumar, secretary of the Department of 
Telecommunications, speaking at the Telecom 99 industry fair. 
</P>
<P>
	More network operating partnerships are envisioned over the next  
five years on a revenue-sharing basis, Kumar said, adding that new 
wireline and wireless licenses will be offered once a review is 
completed by the Telecom Regulatory Authority of India. 
</P>
<P>
	India is looking to provide telephone service to the 250,000  
villages in the country that aren't connected to any telecom 
network. 
</P>
<P>
	The agency has been talking to satellite system operators as one  
means of bringing service to the 250,000 villages. But they may 
need government subsidies since operators wouldn't be able to 
charge consumers more than cellular services do. 
</P>
<P>
	Atal Bihari Vajpayee was named India's prime minister Monday and  
said his National Democratic Alliance will speed up economic 
reforms, an assurance that buoyed the stock market. 
</P>
<P>
	The vote count last week showed the alliance collecting support  
from more than 300 legislators, enough to form a stable government 
and perhaps complete a full five-year term. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
