<HEADLINE> Europe: Dollar, Gold Both Lower </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- The U.S. dollar fell against most other major  
currencies in European trading today. Gold prices also were lower. 
</P>
<P>
	The euro was quoted at $1.0642 in European trading, up from  
$1.0636 Monday. Later, in midday trading in New York, the euro 
traded at $1.0735. 
</P>
<P>
	Other dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Monday,  
included 106.23 Japanese yen, down from 106.69; 1.4832 Swiss 
francs, down from 1.4988; 1.4744 Canadian dollars, up from 1.4709. 
</P>
<P>
	The British pound was quoted at $1.6534, down from $1.6549.  
</P>
<P>
	In midday trading in New York, the dollar bought 106.22 yen and  
the pound was worth $1.6542. 
</P>
<P>
	Currencies of the 11 countries participating in the euro are no  
longer traded separately, though they remain in use. Based on euro 
rates, the dollar is worth 1.8219 German marks, down from 1.8389; 
6.1105 French francs, down from 6.1673; 2.0528 Dutch guilders, down 
from 2.0719; 1,803.70 Italian lire, down from 1,820. 49. 
</P>
<P>
	Gold closed in London at $318.50 bid per troy ounce, down from  
$318.60 on Monday. In Zurich the bid price was $317.30, down from 
$318.00. Gold rose $5.0 in Hong Kong to close at $323.50 . 
</P>
<P>
	Silver closed in London at $5.57 bid per troy ounce, down from  
$5.59. 
  	   	
</P>
