<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Jitney Jungle Files Under Ch. 11 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	JACKSON, Miss. (AP) -- Jitney-Jungle Stores of America Inc. filed  
for federal bankruptcy protection today in U.S. Bankruptcy Court in 
Delaware. 
</P>
<P>
	The Chapter 11 filing will let the Jackson-based supermarket  
chain reorganize its capital structure and focus on strengthening 
its overall operations and financial position, company officials 
said Today. 
</P>
<P>
	Jitney-Jungle operates 196 supermarkets, 10 liquor stores and 55  
gasoline stations in Mississippi, Alabama, Louisiana, Tennessee, 
Florida and Arkansas. 
</P>
<P>
	Jitney-Jungle president and CEO Ron Johnson said that the  
company was able to obtain a $260 million financing agreement from 
a consortium of lenders led by BT Commercial Corp. 
</P>
<P>
	Pending approval by the court, that money will be used by  
Jitney-Jungle to retire a $150 million revolving credit facility 
and give it enough liquidity to meet all of its current inventory 
needs and fulfill operating obligations. 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson said the filing won't mean a closing of stores or  
layoffs. 
</P>
<P>
	As a result of the filing, Jitney-Jungle hired Jay Alix &AMP;  
Associates to serve as its crisis management and corporate 
turnaround expert. 
</P>
<P>
	Michael Feder of Jay Alix will serve as chief restructuring  
officer and chief administrative officer of Jitney-Jungle during 
the bankruptcy protection period. 
</P>
<P>
	Jitney had earnings of $117 million on about $2 billion in sales  
last year and has faced increasing competition from Albertson's, 
Kroger, Winn Dixie and Wal-Mart in recent years. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
