<P>
	European Stocks Close Lower  
</P>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- European stocks closed lower today, with  
telecommunications shares dragging down Milan's market and the 
French market hurt by the performance of the specialty chemicals 
group Rhodia. The Paris CAC-40 index closed down 1.4 percent to 
4,658.4 and Milan's MIBtel index fell 1.6 percent to 33,195, making 
them among the day's worst performing bourses. London's FTSE 100 
index of leading blue-chip shares fell 1 percent, to close at 
6,174.8. The Dow Jones Stoxx Index of 614 European companies fell 
3.53 points, or 1.1 percent, 309.62. The Dow Jones Euro Stoxx 
Index, which tracks 310 companies in countries that joined the 
single currency, closed down 3.10 points at 324.65. 

</P>
<P>
	Brit Air Chooses Pratt &AMP; Whitney  
</P>
<P>
	EAST HARTFORD, Conn., (AP) -- British Airways has selected a  
Pratt &AMP; Whitney engine for its new Airbus Industrie A318 aircraft, 
a deal worth more than $300 million. The airline selected Pratt's 
PW6000 engine for the new planes. British Airways has a firm order 
for 12 A318s and an option on 12 more with deliveries beginning in 
January 2003 as part of its effort to revamp its aging fleet. Pratt 
&AMP; Whitney Engine Services also was selected to provide a long-term 
fleet management program for the engines. 

</P>
<P>
	Northwest Denies Sun Country Access  
</P>
<P>
	EAGAN, Minn. (AP) -- Northwest Airlines has decided to stop  
letting Sun Country Airlines use its emergency training facilities, 
forcing the smaller Minnesota-based rival to scramble for 
alternative ways to provide federally mandated training for flight 
attendants and pilots. Sun Country had paid Northwest $250,000 a 
year during the past five years for the training, which teaches 
pilots and flight attendants how to exit aircraft in emergency 
situations. The two airlines are competing for passengers flying in 
and out of Minneapolis and St. Paul. Northwest controls about 80 
percent of the Twin Cities air market. 

</P>
<P>
	Fendi Sells to Prada, Louis Vuitton  
</P>
<P>
	MILAN, Italy (AP) -- Fendi, the Italian fashion house best known  
for its ``baguette'' handbags, announced plans today to sell 51 
percent of the company to a joint venture of Italy's Prada and 
France's LVMH Moet Hennessy Louis Vuitton. Terms were not 
disclosed, but reports have put the price at around $900 million. 
Five Fendi sisters will retain a 49 percent stake in the company 
and will continue to run the company. In addition to the 
sought-after bags, Fendi is also famous for its extravagant furs, 
designed by Karl Lagerfeld. 

</P>
<P>
	Japanese Defense Official Sentenced  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- A former Japanese Defense Agency official got a  
three-year suspended sentence today for helping defense contractors 
overcharge the government millions of dollars. Masuo Morodomi, 60, 
pleaded guilty in March to breach of trust for allowing two 
companies linked to computer giant NEC Corp. to illegally reduce 
refunds they owed the agency after it was discovered they billed 
the government too much for military equipment. 

</P>
<P>
	India Encourages Telecom Activity  
</P>
<P>
	GENEVA (AP) -- India's new government will encourage foreign  
participation in the development of its telecommunications network, 
an official said today. Contracts for building domestic 
long-distance networks will be put up for bid on Jan. 1 and foreign 
companies are welcome to participate, said Anil Kumar, secretary of 
the Department of Telecommunications, speaking at the Telecom 99 
industry fair. More network operating partnerships are envisioned 
over the next five years on a revenue-sharing basis, Kumar said. 

</P>
<P>
	Hertz CEO Announces Retirement  
</P>
<P>
	PARK RIDGE, N.J. (AP) -- Frank A. Olson will retire as chief  
executive of the Hertz Corp. on Dec. 31 after a 23-year tenure, but 
continue as chairman of the car rental company. Craig R. Koch, 
president and chief operating officer, will succeed Olson as CEO. 
Olson, a 35-year veteran at Hertz, has also held senior positions 
with two of the company's former parent companies, RCA Corp. and 
Allegis Corp. 

</P>
<P>
	Lorillard Announces Anti-Smoke Plan  
</P>
<P>
	GREENSBORO (AP) -- Lorillard Tobacco Co. is launching a  
nationwide youth smoking-prevention program in addition to the one 
included in the industry's $206 billion settlement with 46 states. 
The program, which urges parents to talk to their children about 
not smoking, includes national print and broadcast announcements, 
Web sites and a multi-city tour. Philip Morris Inc., the leading 
cigarette maker, sponsored a similar program earlier this year that 
critics said lacked credibility with children. Lorillard officials 
said their program was carefully researched to ensure it wouldn't 
be perceived as even remotely encouraging tobacco consumption. 

</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Economic reports:  
</P>
<P>
	Thursday: Retail sales  
</P>
<P>
	Thursday: Jobless claims  
</P>
<P>
	Friday: Producer prices  
</P>
<P>
	Friday: Business inventories  
</P>
<P>
	Friday: Industrial production  



  	   	
