<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> More Black Farmers Try Joining Suit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- About 15,000 black farmers have filed claims  
in the settlement of a racial discrimination lawsuit against the 
Agriculture Department, and lawyers are seeking time for additional 
producers to join the case. 
</P>
<P>
	Tuesday was the deadline for claims, but a judge has been asked  
to extend it to Oct. 29. 
</P>
<P>
	Farmers in North Carolina and South Carolina who were victims of  
Hurricane Floyd haven't had time to file yet, and large numbers of 
last-minute filings in Alabama and Mississippi have delayed claims 
as well, said Alexander Pires, the lead attorney in the case. Eight 
members of the Congressional Black Caucus joined in requesting the 
extension. 
</P>
<P>
	Agriculture Secretary Dan Glickman doesn't think a court-ordered  
extension is necessary, USDA spokesman Andy Solomon said, because 
the settlement already allows the judge to accept late claims by 
farmers who couldn't file in time due to uncontrollable 
circumstances. 
</P>
<P>
	That is ``adequate leeway to allow any farmer who is impacted by  
something like Hurricane Floyd to participate,'' Solomon said. 
</P>
<P>
	Aides to U.S. District Judge Paul Friedman, who approved the  
settlement in April, said he would wait to hear from Glickman 
before ruling on the extension request. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the deal, farmers with less documented evidence of  
discrimination can take a $50,000 payment, as well as $12,500 to 
cover taxes, and have their government debts forgiven. Farmers with 
more evidence could opt to go before an independent arbitrator and 
seek larger damages. Farmers could also choose to opt out of the 
lawsuit and pursue their own cases. 
</P>
<P>
	Pires said he expected the number of claims to reach 18,000.  
</P>
<P>
	``Surely we should have an enlargement of time (to file claims)  
since USDA had discriminated against black farmers for decades,'' 
said John Boyd Jr., president of the National Black Farmers 
Association. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
