<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Vikings' Moss Has NBA Aspirations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	EDEN PRAIRIE, Minn. (AP) -- Minnesota Vikings general manager Tim  
Connolly says he would be the first in line to watch Randy Moss try 
his hand at the NBA. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've heard he's a better basketball player than a football  
player,'' Connolly said Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The Vikings don't have a position on Moss' NBA aspirations,  
``but he's a tremendous athlete and we'd all be curious and 
interested to see him play pro basketball,'' Connolly said in his 
first comments on the matter. 
</P>
<P>
	Last weekend, Minnesota Timberwolves coach Flip Saunders said  
one of Moss' representatives had contacted him to float the idea of 
Moss playing alongside fellow superstar Kevin Garnett at some 
point. 
</P>
<P>
	Moss refused to discuss the issue this week, and his agent,  
Dante DiTrapano, didn't return phone calls from The Associated 
Press. 
</P>
<P>
	But in August, the Vikings' star receiver said he would love to  
try playing professional basketball. He was twice named West 
Virginia's Mr. Basketball when he was in high school, when his 
teammate was Sacramento Kings guard Jason Williams. 
</P>
<P>
	Saunders said the arrangements of a two-sport career could be  
complicated but not impossible. 
</P>
<P>
	``We'd probably have to see him play in the summer time,''  
Saunders said. ``I'd never say never.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Even Vikings coach Dennis Green has said that Moss' electrifying  
athletic skills would suit him in the NBA, where he'd miss about 
half the season providing the Vikings go deep into the playoffs. 
</P>
<P>
	Connolly said he's not sure if Moss is serious about playing in  
the NBA. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've never spoken to Randy about it, I've not spoken to his  
agent about it and I've not spoken to the Timberwolves about it,'' 
Connolly said. ``But I think Randy Moss is one of those rare people 
who could play two sports. With the Minnesota Vikings, he's got a 
home as long as he wants.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Moss sprained his ankle playing hoops two days before the team's  
May minicamp after he was drafted last year. He sat out the camp 
with a cast and, according to Green, the injury hampered Moss's 
play his entire rookie season, which was nonetheless spectacular. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year, Moss signed a four-year, $4.4 million contract that's  
widely expected to be torn up after this season. 
</P>
<P>
	Connolly said that despite the increased chance of injury, any  
new deal for Moss, the 1998 Offensive Rookie of the Year, wouldn't 
include language discouraging Moss from pursuing a pro basketball 
career on the side. 
</P>
<P>
	``It will be a standard NFL contract, 20 games and hopefully  
playoffs,'' Connolly said. ``What he does in his spare time is his 
business. Some guys like to hunt, some guys like to fish, some guys 
like to golf. 
</P>
<P>
	``If he want to play basketball, then more power to him. I'd  
love to see it.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
