<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bonds Prices Fall / Bonds  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Bond prices fell modestly Tuesday amid nagging  
concerns about inflation and interest rates. 
</P>
<P>
	The price of the benchmark 30-year Treasury bond fell 1/2 point,  
or $5.00 per $1,000 in face value. Its yield, which moves in the 
opposite direction, rose to 6.22 percent from 6.19 percent late 
Friday. The bond market was closed Monday in observance of the 
Columbus Day holiday. 
</P>
<P>
	Prices of short-term Treasury securities were unchanged to down  
1/32 point while intermediate maturities fell 1/16 point to 3/16 
point, reported Bridge Telerate, a financial information service. 
</P>
<P>
	Bond investors, worried about interest rates, sold ahead of this  
week's government reports on wholesale prices and industrial 
production, analysts said. The reports are expected to offer the 
latest signs of whether inflation is escalating in the U.S. economy 
</P>
<P>
	The Federal Reserve policy-making committee held interest rates  
steady last week, but the Fed left open the possibility of another 
rate increase, which would be the third this year. 
</P>
<P>
	Traders said inflation remains the market's overriding concern.  
A rise in commodity prices, mostly a jump in crude oil futures, 
added to the market's anxiety. 
</P>
<P>
	Yields on three-month Treasury bills were 4.91 percent as the  
discount rose 0.11 percentage point from Friday to 4.78 percent. 
Six-month yields were 5.12 percent, as the discount rose 0.03 
percentage point to 4.92 percent. One-year yields were 5.32 percent 
as the discount rose 0.03 percentage point to 5.06 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Yields are the interest bonds pay by maturity, while the  
discount is the interest at which they are sold. 
</P>
<P>
	The federal funds rate held steady at 5.31 percent, the same as  
late Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	In the tax-exempt market, the Bond Buyer index of 40 actively  
traded municipal bonds fell to 110 5/8 from 111 7/32 late Friday. The 
average yield to maturity rose to 5.99 percent from 5.95 percent on 
Friday. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
