<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 7 a.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Tuesday, Oct. 12, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	Dutch Scientists Win Physics Nobel  
</P>
<P>
	STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) -- Two Dutch scientists, Gerardus 't Hooft  
and Martinus J.G. Veltman, won the 1999 Nobel Prize for physics 
today for their work on the quantum structure of electroweak 
interactions in physics. ``Their work has given researchers a 
well-functioning theoretical machinery which can be used for, among 
other things, predicting the properties of new particles,'' the 
Royal Swedish Academy of Sciences said. Their equations were vital 
in calculating the mass of the top quark, which was observed for 
the first time in 1995 at the Fermilab in the United States. 

</P>
<P>
	Russia Targets Chechen Positions  
</P>
<P>
	GROZNY, Russia (AP) -- Russian forces pounded Chechen positions  
with an artillery barrage on several fronts today, and Russian 
authorities said they suspect Chechen militants will soon try to 
launch terrorist attacks. Both the Russians and the Chechens have 
been fortifying fixed positions in recent days, but neither side 
has launched any major offensives. The Russians have been relying 
mostly on their big artillery guns. They were hammering two areas 
north of Chechnya's capital, Grozny, this morning. 

</P>
<P>
	N. Korea Keeps Beefing Up Military  
</P>
<P>
	SEOUL, South Korea (AP) -- Despite continuing economic  
difficulty, North Korea is beefing up its 1.1 million-strong 
military with missiles and biochemical weapons, a South Korean 
defense report said today. But South Korea's 690,000-member armed 
forces, backed by 37,000 U.S. troops stationed here, can cope with 
any military threat from the hard-line communist North, the report 
said. As in past years, North Korea is believed to be spending more 
than 30 percent of its budget this year on its military, already 
the world's fifth largest, the paper said. 

</P>
<P>
	Covenant House Founder Dies at 72  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The Rev. Bruce Ritter, who founded the Covenant  
House shelters for homeless teen-agers but was forced to resign 
after several young men accused him of seducing them, is dead at 
72. The Roman Catholic priest had suffered from Hodgkin's disease, 
cancer of the lymph nodes. Ritter had denied the accusations of 
sexual misconduct and was never formally charged. He resigned from 
Covenant House in 1990; in August 1991, Ritter left the Franciscan 
order. 

</P>
<P>
	1M Infected With HIV in W. Pacific  
</P>
<P>
	MANILA, Philippines (AP) -- About 1 million people in the Western  
Pacific are now infected with HIV and the rate of infection is 
rising rapidly in many countries in the region, the World Health 
Organization said today. Last year, WHO officials estimated there 
were about 700,000 HIV infections in the region and 40,000 actual 
cases of AIDS. If left unchecked, they said, the number of HIV 
infections in the region will exceed 1.5 million in 2000. 

</P>
<P>
	Nuke Power Plant Shut Down in India  
</P>
<P>
	BOMBAY, India (AP) -- A nuclear power plant in northern India was  
shut down when an airlock door leading into the reactor came off 
its hinges, engineers said today. Nuclear officials told The 
Associated Press there was no danger of any radioactive leakage and 
repairs would be completed by the end of the month. The incident 
occurred Sept. 30 at the 220-megawatt nuclear power plant at Narora 
110 miles east of the Indian capital New Delhi. The Indian Express 
newspaper, which reported the shut down today, quoted R. 
Chidambaram, chairman of the Atomic Energy Commission, saying there 
was ``absolutely no danger'' from the accident. 

</P>
<P>
	Taiwan Quake Causes $9.2B in Damage  
</P>
<P>
	TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) -- Taiwan's earthquake caused an estimated  
$9.2 billion in damage, equal to 3.3 percent of the island's gross 
domestic product, the government said. The damage to buildings and 
homes was the costliest, totaling $6.6 billion, according to the 
Directorate General of Budget, Accounting and Statistics. The 
remaining losses were reported by industry, agriculture and 
transportation, the agency said yesterday in a report. The total 
damage estimate from the 7.6-magnitude quake on Sept. 21 was much 
lower than the $100 billion in damage in Japan after a 
7.2-magnitude quake struck the southern city of Kobe in 1995, the 
report said. 

</P>
<P>
	Tokyo Stocks Close Higher  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo stock prices gained slightly today, boosted  
by an increase in U.S. high technology shares and hopes for company 
alliances in oil and telecommunications. The Nikkei gained 28.63 
points to close at 18,090.81. 

</P>
<P>
	Predators 4, Maple Leafs 2  
</P>
<P>
	TORONTO (AP) -- Rookie David Legwand broke a tie with his first  
NHL goal with 1:03 left in the third period as the Nashville 
Predators beat the Toronto Maple Leafs 4-2 last night. The loss 
came on the same day the Maple Leafs learned that team captain Mats 
Sundin has a broken right ankle and will be out for six weeks. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by VINCENT K. WILLIS  
  	   	
</P>
