<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 10:30 a.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Tuesday, Oct. 12, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	Pakistani Army Surrounds Airport, TV Station  
</P>
<P>
	ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) -- Pakistan's army surrounded  
Islamabad's airport and state-run radio and television today, 
witnesses said, following the dismissal of the powerful army chief 
of staff. Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif's firing of Gen. Pervaiz 
Musharraf took the military by surprise. There was no immediate 
reason for the army chief's dismissal, but in recent weeks there 
have been reports of a rift between the army and the civilian 
government. Musharraf's term was to end in April 2000. The rift 
between the two apparently developed after Sharif ordered militants 
to withdraw this summer from Indian territory in the Kargil region 
ending a bitter two-month border dispute with India. 

</P>
<P>
	Physics, Chemistry Nobels Awarded  
</P>
<P>
	STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) -- Egyptian-born scientist Ahmed H. Zewail  
of the California Institute of Technology won the Nobel Prize for 
chemistry today for demonstrating that a rapid laser technique can 
observe the motion of atoms in a molecule as they occur during a 
chemical reaction. Also today, Dutch scientists Gerardus 't Hooft 
and Martinus J.G. Veltman won the 1999 Nobel Prize for physics for 
their theoretical work on the structure and motion of subatomic 
particles. 

</P>
<P>
	Poll: Bradley Closing on Gore  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The race for the Democratic presidential  
nomination is growing tighter nationally, with Vice President Al 
Gore holding a 51 percent to 39 percent lead over former New Jersey 
Sen. Bill Bradley, according to a new poll. Both men remain behind 
George W. Bush, the leader among Republican presidential 
candidates, in a CNN/Gallup/USA Today poll released yesterday. A 
CNN/USA Today/Gallup poll taken a few weeks ago, in mid-September, 
showed Gore with 63 percent and Bradley with 30 percent. In the new 
poll, Gore and Bradley were in a statistical dead heat among male 
voters, but Gore led among women. 

</P>
<P>
	Experts: JonBenet Decision Coming  
</P>
<P>
	BOULDER, Colo. (AP) -- With the grand jury's term expiring next  
week, an adviser in the JonBenet Ramsey case says a decision on 
indictments could come today or tomorrow. But forensic expert Henry 
Lee, known for his work in the O.J. Simpson case, says he can't 
predict if there will be indictments in the 3-year-old case because 
it ``has inherent issues and problems.'' JonBenet's body was found 
beaten and strangled in the basement of her parents' home Dec. 26, 
1996. Police have said her parents, John and Patsy Ramsey, remain 
under an ``umbrella of suspicion.'' The Ramseys have steadfastly 
maintained their innocence. 

</P>
<P>
	Senate May Vote on Test Ban Treaty  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Senate is weighing today whether to vote  
on a global nuclear test ban treaty or delay the certain-to-fail 
measure. President Clinton is pressing for a pause and put his 
request in writing yesterday. But some Republican lawmakers are 
still demanding a promise that Clinton won't revive the treaty 
during the 2000 election season. Supporters insist the treaty is in 
the best interests of U.S. national security. Conservative 
opponents call the treaty dangerous and insist it must be defeated. 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton Expands Insurance Programs  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton is directing education and  
health officials to work with school officials to get more poor 
children covered under government insurance programs. It is 
estimated that about five million poor children would qualify for 
government health insurance if their parents would apply. Clinton 
says he wants ways developed to reach those parents, and he wants a 
report on the outreach programs from his secretaries of health and 
education within six months. 

</P>
<P>
	Nuke Power Plant Shut Down in India  
</P>
<P>
	BOMBAY, India (AP) -- A nuclear power plant in northern India was  
shut down when an airlock door leading into the reactor came off 
its hinges, engineers said today. Nuclear officials said there was 
no danger of any radioactive leakage and repairs would be completed 
by the end of the month. Antinuclear activists criticize India's 
aging reactors as unsafe, but the influential science community is 
lobbying for more nuclear power to answer the country's energy 
shortages. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Down 67  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Just before 10 a.m. EDT, the Dow industrials  
were down 67.75 to 10,580.43. Declining issues on the New York 
Stock Exchange led advancers 903-584. The Nasdaq was up 4.53 to 
2,920.48. 

</P>
<P>
	Toronto Loses Sundin to Broken Ankle  
</P>
<P>
	TORONTO (AP) -- The Toronto Maple Leafs will be without team  
captain Mats Sundin for the next six weeks because of a broken 
right ankle. The high-scoring center was injured Saturday in a game 
against Ottawa. The team had won its first three games, but without 
its leading scorer, lost to Nashville last night. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by VINCENT CINISOMO  
