<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991012.0224 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-12 07:49:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Sound Bites: Audio Reviews </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Puccini's ``La Boheme,'' opera in 4 acts (Decca) -- starring  
Angela Gheorghiu, Roberto Alagna, Elisabetta Scano, Simon 
Keenlyside, Roberto de Candia and Ildebrando D'Arcangelo. Chorus 
and orchestra of La Scala, conducted by Riccardo Chailly. A 2-CD 
set. 

</P>
<P>
	The opportunity for another album featuring opera's Most Famous  
Married Couple provides an answer to the obvious question: Why 
another recording of ``La Boheme''? 
</P>
<P>
	And fans of the Romanian soprano and French-Sicilian tenor won't  
be disappointed, as both are captured here in fine voice. Alagna 
sounds fresh and strong, investing the familiar ``Che gelida 
manina'' with youthful fervor and tenderness. Perhaps he overdoes 
the sobbing a bit at Mimi's death, but that's a common failing. 
Gheorghiu, always the superior of the two vocally, is radiant, 
especially in her upper register. Her soprano is incisive without 
ever turning harsh, and she maintains a remarkably even sound 
throughout her range. 
</P>
<P>
	Decca has supplied a generally strong supporting cast,  
especially the estimable English baritone Simon Keenlyside, who 
makes a particularly warm and sympathetic Marcello. The one weak 
link is the young Italian soprano Elisabetta Scano, a shrill and 
quavery Musetta. 
</P>
<P>
	Riccardo Chailly conducts a first-rate performance by orchestra  
and chorus, which must know this music in their sleep. The program 
notes proclaim this the ``first studio recording of the new 
critical edition,'' but only scholars are likely to hear a 
difference -- a few notes for a flute in Act 1, a new phrase for the 
chorus in Act 2. 
</P>
<P>
	-- By Mike Silverman, Associated Press Writer.  
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	``Renee Fleming Sings Strauss Heroines'' (Decca) -- with Barbara  
Bonney and Susan Graham. Christoph Eschenbach conducts the Vienna 
Philharmonic. 

</P>
<P>
	Renee Fleming seems to be at that magical point in her career  
where she can tackle just about any role and sing it definitively. 
Her vocalism on this collection of scenes from Richard Strauss 
operas is, in a word, ravishing. And the maturity she brings to the 
characterizations and the delicate shading she imparts to the 
German words put her interpretations on a par with such 
standard-setters of the postwar years as Elisabeth Schwarzkopf and 
Lisa Della Casa. 
</P>
<P>
	The selections here are few but extended. From ``Der  
Rosenkavalier'' we get the Marschallin's Act 1 monologue, in which 
she ruminates about her inevitable loss of youth, and the ending of 
Act 3, from the sublime trio through the ecstatic duet for Octavian 
and Sophie. From ``Arabella,'' there's the Act 1 duet for the 
heroine and her sister, Zdenka; from ``Capriccio,'' the Countess' 
long final monologue. 
</P>
<P>
	It's hard to imagine better vocal support than that provided by  
soprano Barbara Bonney and mezzo Susan Graham. The sound of their 
voices blending together in the Rosenkavalier trio is enough to 
melt the hardest heart, despite the eccentrically slow tempo chosen 
by conductor Christoph Eschenbach. 
</P>
<P>
	In the Arabella duet, my own favorite on the album, Bonney is a  
wonderful partner, tracing her high-lying vocal part with warmth 
and silver purity. The ``Capriccio'' selection shows Fleming more 
than ready to take up the mantle of this autumnal role from Dame 
Kiri te Kanawa, who has made it a specialty in recent years. 
</P>
<P>
	-- By Mike Silverman, Associated Press Writer.  
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	``Jaze'' (Universal) -- Jaze  

</P>
<P>
	Truth be told, there's nothing particularly jazzy about Jaze, a  
new all-male soul quartet out of Orlando, Fla. Unlike some other 
male groups, their lyrics aren't dripping with sexual references 
and their voices aren't overshadowed by overused musical hooks. 
</P>
<P>
	And that's probably what makes their self-entitled debut so  
refreshing. It's just pure music, pure harmonizing, and that makes 
for a pure enjoyment. 
</P>
<P>
	In the vein of Boyz II Men, Jaze's emphasis is on mid-tempo  
grooves or slow love ballads, like ``Have You Ever,'' or the 
dreamy, wistful ``Fly Away.'' The group co-wrote seven tracks on 
the disc. But the real draw here listening to the blending voices 
of the group -- Larry Ballard, John Gibson, Chauncy Jackson and Jose 
Perez. In fact, their best vocal performance is done a capella -- 
their beautiful, serene version of ``The Lord's Prayer. 
</P>
<P>
	-- By Nekesa Mumbi Moody, Associated Press Writer.  
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	``What Does It Take'' (N-Coded Music) -- Candy Dulfer  

</P>
<P>
	Saxophonist Candy Dulfer has toured with artists like Madonna,  
Pink Floyd and the Artist formerly known as Prince. So it's 
probably no surprise that she dabbles in just about every style of 
music on her latest release, ``What Does It Take.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Not that that's a bad thing. What could have been a disastrous  
case of trying to appeal to all genres actually comes across as a 
great musical melting pot that keeps your attention on each track. 
</P>
<P>
	The Grammy-nominated Dulfer sounds very Prince-like on ``2025,''  
a funky jam that features her performing both alto sax and vocals. 
Then, on the remake of ``What Does It Take to Win Your Love,'' 
Dulfer takes a back seat and allows the Jonathan Butler, the South 
African guitarist/vocalist, to take center stage, singing on the 
more mellow tune. 
</P>
<P>
	She even infuses a little Caribbean sound on ``Island Lady,''  
that features her saxophonist father, Hans Dulfer. But her use of 
different sounds doesn't sound forced or contrived. It's just 
entertaining. 
</P>
<P>
	-- By Nekesa Mumbi Moody, Associated Press Writer.  
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	``Jellycream'' (RCA Records) -- Bramhall  

</P>
<P>
	Doyle Bramhall II keeps the blues in his back pocket for his  
second solo effort, ``Jellycream.'' It's a guitar-driven recording 
that showcases the six-string talents of ``Bramhall,'' his new, 
two-syllable, one-word moniker. 
</P>
<P>
	There's a tough edge to the music with purposeful solos and  
crisp production. There's also some honest songwriting, done by 
Bramhall in collaboration with Chris Bruce, who also sings backup 
and plays bass and guitar on some of the tracks. Son of Texas 
bluesman Doyle Bramhall, the younger is best known for his work 
with the Fabulous Thunderbirds, his own former band, Arc Angels, 
and, most recently, as lead guitarist on tour with Pink Floyd 
founder Roger Waters. Such diverse influences came together to help 
Bramhall make a strong sophomore showing. 
</P>
<P>
	-- By James Reindl, Associated Press Writer.  
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	``What Is Hip?'' (Warner Archives/Rhino Records) -- Tower of  
Power 

</P>
<P>
	To answer what is hip, listen to ``Soul With a Capital 'S''' on  
the new Tower of Power anthology. It captures everything about one 
of the country's best known multiracial soul bands. It sets up with 
a funky guitar riff backed by the powerful TOP horn section and it 
lays out in words the band's love for the music that won't let you 
sit still. Founders Emillio Castillo and Stephen ``Doc'' Kupka 
teamed up in 1968 in Oakland, Calif. and have been laying down a 
steady groove for more than 30 years since. 
</P>
<P>
	``What Is Hip?'' delivers 35 cuts from the band's history.  
Amazingly, the band's style has hung together through lineup 
changes and the pressures generated by the public's constantly 
changing tastes. Certainly, TOP wouldn't sell today like it did in 
the funk-driven era of disco in the 1970s. Still, the music has 
strong appeal across time. Great party music never dies. 
</P>
<P>
	-- By James Reindl, Associated Press Writer.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
