<HEADLINE> Justice Probing Baltimore Shooting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BALTIMORE (AP) -- The Justice Department said Tuesday it will  
investigate the fatal shooting of a black man by two white city 
police officers to determine if civil rights laws were violated. 
</P>
<P>
	NAACP President Kweisi Mfume sought the investigation, saying  
the civil rights organization was concerned about the discrepancy 
between the police version of Larry Hubbard's shooting and 
eyewitness accounts. 
</P>
<P>
	``Good police officers and good law-abiding citizens can only  
benefit from a complete and thorough finding of the facts in this 
case. Absent that, we are left with the possibility of charges, 
counter charges and anarchy,'' Mfume said. 
</P>
<P>
	Police said Hubbard, 21, was shot in the head while struggling  
with officers after being pulled over for driving a stolen car. 
</P>
<P>
	The FBI will investigate the case and present the findings to  
the Justice Department's attorneys, who will decide whether to take 
legal action. 
  	   	
</P>
