<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Justices Urged To Uphold Penalties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Polluters sued by private citizens under  
federal environmental laws should not be able to avoid paying 
damages by stopping their misconduct while the case is under way, a 
lawyer for environmental groups told the Supreme Court on Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	But a South Carolina hazardous waste plant owner told the  
justices the company should not have to pay a penalty for ``long 
past violations'' of wastewater discharge limits. 
</P>
<P>
	The case is a test of the federal Clean Water Act's provision  
letting private citizens file lawsuits to help enforce the law. 
Under the law, citizens can seek court orders requiring an end to 
misconduct, plus financial penalties to be paid to the federal 
government. 
</P>
<P>
	A federal appeals court threw out a $405,800 penalty against  
Laidlaw Environmental Services. The court said once a judge 
determined that violations of discharge limits had ceased and a 
court-ordered ban on future violations was not needed, the case was 
moot and a financial penalty was no longer warranted. 
</P>
<P>
	Bruce J. Terris, the lawyer for three environmental groups who  
sued, called that ruling a ``perverse result.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Justice Department lawyer Jeffrey P. Minear, supporting the  
environmental groups, said the ruling would encourage 
``gamesmanship'' and give polluters an ``incentive to string the 
litigation along'' until a case could be declared moot. 
</P>
<P>
	The plant owner's lawyer, Donald A. Cockrill, said the lower  
court correctly ruled that the environmental groups could not 
continue seeking a financial penalty because they would not benefit 
from a fine paid to the government. 
</P>
<P>
	The justices asked questions on numerous aspects of the  
citizen-lawsuit provisions, including whether a penalty paid to the 
government would help private citizens by deterring future 
violations. 
</P>
<P>
	``What difference does it make if the penalty goes to the  
government as opposed to private parties as far as a deterrent?'' 
asked Justice Anthony M. Kennedy. 
</P>
<P>
	Justice David H. Souter suggested Cockrill's argument ``turns  
this into kind of a sport'' by requiring private citizens to 
continue seeking a ban on future misconduct in an effort to keep 
alive their request for financial penalties. 
</P>
<P>
	However, Justice Antonin Scalia questioned the whole idea of  
letting private citizens seek financial penalties to be paid to the 
government. ``Just because Congress has said it does not mean the 
courts can do it,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Laidlaw was sued in 1992 over wastewater discharges from its  
hazardous waste incinerator in Roebuck, S.C. The lawsuit by Friends 
of the Earth, Citizens Local Environmental Action Network and the 
Sierra Club said the plant violated limits on mercury discharges. 
</P>
<P>
	By the time a federal judge ruled on the lawsuit in 1997,  
Laidlaw was found to have come into compliance with the discharge 
limits. Therefore, the judge did not issue an order banning future 
violations, but instead imposed a $405,800 civil penalty. 
</P>
<P>
	The 4th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals threw out the penalty last  
year and declared the case moot. The appeals court said that once 
the judge decided not to ban future violations, the only remaining 
remedy -- a civil penalty -- would not benefit the environmental 
groups because it would be paid to the federal government. 
</P>
<P>
	The case is Friends of the Earth vs. Laidlaw Environmental  
Services, 98-822. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
