<HEADLINE> AskJeeves Jumps on Microsoft Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Shares of AskJeeves Inc. soared by more than 35  
percent after Microsoft Corp. said it would use an AskJeeves 
service to provide online technical support for the Windows 98 
operating system. 
</P>
<P>
	AskJeeves, based in Emeryville, Calif., operates a popular Web  
site searches the Internet to find answers to questions users type 
in ordinary English. 
</P>
<P>
	Shares of AskJeeves rose $17.87 1/2 to close at $68.31 1/4 on the  
Nasdaq Stock Market Monday. About 4 million shares changed hands, 
more than 11 times their average daily volume. 
</P>
<P>
	Neither company disclosed financial specifics, but AskJeeves  
Chief Executive Rob Wrubel said the agreement would generate more 
than seven figures during the next 12 months, Dow Jones News 
Service reported. 
</P>
<P>
	Shares of Microsoft, based in Redmond, Wash., fell 62 1/2 cents to  
$94.31 1/4, also on Nasdaq. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
