<DOCNO> APW19991012.0232 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-12 07:10:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> HS Football Coach Also a Preacher </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LADONIA, Texas (AP) -- With a coach who's a preacher, mothers who  
moonlight as groundskeepers and a girl who scores touchdowns, 
Ladonia Fannindel High School has the most unusual football team in 
Texas. 
</P>
<P>
	``I remember when most of the players were born, and I even  
remember their mothers when they were little,'' said Cecil Jones, a 
Baptist minister who doubles as an assistant coach at the 
62-student school, the smallest in the state with an 11-man 
football team. ``I don't think there's a lot of high school 
football coaches who can say that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That the Falcons are coached by a pastor is appropriate. Just  
about everyone pulls one form of double duty or another in Ladonia, 
population 761. 
</P>
<P>
	Mothers trim the grass and paint the fences at Fannindel's  
football field. Janna Reel, the owner of Reel's Cafe on the town 
square, makes care packages presented to the players at pep 
rallies. 
</P>
<P>
	And to top it all off, the student coaches call ``the smartest  
girl in school'' is also a Falcons running back-receiver. 
</P>
<P>
	That's right -- Jentaisha Scott, a 5-foot-8-inch sophomore with  
powerful legs and a winning smile, is believed to be the only girl 
in Texas to have scored a touchdown this season. 
</P>
<P>
	With only 33 boys in the entire high school, head coach Kris  
Crews told Scott she was more than welcome to join the squad when 
she asked this season. 
</P>
<P>
	Although she had no football experience before practice began in  
August, Scott has more than stepped up to the challenge, emerging 
as the junior varsity's starting tailback and one of the varsity's 
best wide receivers. 
</P>
<P>
	And how do opponents react after being scored upon by a female?  
</P>
<P>
	``Most of them don't realize it until halftime,'' Scott said.  
``They look pretty surprised when I take my helmet off, though.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Those Fannindel students who don't strap on helmets at practice  
every afternoon are few and far between. Like many Class 1A high 
schools, every able-bodied boy in the school is expected to play 
football, and all but five of the boys who attend Fannindel do just 
that. 
</P>
<P>
	The school is small enough to be eligible for six-man football,  
but administrators and coaches have never considered making the 
switch because of tradition and the athletic program's history of 
success. 
</P>
<P>
	Although the Falcons are 1-5 this year, they reached the state  
semifinals in 1988 and the school won the 1A state basketball title 
a few months later. 
</P>
<P>
	National TV crews converged on Ladonia when the Texas  
Legislature instituted its ``no pass, no play'' rule in the 
mid-1980s. At one point, the team was down to just 11 eligible 
players, but the Falcons responded by winning four of their last 
five games and reaching the playoffs. 
</P>
<P>
	``I like it that we're smaller than everybody else,'' said  
Derrick Houston, the starting running back and defensive end, 
``because it gives us an even bigger chance to prove ourselves.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Despite recent struggles, pride runs rampant in Fannindel's  
program. As much as coaches tout star players like quarterback 
Quentin Dowdy, they brag even more about stellar fan support and 
the cohesiveness of the community. 
</P>
<P>
	In fact, so many Ladonia residents are Falcons fans that Reel  
closes her restaurant on the nights of home games. 
</P>
<P>
	``The people here are uniquely close,'' athletic director Mike  
Smith said. ``They might fight with each other sometimes, but if 
one of them gets in trouble, everybody in town is fighting on the 
same side.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Players thrive on that support. They say the advantages of  
living in a laid-back, small town far outweigh the drawbacks of 
being a half hour away from the nearest movie theater or 
McDonald's. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think the kids that go to school in the city are the ones  
who are missing out,'' said junior running back Dustin Smith, 
Mike's son. ``They'll never feel the sense of family and the 
closeness that we feel here. I wouldn't trade places with 
anybody.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991012.0233 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-12 19:50:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dylan Makes Sitcom Appearance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Now that he's made his sitcom debut on ``Dharma  
&AMP; Greg,'' a whole new world of possibilities opens up for Bob 
Dylan. 
</P>
<P>
	How about a role as a high school teacher on ``That '70s Show''?  
A space alien on ``3rd Rock From the Sun''? Or one of the 
interchangeable cads on ``Sex and the City''? 
</P>
<P>
	The inscrutable rock legend started simply -- with a jovial  
version of himself -- in an unbilled appearance on the ABC sitcom 
Tuesday night. 
</P>
<P>
	It came at the end of the show, when Dharma, played by Jenna  
Elfman, decides to show off her drum skills by trying out for a 
band. Dylan is the bandleader. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'll count it off,'' Dylan advises Dharma as a song begins.  
</P>
<P>
	The odd appearance was engineered by Eddie Gorodetsky, a writer  
on the sitcom who is friendly with Dylan. When producers sought a 
nationally known musician for the cameo role, they decided to test 
the contact. 
</P>
<P>
	Through his manager, Dylan requested a few tapes of ``Dharma &AMP;  
Greg,'' said the show's creator, Chuck Lorre. About a month later 
came the word: Bob was game. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was a series of miracles,'' Lorre said.  
</P>
<P>
	Taping took an hour, with Ms. Elfman trying her best to keep up  
with the legend. 
</P>
<P>
	At one point, Dylan suggests a meringue beat, then a polka.  
</P>
<P>
	When Dharma tries a different beat, she says, ``That's kind of  
too funky for your style, eh? 
</P>
<P>
	``Not at all,'' Dylan says with a wide smile.  
</P>
<P>
	He demurs when Dharma asks if she's passed the audition, but  
laughs when she asks whether he can help pack up her drum kit. 
</P>
<P>
	``Yeah, sure,'' he says, already completing more dialogue than  
he uses during most concert appearances. 
</P>
<P>
	There's no telling what it was about ``Dharma &AMP; Greg'' that  
appealed to Dylan; his spokesman didn't return a call for comment 
on Tuesday. And Dylan insisted a tight lid be kept on all 
publicity: ABC officials concealed his identity during show promos 
and wouldn't even confirm his appearance hours before the taped 
show aired. 
</P>
<P>
	``Anytime he wants to do another episode,'' Lorre said, ``we'll  
figure it out.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
