<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Public Records Bill Vetoed in Calf. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) -- California's governor has vetoed a  
bill that would have required government agencies to make 
computerized public records available to the public and press in an 
electronic format. 
</P>
<P>
	The measure would also have prohibited agencies from charging  
more than the actual cost of providing the records on computer 
disks or in other electronic formats. 
</P>
<P>
	The bill was ``well intentioned'' but many state computer  
systems could not comply with it without compromising confidential 
material stored in those systems, Gov. Gray Davis said in his veto 
message, released Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	``I believe the state's information technology resources should  
be directed toward making sure its computer systems are year-2000 
compliant,'' Davis added, rather than diverting time and money to 
designing programs to separate confidential from public information 
in computer files. 
</P>
<P>
	Terry Franke, general counsel of the media-supported California  
First Amendment Coalition, said the bill would have prevented 
agencies that keep records in easily searchable formats from 
instead releasing them only in a more expensive and hard-to-search 
``haystack of hundreds of pages of paper.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It is the second public records bill Davis has vetoed in the  
past week. On Friday, he vetoed a that would have imposed 
$100-per-day fines for deliberately withholding public records. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
