<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Wisconsin To Decide Alvarez's Role </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MADISON, Wis. (AP) -- Barry Alvarez isn't so old that his  
favorite topic of conversation is his health. In fact, he'd rather 
be talking about almost anything else. 
</P>
<P>
	But after the misadventures the Wisconsin coach has undergone in  
the past months with his badly damaged knee, that's all anyone 
wants to ask him about. In the meantime, the 17th-ranked Badgers 
play on -- likely for at least another week -- without their leader. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm just kind of in limbo right now. I just want to do  
something. I just want to make a move,'' Alvarez said. ``I don't 
think I've ever been this confined in my life. It's very, very 
difficult for me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Alvarez was released from the Mayo Clinic in Rochester, Minn.,  
and returned to Madison on Tuesday, a week after his knee 
replacement surgery turned into a cleaning operation to remove an 
infection from his right leg. He didn't speak to the team, though 
he probably will later in the week. 
</P>
<P>
	School officials say it hasn't been decided whether Alvarez will  
sit in the Camp Randall Stadium press box for Saturday's game 
against Indiana, or whether he will watch it from home. He might 
have contact with his players at week's end, perhaps meeting with 
them at the team hotel on Friday night. 
</P>
<P>
	Alvarez still needs the knee replacement, but the six weeks of  
antibiotics he must take to treat the infection have postponed the 
procedure yet again. Originally, Alvarez had hoped to put off the 
surgery until after the season, and now he'll get his wish -- though 
his role in coaching the Badgers for the rest of the season is 
still up in the air. 
</P>
<P>
	Alvarez monitored the Badgers' 20-17 overtime win at Minnesota  
last Saturday from his hospital bed with a television and a 
headset, though he said he didn't contribute much to his 
assistants' winning game plan. 
</P>
<P>
	As the Badgers seized Paul Bunyan's Axe and pretended to chop  
down the Gophers' goal post, Alvarez's pride and frustration grew 
apace. 
</P>
<P>
	``There never seems to be a light at the end of the tunnel with  
this knee,'' Alvarez said. ``Every day I get a little better, but 
you know what it's like after you go through surgery.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Alvarez has a 10-inch incision, which has been closed by a few  
fragile sutures, stretching above and below his knee. Since even a 
slight jolt could open the sutures and invite infection again, he 
likely won't be attending practice this week. 
</P>
<P>
	During last week's 2 1/2-hour surgery, damaged tissue around his  
knee was removed, along with spurs and cysts. It also revealed the 
infection, which doctors are still working to identify. 
</P>
<P>
	He has lost much of the muscle and movement in the joint, but  
although he's still in pain, ``it's a different kind of pain,'' he 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	But the biggest pain of all, he said, is being unable to get on  
the field with the players and the program he has built over the 
past decade. Alvarez reaped the fruits of his labors last season 
with a Rose Bowl win, and this year's team still has a shot at an 
excellent season and even the Big Ten title. 
</P>
<P>
	He said the final moments of the Minnesota game, when Vitaly  
Pisetsky kicked the game-winning field goal and the Badgers seized 
the axe, were difficult to watch without getting overexcited. He 
did so much whooping in his hospital room that the staff asked him 
to quiet down. 
</P>
<P>
	``For me, the box is passive enough, let alone sitting in a  
hospital room with your wife and a headset on,'' Alvarez said. 
</P>
<P>
	Alvarez usually speaks to his team every Friday night before a  
game, and last week he videotaped a message he said was upbeat. 
</P>
<P>
	``I didn't try to play on their emotions because I thought the  
week had been emotional enough,'' he said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
