<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Umpires Seek To Decertify Union </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Umpires disenchanted with union head Richie  
Phillips petitioned the federal government on Tuesday to decertify 
their current union and form a new one. 
</P>
<P>
	The dissidents, headed by three AL umpires, met the National  
Labor Relations Board's requirement of having signatures from at 
least 30 percent of the bargaining unit, which in this case is the 
93 major league umpires. 
</P>
<P>
	Dan Silverman, the NLRB's New York regional director, called for  
an Oct. 22 hearing on the election request and said that if there 
are not objections, he anticipated balloting would take place in 
November. 
</P>
<P>
	The dissidents would not say if they had the support of a  
majority of the umpires. 
</P>
<P>
	``The board keeps confidential the names of the persons who  
signed cards and submit them,'' said Joel Smith, a lawyer for the 
dissidents. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, the dissidents plan to invite all umpires to a Nov.  
2 meeting in Baltimore, a lawyer familiar with their organizing 
said, speaking on the condition he not be identified. 
</P>
<P>
	The dissident umpires, most in the American League, blame  
Phillips and union president Jerry Crawford for the union's 
strategy of mass resignations, which backfired in July and cost 22 
umpires their jobs. 
</P>
<P>
	While the Major League Umpires Association, which Phillips  
heads, has filed a grievance to regain the jobs of the 22, the 
union has not agreed to any of the proposed dates for the hearing 
before arbitrator Alan Symonette, a lawyer involved in the case 
said Tuesday. Union lawyer Pat Campbell declined comment on the 
arbitration. 
</P>
<P>
	The dissidents call themselves the Major League Umpires  
Independent Organizing Committee and have been organized by three 
AL umpires -- Dave Phillips (who is not related to the union head), 
Joe Brinkman and John Hirschbeck. They have been working with 
lawyer Ron Shapiro, who is Cal Ripken's agent. 
</P>
<P>
	Richie Phillips referred questions about the petition to  
Campbell. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is certainly not a surprise. They've been broadcasting  
this for months,'' Campbell said. ``I think that Jerry and Richie 
Garcia believe there is a solid majority that supports the Major 
League Umpires Association.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Garcia, an AL ump who is among the 22 who lost their jobs, is a  
strong supporter of the current union. 
</P>
<P>
	Silverman said NLRB staff lawyer Stephen Appell will take  
testimony during the hearing, which will be held in New York.. 
</P>
<P>
	``Then I will issue a decision on whether there will be an  
election,'' Silverman said. ``That decision is subject to appeal to 
the National Labor Relations Board in Washington.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Umpires embarked on their mass resignation strategy in an effort  
to spark early negotiations to the collective bargaining agreement 
that expires Dec. 31. 
</P>
<P>
	Owners, concluding umpires were getting out of control, then  
hired 25 new umps from the minors and accepted the resignations of 
the 22 -- who tried to withdraw the resignations but were told it 
was too late. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
