<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ad Growth Leads Dow Jones' Profits </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Dow Jones &AMP; Co. earned $45.5 million in the  
third quarter, exceeding analysts' expectations, amid continued 
advertising gains at its flagship newspaper, The Wall Street 
Journal. 
</P>
<P>
	The profits for the three months ended Sept. 30 were equivalent  
to 50 cents per share, surpassing the 47 cents per share forecast 
by analysts surveyed by First Call/Thomson Financial. 
</P>
<P>
	Comparable earnings for the same period a year ago, which do not  
include a restructuring charge of $9.6 million related to severance 
costs at the company's community newspapers, were $35.4 million, or 
37 cents per share. 
</P>
<P>
	The figures for the most recent quarter do not include a  
one-time gain of $57.3 million from the sale of stock in United 
States Broadcasting Inc. Including that gain, Dow Jones earned 
$102.8 million, or $1.13 per share. 
</P>
<P>
	Total revenues rose 6 percent during the quarter to $469.8  
million from $443.6 million a year ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Revenues from print publishing, which include Barron's and  
SmartMoney magazines, rose 18 percent to $310 million. Advertising 
linage at the Journal, which has been lifted by the strong stock 
market, jumped 27 percent during the quarter. 
</P>
<P>
	Revenues from Dow Jones' electronic publishing business, which  
includes a news database partnership recently formed with Reuters, 
rose 3 percent in the third quarter to $101.5 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	Operating income in that area fell 65 percent to $6.2 million,  
which the company attributed to higher costs for content and 
increased spending on investment and sales. The electronic 
publishing segment includes Dow Jones Newswires, several Web sites 
and numerous stock indexes, including the widely quoted industrial 
average. 
</P>
<P>
	For the first nine months of the year, Dow Jones earned $145.2  
million, or $1.59 per share, compared to $129.6 million, or $1.33 
per share. Revenues fell to $1.44 billion from $1.67 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	Even though the earnings beat expectations, Dow Jones stock fell  
$1.31 1/4 to $57.68 3/4 in trading on the New York Stock Exchange. 




  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
