<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Pfizer Must Pay in Trademark Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Pfizer Inc. was ordered Tuesday to pay $143  
million to a British medical electronics company that accused the 
U.S. pharmaceutical company of stealing its name. 
</P>
<P>
	A U.S. District Court jury awarded the damages to Trovan Ltd.,  
and said Pfizer must change the drug's name. 
</P>
<P>
	Trovan Ltd. sued Pfizer for using the name Trovan for an  
antibiotic introduced in 1998. The drug later was linked to several 
cases of liver failure, and the U.S. Food and Drug Administration 
has restricted its use. 
</P>
<P>
	Pfizer plans to appeal the original verdict and the damage  
award. ``These jury verdicts are not supported by either the law or 
the facts, and we are confident this decision will not be upheld,'' 
said Paul S. Miller, Pfizer's general counsel and executive vice 
president. 
</P>
<P>
	Trovan Ltd. and its U.S. distributor, Electronic Identification  
Devices of Santa Barbara, Calif., contended that their reputations 
were damaged by being linked to the antibiotic. 
</P>
<P>
	``A company's reputation is everything,'' said Joseph Masin,  
president of Electronic Identification Devices. ``... With this 
victory, we can continue to grow our company knowing once and for 
all that Trovan is indisputably ours.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Privately held Trovan Ltd. manufactures identification tags that  
are implanted with computer chips containing information about 
patients' medical conditions. The tags also are used by researchers 
and hospitals to track blood supplies and by pet owners to track 
their animals in case they become lost or stolen. 
</P>
<P>
	Trovan attorneys said Pfizer introduced its Trovan antibiotic  
last year despite objections from the British company. 
</P>
<P>
	The verdict is the second setback for New York-based Pfizer in  
recent weeks. In August, the company announced it was halting 
development of Alond, a potentially lucrative drug designed to 
reduce diabetic nerve damage. Pfizer had similarly high 
expectations for Trovan when it was introduced in 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts had projected the Trovan antibiotic to generate $370  
million in worldwide sales this year and about $1.3 billion in 
2002. 
</P>
<P>
	Pfizer has said that Trovan has therapeutic advantages and the  
degree of risk associated with the product is not markedly 
different from other antibiotics. 
</P>
<P>
	Pfizer shares were down 50 cents to $39.31 1/4 in Tuesday trading  
on the New York Stock Exchange. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
