<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Calif. Reapportionment on Ballot </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) -- A measure that would let an  
independent commission rather than the Legislature draw new 
congressional and legislative district lines after the 2000 census 
has won a spot on the March ballot. 
</P>
<P>
	Initiative petitions drew at least 130,000 more signatures from  
registered voters than the 670,000 they needed, Secretary of State 
Bill Jones said Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The measure's sponsors are trying to make it more appealing to  
voters by including a provision that would mandate a 25 percent cut 
in state legislators' salaries. 
</P>
<P>
	That has enraged many Republican lawmakers who otherwise would  
be among the measure's strongest supporters, and could cut off an 
important source of funds in favor of the measure. 
</P>
<P>
	The measure is sponsored by the conservative People's Advocate  
political action group and most of California Republican members of 
Congress, who say they fear Democratic Gov. Gray Davis and a 
Democratic-controlled Legislature will draw congressional and 
legislative boundaries to help their party and hurt Republicans. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
