<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-12 07:49:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> At the Movies: `Romance' </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	If it's possible to make a boring film about sex, ``Romance'' is  
it. 
</P>
<P>
	Tedious and utterly joyless, ``Romance'' is the so-called  
provocative tale of a young French woman's quest for sexual 
independence. Actually, it's a series of graphic encounters 
connected by our shallow heroine's musings on genitalia. 
</P>
<P>
	Caroline Ducey plays Marie -- elementary school teacher by day,  
naughty nymph by night. Marie is trapped in a passionless 
relationship with pretty-boy male model Paul (Sagamore Stevenin), 
but she's too madly in love with him to leave. 
</P>
<P>
	And who could blame her? When he's not looking pouty in a  
toreador costume for a photo shoot, he's reading Bukowski while 
dining alone at a sushi bar. This guy is deep. 
</P>
<P>
	Feeling frustrated in the middle of the night, Marie gets out of  
bed, gets dressed and begins her search for intimacy, logically 
enough, at a bar. There she meets Paolo (Rocco Siffredi, Italy's 
most famous porn star), who is equally eager for a fling. Paolo is 
kind and attentive to her, and freakishly well-endowed. She uses 
him and pushes him away. 
</P>
<P>
	Later, she hooks up with Robert (Francois Berland), her boss at  
school who claims he's a ``sexologist'' and has bedded 10,000 
women. He's not nearly as attractive as Paolo, but he has a bevy of 
bondage equipment. This intrigues Marie. However, it forces the 
audience to suffer through a lengthy scene in which he ties her up, 
half naked, in elaborate knots using very long pieces of white 
rope. As she peers around at the predicament she's gotten herself 
into, she looks neither aroused nor frightened. She looks bored. We 
are, too. 
</P>
<P>
	There is one funny moment, though, when Robert takes his  
sadomasochistic game too far and makes Marie cry. In an effort to 
console her, he strokes her hair and promises, ``I can tie you up 
less severely.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Marie later gets raped in a stairwell, which she finds  
liberating. ``When he wants an evening without me, I make the best 
of it,'' she rationalizes. This is not philosophical -- it's 
disturbing. 
</P>
<P>
	A scene in which Marie visits the gynecologist is about as  
erotic as her sexual encounters. She finds bitter pleasure in the 
fact that, on this particular day, her doctor has a group of male 
interns with him, who pull on rubber gloves and take turns probing 
her. For Marie, this is almost like group sex -- another step in her 
sick journey. 
</P>
<P>
	Nothing about this film is arousing. The sex is intentionally  
clinical and mechanical, which is supposed to make it edgy and 
arty. Instead, the acts are just plain dull. 
</P>
<P>
	What's worse is the incessant banter in Marie's head. She  
obsesses over why her boyfriend won't touch her, the size of men's 
organs, the size of her own, the intricacies of foreplay. Can't 
this woman think about anything else? 
</P>
<P>
	It's impossible to care about her or any of these people, mostly  
because writer-director Catherine Breillat tells us little about 
them beyond their sexual quirks. We never even learn Marie's name 
until the closing credits roll. 
</P>
<P>
	The film's use of color is interesting, though. Paul's pad is  
full of sleek modern furniture and decorated all in white -- the 
sheets, the curtains, the kitchen table, even his cat -- to reflect 
his lack of passion. By contrast, the sexologist's babe lair is 
full of dark wood and rich earth tones. He seems to own just one 
shirt -- we see him repeatedly in a red button-down. And as Marie 
sinks deeper into her relationship with him, she discards her 
neutral-colored, conservative attire for an off-the-shoulder red 
gown. 
</P>
<P>
	According to the film's promotional materials, Marie's quest  
``eventually leads to her fulfillment.'' If only the audience had 
gotten so lucky. 
</P>
<P>
	``Romance,'' a Trimark Pictures release, is not rated but  
contains strong language and graphic sexual situations. It is in 
French with English subtitles and runs 95 minutes. 
</P>
<P>
                            	 *------	 
</P>
<P>
	Motion Picture Association of America rating definitions:  
</P>
<P>
	G -- General audiences. All ages admitted.  
</P>
<P>
	PG -- Parental guidance suggested. Some material may not be  
suitable for children. 
</P>
<P>
	PG-13 -- Special parental guidance strongly suggested for  
children under 13. Some material may be inappropriate for young 
children. 
</P>
<P>
	R -- Restricted. Under 17 requires accompanying parent or adult  
guardian. 
</P>
<P>
	NC-17 -- No one under 17 admitted.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
