<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 2 a.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Wednesday, Oct. 13, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	Vajpayee Sworn In As Indian PM  
</P>
<P>
	NEW DELHI, India (AP) -- Prime Minister Atal Bihari Vajpayee was  
sworn in Wednesday as India's leader for the third time amid 
political upheaval in neighboring Pakistan, where a military coup 
may further complicate relations between the two rivals. Vajpayee's 
government fell in April when a southern politician withdrew her 
party's 18 seats from the coalition and Vajpayee lost a confidence 
motion by one vote. No other group was able to form a government 
and Vajpayee remained in charge of a caretaker government while 
elections were held. Vajpayee had said that one of the first tasks 
of his new government would be to restart peace talks that were 
disrupted by recent fighting in Kashmir, which has been the cause 
of two of the three wars between Pakistan and India. 

</P>
<P>
	Coup Throws Pakistan Into Chaos  
</P>
<P>
	ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) -- A military coup has thrown Pakistan  
into political disarray just one year after it exploded a nuclear 
device and months after a conflict with India nearly erupted into a 
full-fledged war. Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif and most of his 
government ministers were under apparent house arrest, with 
soldiers surrounding their homes refusing to let anyone in or out. 
Army Chief Gen. Pervaiz Musharraf spoke briefly on national 
television urging calm and saying the military had no choice but to 
take over. Western diplomats say it was Musharraf who orchestrated 
the takeover of Indian territory in Kashmir this summer, provoking 
a bitter border dispute that many feared would escalate into an 
all-out war. 

</P>
<P>
	Test Ban Agreement Remains Elusive  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- While bipartisan support is building in the  
Senate to delay a nuclear test ban vote, finding a graceful exit 
from near-certain defeat of the pact remains elusive. A small group 
of conservatives continues to threaten to block any effort at 
meeting President Clinton's request that the vote on the 
Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty be postponed. Unless a deal can be 
reached, a showdown vote on the pact will occur late today. Clinton 
and other supporters concede they are far short of the 67 needed 
for ratification if all 100 senators vote. Senate Minority Leader 
Tom Daschle, D-S.D., offered a pledge to Republicans on Tuesday 
that he would not seek to reschedule a vote on the treaty before a 
new president and new Congress is sworn in in 2001 ``barring 
extraordinary circumstances.'' 

</P>
<P>
	U.S., China Plan High-Level Talks  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Top-level U.S. negotiators will head to Beijing  
later this month to try again to reach an agreement to lower 
China's trade barriers to American products, a prerequisite to U.S. 
endorsement of that nation's bid for membership in the World Trade 
Organization. Treasury Secretary Lawrence Summers said Tuesday he 
will lead a delegation of top economic policy-makers from a number 
of Cabinet agencies. The talks are set to begin Oct. 25. Once a 
deal is struck, the United States has said it will drop its 
objections to China's entry into the 134-member WTO, the 
international group that sets rules for world trade. 

</P>
<P>
	Basketball Great Chamberlain Dead At 63  
</P>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Basketball Hall of Famer Wilt Chamberlain was  
found dead Tuesday in his Bel-Air home. He was 63 years old. 
Authorities said there were signs that Chamberlain might have had a 
heart attack. Sy Goldberg, Chamberlain's agent, said he had been 
hospitalized with an irregular heartbeat in 1992, and was on 
medication. ``Wilt the Stilt'' played from 1959 to 1973 for the 
Philadelphia (later the San Francisco) Warriors, the Philadelphia 
76ers and the Lakers. He averaged 30.1 points per game. 

</P>
<P>
	U.S. Rescue Planes Head to S.Pole  
</P>
<P>
	CHRISTCHURCH, New Zealand (AP) -- After a 24-hour delay caused by  
bad weather, two U.S. military cargo planes departed for Antarctica 
Wednesday to prepare to rescue a doctor at the South Pole who has a 
lump in her breast. Two Air National Guard Hercules LC-130 cargo 
planes set out for McMurdo base on the northern coast of Antarctica 
after high winds and swirling snow eased on the frigid continent. 
The 1,975-mile flight was expected to take about eight hours, 
putting the planes into McMurdo late Wednesday afternoon New 
Zealand time (1 a.m. Wednesday EDT). 

</P>
<P>
	Alabama Rejects Lottery  
</P>
<P>
	MONTGOMERY, Ala. (AP) -- Alabama voters soundly rejected the  
governor's appeal for a lottery Tuesday, heeding the warnings of 
ministers over arguments that the revenue would be vital to 
improving the state's lagging schools. With 94 percent of precincts 
reporting, 54 percent had voted against the lottery, and 46 percent 
were for it. The lottery was once thought to be a sure bet to be 
approved, but it came under fire from church groups who said it 
would exploit the poor. 

</P>
<P>
	Tokyo Stocks Slip  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo stock prices declined on Wednesday. The  
Nikkei plunged 253.69 points to 17,837.12 in early trading. In New 
York, the Dow ended down 231.12 at 10,417.06. 

</P>
<P>
	Braves Take Game One of NLCS  
</P>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- The Atlanta Braves defeated the New York Mets  
Tuesday 4-2, reminding the Mets who's boss in the National League. 
Greg Maddux shut down Mike Piazza and the Mets for seven innings 
and John Rocker sprinted from the bullpen to finish them off, 
giving the Braves a victory in Game 1 of the NL Championship 
Series. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by BRADLEY BROOKS  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
