<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Merrill Lynch Profit Beats Forecast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co., the largest brokerage firm  
in the United States, reported strong third-quarter earnings 
Tuesday of $572 million, easily beating analysts' expectations. 
</P>
<P>
	The company's profits represent earnings of $1.34 a share, a  
nickel more than the $1.29 a share analysts had predicted, 
according to First Call Corp. 
</P>
<P>
	In the third quarter of 1998, Merrill Lynch reported a loss of  
$173 million, or 48 cents a share, due to a $430 million pretax 
write-off of costs related to staff reductions. 
</P>
<P>
	Merrill Lynch cited record revenues in both global stock  
underwriting and investment banking, which includes mergers and 
acquisitions. 
</P>
<P>
	Total third-quarter revenues were $5.27 billion, up from $3.85  
billion a year ago. 
</P>
<P>
	``Investment banking revenues and asset management and portfolio  
service fees set records, and our global debt and equity businesses 
posted solid trading results despite a more difficult 
environment,'' said Merrill Lynch chairman David Komansky. 
</P>
<P>
	For the first nine months of 1999, Merrill Lynch posted earnings  
of $1.9 billion, or $4.36 a share, up from $900 million, or $2.14 a 
share, in 1998, when taking into account the $430 million loss 
related to layoffs. 
</P>
<P>
	Nine month revenues came to $16 billion, compared to $13.5  
billion a year ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Shares of Merrill Lynch fell 75 cents to $67 in trading on the  
New York Stock Exchange. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
