<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  China, Romania Are Gymnast Champs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TIANJIN, China (AP) -- China easily won its fourth consecutive  
men's world gymnastics championship Tuesday, while Romania narrowly 
defended its women's title when Russia's Svetlana Khorkina fell on 
her final routine. 
</P>
<P>
	China, hoping to win its first men's Olympic gymnastics team  
gold medal, finished with 230.395 points to 228.145 for Russia, the 
1996 Olympic winner. 
</P>
<P>
	Belarus was third with 227.631, followed by Japan with 225.908,  
South Korea with 225.870 and the United States with 225.196. 
</P>
<P>
	In women's competition, newcomers Maria Olaru had a 38.749 and  
Andreea Raducan finished with a 38.567 to lead Romania, which 
scored a total of 153.527 points to Russia's 153.209. 
</P>
<P>
	China was third with 152.423 in a repeat of the finish order at  
the last World Championships in 1997. Ukraine was fourth with 
152.338, next year's Olympic host Australia was fifth with 150.932 
and the United States sixth with 150.213. 
</P>
<P>
	In Russia's last routine of the day, 1997 individual champion  
Khorkina was in a position to give her team the gold medal with a 
stellar routine. She already had scored the meet's best score so 
far, a 9.825 on the uneven bars, and a 9.800 in the floor 
exercises. 
</P>
<P>
	But she went off the balance beam on a back flip and scored just  
9.075, after Anna Kovaleva had left the Russian team in a perilous 
position by fumbling her balance beam routine. 
</P>
<P>
	The Romanians had started on the balance beam, and also ran into  
trouble, including a fall by 1997 individual silver medalist Simona 
Amanar. 
</P>
<P>
	But they bounced right back in the floor exercises, where their  
lowest score was a 9.700. Amanar scored 9.812 and Raducan, a 
16-year-old who seems to float through her routines, had 9.800. 
</P>
<P>
	The top two finishers of 1997 -- Khorkina and Amanar -- were  
performing at the same time at the end. Amanar closed with a 9.700 
on the uneven bars, and came out ninth among individuals with 
38.155. Khorkina was 11th with 37.956. 
</P>
<P>
	China had two of the top five individuals -- Ling Jie, third with  
38.418 including a 9.787 on the uneven bars, and Liu Xuan, fifth 
with 38.275, including a 9.775 on the bars. 
</P>
<P>
	The Americans had few mistakes, although Vanessa Atler performed  
a wobbly balance beam routine. But they didn't come up with the 
extra points needed to win a medal. 
</P>
<P>
	Elise Ray led the U.S. team with 38.187, eighth best among  
individuals, and national champion Kristen Maloney stood 14th with 
37.848. Ray's best scores were 9.725's on the bars and the floor 
exercises. 
</P>
<P>
	The teams in the final were the top six from qualifying rounds  
earlier in the meet. Atler had saved the Americans a place in the 
finals with a 9.762 in the team's final routine, in the floor 
exercises. 
</P>
<P>
	Consistency and depth were the keys to the Chinese men's  
victory. 
</P>
<P>
	Top scorer for China was Huang Xu, with 57.049. But with the  
exception of Lu Yufu's high-bar fumble, the Chinese had no major 
mistakes. Lu still finished eighth, with 56.823. 
</P>
<P>
	The Chinese men just kept piling up points while their rivals  
struggled. The Russians started poorly on the rings, but captured 
the silver with a strong final round on the pommel horse, where 
Alexei Nemov scored 9.750, Nikolay Krukov 9.737 and Alexei 
Bondarenko 9.725. 
</P>
<P>
	They will have a chance to defend their 1997 medals when  
individual competition starts Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	American Blaine Wilson stood ninth with 56.798, but his  
teammates suffered costly problems in the floor exercises. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
