<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Report: U.S. Runs $1B Budget Surplus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Congressional Budget Office estimated  
today that excluding Social Security, the government ran a $1 
billion surplus for the fiscal year just ended, the first time that 
has happened in four decades. 
</P>
<P>
	If the projection holds up -- and final figures should be  
available later this month -- the development could have an 
important political impact on the fight between President Clinton 
and congressional Republicans over the new year's spending bills. 
</P>
<P>
	Both sides have been insisting they will not tap into Social  
Security surpluses to pay for the spending bills, which would 
reverse what has been standard procedure for decades. Many 
analysts, plus many lawmakers speaking privately, believe that a 
paucity of other politically feasible savings make it likely Social 
Security money will again be spent. 
</P>
<P>
	But since the new estimates show they did not spend any Social  
Security funds in fiscal 1999, it could be politically harder for 
them to backtrack in fiscal 2000 and resume spending some of the 
pension system's surpluses. 
</P>
<P>
	Spending some of Social Security's surpluses has no effect on  
the program's benefits, since the system converts its cash 
surpluses into Treasury bills before the Treasury Department uses 
the cash for spending, reducing the national debt or other 
purposes. But in a bid to cast themselves as protecting the popular 
pension program, politicians have promised to not touch the 
surpluses. 
</P>
<P>
	The budget office, Congress' nonpartisan, official fiscal  
scorekeeper, cautioned that the actual surplus could differ by $1 
billion to $3 billion. But if there was a non-Social Security 
surplus last year, it would be the first since fiscal 1960, when 
that portion of the budget ran a $510 million surplus. 
</P>
<P>
	Including Social Security, the budget office projected a $125  
billion overall federal surplus for fiscal 1999, which ended on 
Sept. 30. That is more than $55 billion above the 1998 surplus, 
marking the first time since 1956 and 1957 that the government ran 
two consecutive surpluses. 
</P>
<P>
	Last month, the White House Office of Management and Budget  
estimated that the overall 1999 surplus would be at least $115 
billion. But the office declined to say what it believed the 
non-Social Security surplus would be. 
</P>
<P>
	In July, the Congressional Budget Office projected a 1999  
surplus of $120 billion. The new forecast, based on data from 
Treasury, was higher largely because of bigger than expected 
corporate tax payments. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
