<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> WHO To Study Tobacco Cos.' Clout </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	GENEVA -- The health agency of the United Nations said today it  
is asking independent experts to investigate new evidence that the 
tobacco industry tried to influence and undermine U.N. efforts to 
control tobacco use. 
</P>
<P>
	The World Health Organization said newly available documents  
point to a ``systematic and global effort'' dating back at least 20 
years by tobacco companies to divert attention from the health 
risks of smoking. 
</P>
<P>
	On several occasions, the agency said, experts serving on WHO  
committees were also receiving payments from tobacco companies. 
</P>
<P>
	The evidence comes from some 30 million documents made public  
during a case by the state of Minnesota against the tobacco 
industry, a suit which resulted in the companies paying out a 
combined $6.6 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	``In that information, there are many instances of how  
supposedly independent experts are actually funded by the tobacco 
industry,'' WHO spokesman Gregory Hartl said. 
</P>
<P>
	``There are also indications that front groups for the tobacco  
industry have tried consistently to turn WHO's interests away from 
tobacco into other areas.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In one document from 1988, the agency said, Philip Morris  
International President Geoffrey Bible points to the 
``extraordinary influence'' that WHO has on many governments and 
suggests the company should use its food operations to counter 
negative images about its tobacco operations. 
</P>
<P>
	``We need to think through how we could use our food companies,  
size, technology, and capability with governments by helping them 
with their food problems and give us a more balanced profile with 
the government than we now have against WHO's powerful influence,'' 
Bible said, according to documents quoted by WHO. 
</P>
<P>
	WHO has appointed Swiss scientist Dr. Thomas Zeltner to lead a  
committee of up to four independent experts to review the documents 
and report back. 
</P>
<P>
	``I make this decision in the spirit of full and complete  
transparency, but above all in the service of public health,'' said 
WHO Director-General Gro Harlem Brundtland. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
